/** Etymology data for lemma IDs in chunk 1 */
export const etymologyChunk1: Record<number, string> = {
  "480": "إِفْكٌ and related words stem from the root أ-ف-ك, with the root verb أَفَكَ meaning \"he turned away,\" \"he lied,\" or \"he changed his/its manner of being.\" إِفْكٌ means \"falsehood\" or \"lie,\" encapsulating the act of deviating from the truth. The connection lies in the root’s focus on turning away from the truth, distortion, and the perversion of reality. This implies that إِفْكٌ involves a deliberate effort to twist or corrupt the truth, often with the intent to deceive or harm, highlighting its malicious nature in spreading falsehoods.",
  "481": "إِقامَةٌ and related words stem from the root ق-و-م, with the root verb قامَ meaning \"he stood\" or \"he rose.\" The root conveys ideas of standing upright, establishing, maintaining, and ensuring stability. إِقامَةٌ means \"establishment\" or \"setting up,\" referring to the act of making something stand firmly or upholding it in a stable position. This meaning extends from the physical act of standing to broader notions of maintaining systems, structures, or states in a firm and enduring manner. In certain contexts, it also means \"encampment\" or \"stay,\" emphasizing a stationary phase or period of residence, especially in contrast to movement or travel.",
  "482": "إِكْرَامٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ر-م, with the root verbs كَـرُمَ meaning \"he or it was highly esteemed, valued, precious, or rare,\" and كَرَّمَ meaning \"he honored greatly\" or \"he ennobled.\" إِكْرَامٌ means \"honoring\" or \"the act of bestowing honor,\" emphasizing noble deeds and generosity. The majestic name ذُو ٱلْجَلَالِ وَٱلْإِكْرَامِ combines جَلَالٌ (majesty) and إِكْرَامٌ (honor, generosity), highlighting Allah’s (ﷻ) supreme greatness and boundless generosity. This name reflects the perfect balance of awe-inspiring majesty and divine kindness, reminding believers to recognize Allah’s (ﷻ) greatness, seek His blessings, and reflect gratitude through virtuous actions.",
  "483": "إِكْرَاهٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ر-ه, with the root verb كَـرِهَ meaning \"he disliked\" or \"he hated.\" إِكْرَاهٌ means \"compulsion\" or \"coercion,\" representing the act of forcing someone to act against their will. The term directly reflects the root’s emphasis on aversion, extending it to the external imposition of unwanted actions. It often carries moral and legal implications, distinguishing between actions done willingly and those compelled by external forces.",
  "484": "إِلَافٌ and related words stem from the root أ-ل-ف, with the root verb أَلِفَ meaning \"he became familiar\" or \"he was accustomed.\" إِلَافٌ means \"familiarity\" or \"habitual practice.\" The connection reflects the root’s broader meaning of forming bonds or becoming accustomed to something through repeated interaction. It highlights how familiarity and mutual understanding develop over time, forming connections and establishing trust, whether through repeated actions, agreements, or customs.",
  "485": "The particle إِلَى means \"to,\" \"towards,\" or \"until\" and is used to indicate direction, destination, purpose, or the extent of something. It specifies a point in space or time, marking limits or goals in both literal and abstract contexts. By directing action or intention, إِلَى emphasizes movement, effort, and purpose, highlighting the connection between an action and its endpoint.",
  "486": "إِلٌّ and related words stem from the root أ-ل-ل, which means \"relationship,\" \"kinship,\" \"covenant,\" or \"oath.\" It highlights bonds and obligations between individuals or communities, reflecting loyalty, responsibility, and the sanctity of such ties. The word إِلٌّ can also mean \"good origin,\" indicating noble ancestry or a pure source, or \"an alliance,\" depending on context. In the Qur'an, it stresses honoring relationships and covenants and warns of the consequences of breaking them. This root highlights the sacredness of connections through blood ties, agreements, or allegiance, urging individuals to fulfill their duties and avoid betrayal or disorder.",
  "487": "إِلْحَادٌ and related words stem from the root ل-ح-د, with the root verb لَحَدَ meaning \"he deviated,\" \"he turned aside,\" or \"he inclined away.\" إِلْحَادٌ specifically means \"deviation,\" \"heresy,\" or \"disbelief,\" emphasizing a deliberate departure from truth or righteousness. The root conveys the notion of veering from a straight or correct path, whether physically or metaphorically, such as in misguidance or error. This term highlights the act of straying from or distorting established truths or principles. It reflects the broader concept of inclining away from what is correct and embracing beliefs or actions that deviate from the intended path of truth and guidance.",
  "488": "إِلْحَافٌ and related words stem from the root ل-ح-ف, with the root verb لَحَفَ meaning \"he persisted,\" \"he was importunate,\" or \"he pressed with urgency.\" إِلْحَافٌ specifically denotes \"insistence\" or \"importunity,\" reflecting the act of pressing or asking with persistent urgency. The connection to the root lies in the repetitive or forceful nature of the act, emphasizing behavior that goes beyond ordinary requests to convey a sense of urgency or excessive demand. This meaning highlights the persistence and intensity of an action, aligning with the root’s broader theme of pressing or pursuing something insistently.",
  "489": "إِلْيَاسُ is the name of Prophet Elijah (ﷺ). In ancient Hebrew it combines Eli (my God) and Yah (the Lord), translating to \"The Lord is My God.\" This reflects Prophet Elijah's (ﷺ) central role as a defender of monotheism. He called his people to abandon idol worship and return to Allah (ﷻ), affirming the sovereignty of the one true God. The meaning of his name aligns with his mission of reminding people that their devotion belongs solely to the Creator, as seen in the Qur'anic account where he proclaims Allah (ﷻ) as \"the Best of creators.\"",
  "490": "إِلٰهٌ and related words stem from the root أ-ل-ه, with the root verb أَلِهَ meaning \"he served,\" \"he worshipped,\" or \"he adored.\" إِلٰهٌ means \"god\" or \"deity,\" reflecting an entity worthy of worship and devotion. The root conveys seeking refuge, awe, and turning toward something in need or reverence. This connection highlights not only worship but also the deep attachment and dependence on the divine, emphasizing adoration and the act of seeking guidance or protection from a higher power.",
  "491": "إِمامٌ and related words stem from the root أ-م-م, with the root verb أَمَّ meaning \"he intended,\" \"he aimed at,\" \"he directed his course toward,\" or \"he led.\" إِمامٌ holds multiple meanings, including \"a person whose example is followed, such as a leader or guide,\" \"scripture, book, or written record,\" and \"a manifest road or path.\" The connection across these meanings lies in the root’s emphasis on direction, purpose, and guidance—whether as a person setting an example, a text guiding actions, or a clear path to follow. إِمامٌ represents any source of direction for others to align with and follow.",
  "492": "إِمْرٌ and related words stem from the root أ-م-ر, with the root verb أَمَرَ meaning \"he commanded\" or \"he ordered.\" إِمْرٌ translates to \"foul,\" \"grave,\" or \"terrible,\" referring to something so severe, unusual, or extraordinary that it elicits a notable or distressing effect. This term conveys the gravity of an act, command, or decision that profoundly impacts those involved, evoking awe, shock, or deep concern. The connection to the root highlights the significant weight and authority of the underlying command or act, emphasizing its extraordinary or unsettling nature.",
  "493": "إِمْسَاكٌ and related words stem from the root م-س-ك, with the root verb مَسَكَ meaning \"he held\" or \"he grasped.\" إِمْسَاكٌ means \"withholding,\" \"restraint,\" or \"abstinence.\" The connection lies in the act of holding back or retaining, reflecting the root's fundamental idea of grasping. This term conveys themes of control and limitation, highlighting the power to prevent or withhold, whether in a physical, emotional, or metaphorical sense. In Islamic jurisprudence, it refers to the act of retaining, such as in the context of marriage and divorce, where the term relates to the retention of a spouse during the waiting period.",
  "494": "إِمْلاقٌ and related words stem from the root م-ل-ق, with the root verb مَلَقَ meaning \"to be poor,\" \"to be destitute,\" or \"to lack resources.\" It also carries the sense of \"seeking favor or affection through extreme humility or entreaty,\" reflecting a state of dependency or need. إِمْلاقٌ specifically denotes \"poverty\" or \"extreme destitution,\" emphasizing severe material deprivation. The root dimensions encompass themes of helplessness, reliance, and the act of humbly seeking aid, broadening the understanding of إِمْلاقٌ as a condition not only of lacking material wealth but also of emotional and social vulnerability.",
  "495": "إِنْجِيلُ is the Arabic term for the \"Gospel,\" the scripture revealed to Prophet Yeshua (ﷺ). It is derived from the Aramaic word ܐܘܢܓܠܝܘܢ (Ewangeliyon), meaning \"good news.\" The term signifies the sharing of glad tidings and Allah's (ﷻ) guidance. إِنْجِيلُ refers to the original revelations given to Prophet Yeshua (ﷺ), emphasizing its role as a source of guidance and instruction for his followers.",
  "496": "إِنسٌ and related words stem from the root أ-ن-س, with the root verb أَنَسَ meaning \"he was sociable,\" \"he became familiar,\" or \"he found comfort.\" إِنسٌ translates to \"humankind\" or \"people.\" The connection lies in humanity's innate sociability and need for companionship, emphasizing the root’s focus on familiarity and social bonds. Humans are referred to as إِنسٌ due to their inherent drive for community and comfort in one another's presence, reflecting the central role of relationships in human life.",
  "497": "إِنسانٌ and related words stem from the root أ-ن-س, with the root verb أَنَسَ meaning \"he was sociable,\" \"he became familiar,\" or \"he found comfort.\" إِنسانٌ translates to \"human being.\" The connection lies in humanity's inherent need for companionship and familiarity, where being human signifies more than mere existence—it embodies the pursuit of connection and understanding. This term highlights that the essence of being human is deeply tied to social bonds, emphasizing the importance of family and relationships in shaping identity and fostering emotional well-being.",
  "498": "إِنسِيٌّ and related words stem from the root أ-ن-س, with the root verb أَنَسَ meaning \"he was sociable,\" \"he found comfort,\" or \"he became familiar.\" إِنسِيٌّ means \"human\" or \"of or belonging to humankind.\" The connection lies in describing characteristics or qualities inherently human, reflecting the root’s emphasis on sociability, familiarity, and companionship. This term points to attributes or behaviors that are uniquely human, highlighting the social nature that defines humanity.",
  "499": "إِنْشَاءٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ش-أ, with the root verb نَشَأَ meaning \"he grew up\" or \"he arose.\" إِنْشَاءٌ means \"creation,\" \"establishment,\" or \"bringing into being.\" This term emphasizes the act of initiating or producing something, focusing on the process of origination by a creator. The connection lies in the deliberate action of causing something to arise, directly reflecting the root's themes of growth and emergence. It highlights the creative force behind the beginning of existence or formation.",
  "500": "إِنْفَاقٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ف-ق, with the root verb نَفَقَ meaning \"it expired\" or \"it was depleted,\" and the derived verb أَنْفَقَ meaning \"he spent.\" إِنْفَاقٌ means \"spending\" or \"expenditure.\" The connection lies in the act of disbursing wealth, leading to its reduction, directly relating to the root's meaning. It emphasizes the concept of intentional spending, often in charitable ways, promoting the circulation of wealth for the betterment of society.",
  "501": "إِنًى and related words stem from the root أ-ن-ي, with the root verb أَنَىٰ meaning \"it matured,\" \"it became due,\" or \"it reached its time.\" إِنًى refers to \"the utmost point, reach, or degree,\" \"maturity,\" or \"a full and final state.\" The connection lies in the state of something arriving at its proper time or maturity, embodying the root's emphasis on timing and readiness. This term highlights the importance of patience and natural progression, reminding us that everything has an appointed time for fruition.",
  "502": "The particle إِنَّ affirms or emphasizes the truth and importance of the statement that follows it, translated as \"indeed\" or \"verily.\" This particle strengthens declarations, urging the audience to acknowledge their validity with certainty. By adding weight to the sentence, إِنَّ draws attention to key messages, making it particularly effective in contexts that require affirmation or where the speaker wants to convey a sense of certainty and importance. Its usage often marks critical points in Qur'anic verses or prophetic sayings, emphasizing divine truths or important guidance.",
  "503": "إِيَابٌ and related words stem from the root أ-و-ب, with the root verb آبَ meaning \"he returned\" or \"he came back.\" إِيَابٌ translates as \"return\" or \"the act of returning,\" reflecting the inevitable return of all beings to Allah (ﷻ). This root carries broader meanings of cyclical movement, restoration, and return to an original state, emphasizing both physical and spiritual return to one’s ultimate source. This term highlights the human journey as a temporary departure, destined to conclude with a return to Allah (ﷻ), highlighting life’s transient nature and the certainty of accountability.",
  "504": "إِيتَاءٌ and related words stem from the root أ-ت-ى, with the root verb أَتَى meaning \"he came\" or \"he arrived.\" آتَى means \"he gave\" or \"bestowed,\" while إِيتَاءٌ refers to \"giving\" or \"bestowal.\" The root emphasizes purposeful arrival, which transitions into the act of delivering something to another. In the Qur'an, إِيتَاءٌ is often associated with giving zakat and supporting relatives, highlighting the importance of generosity and maintaining kinship ties in the sight of Allah (ﷻ). Such acts strengthen bonds and bring divine reward, reflecting the root’s focus on meaningful movement and connection.",
  "505": "إِيمانٌ and related words stem from the root أ-م-ن, with the root verb آمَنَ meaning \"he believed\" or \"he had faith.\" إِيمانٌ translates to \"faith,\" \"belief,\" or \"conviction.\" The connection lies in placing one’s trust and confidence in Allah (ﷻ) or in the truths of faith, reflecting the root’s emphasis on trust, security, and assurance. إِيمانٌ embodies not only an inner state of conviction but also a steadfast commitment that brings peace through reliance on something greater than oneself. It highlights the spiritual security and unwavering assurance found in faith and trust in Allah (ﷻ), reinforcing dependability and a sense of moral grounding.",
  "506": "The emphatic particle إِيَّا denotes exclusivity, often translated as \"only\" or \"alone.\" It serves to focus attention solely on the subject. In the Qur'an, it emphasizes exclusivity in worship, particularly in phrases like إِيَّاكَ (as in إِيَّاكَ نَعْبُدُ), highlighting that worship belongs to Allah (ﷻ) alone. While إِيَّا itself is a grammatical construct, it shares a connection with the root verb تَأَيَّى, meaning \"he directed himself\" or \"he aimed,\" emphasizing the act of intentionally directing one’s focus. This connection serves as a reminder for believers to direct their hope, effort, and worship exclusively to Allah (ﷻ).",
  "507": "اؤْتُمِنَ and related words stem from the root أ-م-ن, with the root verb اِئْتَمَنَ meaning \"he entrusted\" or \"he considered trustworthy.\" اؤْتُمِنَ is a passive form, meaning \"he was entrusted\" or \"he was deemed trustworthy.\" The connection lies in the act of receiving trust or being regarded as reliable, reflecting the root’s focus on security, responsibility, and moral reliability. This term emphasizes both the privilege and duty of being trusted, highlighting a deeper ethical commitment to uphold that trust with integrity and loyalty, thereby reinforcing social bonds and personal accountability.",
  "508": "ابْتَدَعُوا and related words stem from the root ب-د-ع, with the root verb بَدَعَ meaning \"he innovated,\" \"he created without precedent,\" or \"he introduced something new.\" ابْتَدَعُوا translates as \"they innovated\" or \"they introduced unprecedented practices.\" This root emphasizes originality and the act of creating something entirely novel. While it highlights the potential for innovation, the Qur'an warns against practices that deviate from Allah’s (ﷻ) guidance, emphasizing how such innovations in matters of faith can lead to unnecessary burdens, misguidance, and spiritual harm.",
  "509": "ابْتَغَىٰ and related words stem from the root ب-غ-ى, with the root verb بَغَىٰ meaning \"he sought, desired, or aimed for something,\" or \"he sought beyond the limits.\" ابْتَغَىٰ intensifies this meaning, emphasizing deliberate and earnest pursuit. It reflects a determined effort to achieve a goal, going beyond mere desire to active striving. The root conveys themes of seeking, ambition, and persistence, highlighting both virtuous and destructive pursuits. In the Qur'an, ابْتَغَىٰ is linked to seeking Allah’s (ﷻ) pleasure as a noble aim but also warns against excessive or unjust desires, such as the pursuit of dominance or power.",
  "510": "ابْتَلَىٰ and related words stem from the root ب-ل-و, with the root verb بَلَا meaning \"he tried, proved, or tested,\" referring to testing in a general sense to reveal the nature of someone or something. ابْتَلَىٰ means \"he subjected to a deliberate and significant trial\" or \"he tested with purpose,\" often involving a more intense or personal challenge. It is used in contexts where the trial is intentional and meaningful, designed to reveal character, test faith, or build resilience. The root also carries the meaning of \"smelting,\" a process that purifies metal through intense heat. Similarly, ابْتَلَىٰ reflects trials that refine a person’s inner qualities, uncover hidden strengths, and prepare them for greater purposes.",
  "511": "اِبْتِغَاءً and related words stem from the root ب-غ-ى, with the root verb بَغَىٰ meaning \"he sought, desired, or aimed for something,\" or \"he sought beyond the limits.\" اِبْتِغَاءً reflects the act of seeking, emphasizing purposeful and sincere effort to attain a goal. The root conveys themes of striving, ambition, and diligence, highlighting the importance of intention and persistence. In the Qur'an, اِبْتِغَاءً is often used to describe striving for meaningful objectives, such as seeking Allah’s (ﷻ) approval or pursuing actions that bring spiritual fulfillment and purpose.",
  "512": "ابْلَعِي and related words stem from the root ب-ل-ع, with the root verb بَلَعَ meaning \"he swallowed.\" ابْلَعِي is the command form, meaning \"swallow!\" and conveys the act of consuming something entirely, leaving nothing behind. The root also carries nuances of covering or engulfing completely, implying an action that is final and all-encompassing. This command encapsulates the notion of taking in or absorbing fully, often without the possibility of release, symbolizing a complete and irreversible act.",
  "513": "ابْنٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ن-ي, with the root verb بَنَى meaning \"he built, framed, or constructed.\" ابْنٌ means \"son\" or \"descendant\" and reflects the idea of a son being integral to building and continuing the family lineage, much like constructing and extending a structure. The term emphasizes ancestry and familial bonds, symbolizing the continuation of a legacy. It also extends to associations beyond lineage, such as ابْنُ السَّبِيلِ (\"traveler\"), ابْنُ الطَّرِيقِ (\"thief\"), and ابْنُ الدُّنْيَا (\"rich man\"), reflecting roles or traits tied to identity. This connection highlights the broader theme of building—literal or metaphorical—through relationships, roles, and contributions to family or society.",
  "514": "ابْنَةٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ن-ي, with the root verb بَنَى meaning \"he built, framed, or constructed.\" ابْنَةٌ refers to \"a daughter,\" highlighting the idea of building and establishing a family, where the daughter is an essential part of lineage and heritage. Synonymous with بِنْتٌ, the word ابْنَةٌ is more commonly found in classical Arabic texts and poetry as a variant form. Its additional syllable enhances its suitability for poetic rhythm and meter, making it favored in such contexts. It often appears with suffixes, such as ابْنَتُكَ (\"your daughter\") or ابْنَتُهُمْ (\"their daughter\"), emphasizing relational connections and possession.",
  "515": "ابْيَضَّتْ and related words stem from the root ب-ي-ض, with the root verb بَاضَ meaning \"he surpassed him in whiteness.\" ابْيَضَّتْ means \"it became white,\" describing a physical transformation toward lightness or the absence of color. The root conveys ideas of brightness and illumination, often associated with whiteness as a symbol of purity, renewal, or spiritual clarity. When describing faces, ابْيَضَّتْ signifies joy, honor, and cheerfulness. Conversely, the expression ابْيَضَّتْ عَيْنَاهُ (\"his eyes became white\") refers to loss of sight due to intense grief or prolonged weeping, as though sorrow drained the eyes of their vitality, leaving them opaque and devoid of light.",
  "516": "اتَّبَعَ and related words stem from the root ت-ب-ع, with the root verb تَبِعَ meaning \"he followed.\" اتَّبَعَ is an intensified form meaning \"he followed closely\" or \"he adhered firmly,\" suggesting a deep commitment to following guidance or instruction. While often positive, it can also indicate adherence to misguided paths. The broader root meanings related to continuity and discipline imply an active, intentional following that manifests in actions and choices, representing more than mere physical following.",
  "517": "اتَّخَذَ and related words stem from the root أ-خ-ذ, with the root verb أَخَذَ meaning \"he took,\" \"seized,\" or \"grasped.\" اتَّخَذَ means \"he took for himself,\" \"he adopted,\" or \"he took as.\" The connection lies in the reflexive act of taking or adopting something as one's own, emphasizing deliberate choice and personal agency. اتَّخَذَ often refers to adopting beliefs, taking allies, or making something into an object of devotion. In the Qur'an, it is frequently used to highlight the wrongful act of taking false deities or idols besides Allah (ﷻ), highlighting the importance of sincere monotheism and conscious decision-making.",
  "518": "اتَّسَقَ and related words stem from the root و-س-ق, with the root verb وَسَقَ meaning \"he gathered,\" \"he collected,\" or \"he bound together.\" اتَّسَقَ means \"it became full,\" \"it was completed,\" or \"it attained fullness.\" Often used to describe the moon reaching its full phase, the connection to the root lies in the idea of gathering together until completion. This reflects the culmination of elements coming together harmoniously, emphasizing the root's concept of collecting and unifying.",
  "519": "اتَّقَىٰ and related words stem from the root و-ق-ي, with the root verb وَقَىٰ meaning \"he guarded\" or \"he preserved.\" اتَّقَىٰ means \"he guarded himself\" or \"he was God-conscious,\" driven by both love and fear of Allah (ﷻ). The connection lies in self-protection through God-consciousness, actively avoiding sin and harm. This reflects the root's emphasis on safeguarding oneself spiritually and morally, where mindfulness and reverence of Allah (ﷻ) prevent moral failings and guide one to actions pleasing to Him.",
  "520": "اتِّبَاعٌ and related words stem from the root ت-ب-ع, with the root verb تَبِعَ meaning \"he followed.\" اتِّبَاعٌ means \"following,\" denoting the act of following something, whether an action, idea, or guidance. It can represent both physical and metaphorical adherence, such as following a path, responding to a command, or pursuing truth. The broader implications of تَبِعَ around continuity and purpose suggest that اتِّبَاعٌ emphasizes deliberate pursuit, often indicating a sustained, thoughtful approach to following or completing what has been initiated.",
  "521": "اتِّخاذٌ and related words stem from the root أ-خ-ذ, with the root verb أَخَذَ meaning \"he took,\" and اتَّخَذَ meaning \"he adopted,\" or \"he took as.\" اتِّخاذٌ means \"adoption,\" \"taking for oneself,\" or \"making into.\" The connection lies in the process or act of adopting or accepting something as one's own, reflecting the root's concept of taking. اتِّخاذٌ emphasizes the deliberation involved in such decisions, whether adopting beliefs, practices, or associations. In a moral context, it highlights the significance of intentional choices and their impact on one's faith and actions.",
  "522": "اثَّاقَلْتُمْ and related words stem from the root ث-ق-ل, with the root verb ثَقُلَ meaning \"it was heavy, weighty, burdensome.\" اثَّاقَلْتُمْ means \"you became heavy, slow, or sluggish, inclining to the earth or ground.\" It reflects the act of making oneself heavy, implying hesitation, reluctance, or an unwillingness to move forward. This word metaphorically applies the root’s sense of heaviness to describe a lack of motivation, as though burdened by inertia or attachment to worldly comforts.",
  "523": "اثْبُتُوا and related words stem from the root ث-ب-ت, with the root verb ثَبَتَ meaning \"he continued,\" \"endured,\" or \"remained firm and steadfast.\" اثْبُتُوا, in command form, instructs to \"be steadfast\" or \"stand firm.\" The root conveys that steadfastness and related words embody a sense of enduring through hardship, maintaining resilience and stability despite challenges. This emphasizes an enduring state of inner strength and unwavering commitment, suggesting that true firmness arises from a foundation of patience and resilience.",
  "524": "اثْنَتَيْنِ and related words stem from the root ث-ن-ي, with the root verb ثَنَىٰ meaning \"he doubled\" or \"he folded.\" اثْنَتَيْنِ is the dual feminine form meaning \"two.\" It signifies two items or units in the feminine, directly connected to the root's sense of duplication or pairing.",
  "525": "اثْنَيْنِ and related words stem from the root ث-ن-ي, with the root verb ثَنَىٰ meaning \"he doubled\" or \"he folded.\" اثْنَيْنِ is the masculine dual form meaning \"two.\" It represents two items or units in the masculine, maintaining the root's meaning of duplication.",
  "526": "اجْتَبَىٰ and related words stem from the root ج-ب-ي, with the root verb جَبَىٰ meaning \"he collected\" or \"he appropriated a thing exclusively to himself.\" اجْتَبَىٰ specifically means \"He chose\" or \"He selected specially,\" emphasizing an act of deliberate and exclusive selection by Allah (ﷻ). This verb conveys the process of gathering and choosing with divine precision, focusing on what is most valuable and fitting. The root embodies concepts of collection, exclusivity, and special selection, reflecting Allah’s (ﷻ) supreme authority and wisdom in selecting for a higher purpose. اجْتَبَىٰ captures the act of collection elevated to a profound and purposeful divine choice.",
  "527": "اجْتَرَحُوا and related words stem from the root ج-ر-ح, with the root verb جَرَحَ meaning \"he wounded\" or \"he acquired or earned.\" اجْتَرَحُوا means \"they committed\" or \"they earned (evil deeds),\" emphasizing the act of acquiring actions that leave a figurative mark, much like a wound. The root connects the concept of wounding to the consequences of deeds, suggesting that actions—especially evil ones—can scar an individual spiritually or morally, much as wounds leave lasting marks on the body.",
  "528": "اجْتَمَعُوا and related words stem from the root ج-م-ع, with the root verb جَمَعَ meaning \"he gathered\" or \"he collected,\" emphasizing an external action of assembling separate parts into a whole. The root conveys intentionality, organization, and unity. In contrast, اجْتَمَعَ means \"it became collected or brought together,\" reflecting a mutual or internal state of being united. اجْتَمَعُوا specifically means \"they gathered\" or \"they assembled,\" highlighting the voluntary and collective action of individuals uniting. The connection lies in purposeful assembly, with جَمَعَ focusing on external action and اجْتَمَعُوا on mutual participation.",
  "529": "اجْتَنَبُوا and related words stem from the root ج-ن-ب, with the root verb جَنَبَ meaning \"he placed at a distance, sent away, or turned aside.\" اجتنبَ means \"he kept away\" or \"he avoided,\" often implying a deliberate and purposeful withdrawal. اجْتَنَبُوا means \"they avoided\" or \"they shunned,\" highlighting a conscious effort to create distance. The root conveys the concept of separation or distancing, whether physical or metaphorical, to safeguard oneself. The connection reflects an intentional act of avoiding harm or sin, emphasizing self-discipline, moral responsibility, and awareness of consequences.",
  "530": "اجْتُثَّتْ and related words stem from the root ج-ث-ث, with the root verb جَثَّ meaning \"he cut it off\" or \"he uprooted or eradicated.\" اجْتُثَّتْ is a passive form meaning \"it was uprooted\" or \"eradicated,\" indicating a complete removal from its foundation. The broader root concepts emphasize the idea of severance and total elimination, often leaving no trace. This connection reinforces the imagery of thorough destruction or eradication, whether physical or metaphorical, capturing the intensity and finality inherent in the root.",
  "531": "اجْلِدُوا and related words stem from the root ج-ل-د, with the root verb جَلَدَ meaning \"he whipped,\" in response to a crime, as well as \"he compelled.\" اجْلِدُوا means \"flog\" or \"whip,\" referring to the act of administering physical punishment. In the Qur'an and Sunnah, this punishment is prescribed by Allah (ﷻ) for certain grave crimes, such as fornication or adultery and false accusations of these acts, and is carried out only when strict evidentiary conditions are met. The root conveys themes of strength and endurance, reflecting the gravity and seriousness of this punishment as part of divine justice, intended to maintain moral and social order.",
  "532": "اجْنُبْ and related words stem from the root ج-ن-ب, with the root verb جَنَبَ meaning \"he placed at a distance, sent away, or turned aside.\" اجْنُبْ is a command meaning \"avoid!\" or \"keep away!\" It instructs someone to distance themselves from something harmful or inappropriate. The root conveys the idea of creating physical or metaphorical distance, emphasizing deliberate separation or avoidance. The connection reflects an intentional act of turning away, highlighting themes of caution, self-discipline, and moral awareness in steering clear of harm or misguidance.",
  "533": "احْتَرَقَتْ and related words stem from the root ح-ر-ق, with the root verb حَرَقَ meaning \"he burned\" or \"he scorched.\" احْتَرَقَتْ means \"it was burned\" or \"it burned.\" The connection is direct, involving the act of burning or being consumed by fire, reflecting the root's core sense of combustion and destruction by heat.",
  "534": "احْتَمَلَ and related words stem from the root ح-م-ل, with the root verb حَمَلَ meaning \"he carried\" or \"he bore.\" From this comes حَمَّلَ, meaning \"he imposed a burden,\" and تَحَمَّلَ, meaning \"he took upon himself\" or \"he assumed responsibility.\" احْتَمَلَ means \"he sustained\" or \"he endured,\" signifying the act of willingly accepting and bearing a burden, whether physical, emotional, or moral. The connection lies in the transition from carrying something physically to assuming responsibility intentionally, leading to endurance in the face of challenges. This highlights the root’s broader theme of effort, perseverance, and responsibility.",
  "535": "اخْتَارَ and related words stem from the root خ-ي-ر, with the root verb خَارَ meaning \"he chose or preferred\" or \"he sought what was best or most beneficial.\" اخْتَارَ means \"he selected\" or \"he deliberately made a choice,\" an intensified form of خَارَ, emphasizing careful and intentional selection. The root revolves around goodness, preference, and choice, conveying the act of seeking what is most beneficial or superior. The connection highlights the deliberate nature of choosing, where decisions are guided by wisdom, value, or purpose rather than mere chance.",
  "536": "اِخْتَصَمُوا and related words stem from the root خ-ص-م, with the root verb خَصَمَ meaning \"he disputed in a valid or sound manner.\" اِخْتَصَمُوا means \"they disputed with each other.\" The root conveys contention, dispute, and litigation, often involving sharpness or keenness in argument. The connection lies in reciprocal contention, where opposing parties engage in argumentation or legal proceedings, each presenting their case. This reflects the dynamics of conflict, the assertion of claims, and the pursuit of justice in resolving disputes.",
  "537": "اِخْتَلَطَ and related words stem from the root خ-ل-ط, with the root verb خَلَطَ meaning \"he mixed\" or \"he blended.\" اِخْتَلَطَ means \"it became mixed\" or \"it became blended together,\" emphasizing the merging of different elements into a single entity. The root conveys mixing, blending, and intermingling, whether in a structured or disordered manner. The connection lies in how mixing can create unity or confusion, depending on the elements combined, highlighting both the integration of different parts and the potential loss of clarity or distinction.",
  "538": "اِخْتَلَفَ and related words stem from the root خ-ل-ف, with the root verb خَلَفَ meaning \"he succeeded\" or \"he came after.\" The root conveys succession, substitution, and contrast, where one thing follows another or diverges from what preceded it. اِخْتَلَفَ means \"he differed\" or \"he disagreed,\" emphasizing divergence, variation, and opposing viewpoints. This highlights the inevitability of differences in perspectives, paths, and choices, reflecting how contrast and disagreement naturally arise from change, succession, and the varying circumstances that shape decisions and outcomes.",
  "539": "اِخْتِلَافٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ل-ف, with the root verb خَلَفَ meaning \"he succeeded\" or \"he came after.\" اِخْتِلَافٌ means \"alternation,\" \"diversity,\" or \"contradiction,\" emphasizing the natural variations that emerge over time or between entities. The root conveys succession, replacement, and difference, where what follows may align with or diverge from what came before. اِخْتِلَافٌ highlights the depth of contrast and variety, reflecting the dynamic interplay between change and continuity, whether in creation, thought, or human interactions.",
  "540": "اِخْتِلَاقٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ل-ق, with the root verb خَلَقَ meaning \"he created,\" \"he shaped,\" or \"he formed.\" The root conveys the act of bringing something into existence, giving it form, or shaping it according to a specific design or disposition. It also extends to the idea of something becoming worn out or deteriorating over time. اِخْتِلَاقٌ means \"fabrication\" or \"invention,\" specifically referring to the act of falsely creating or fabricating something, such as lies or deceptions. This reflects the contrast between true creation, which is purposeful and real, and fabrication, which is artificial and deceptive, emphasizing the distinction between genuine existence and falsehood.",
  "541": "اخْسَئُوا and related words stem from the root خ-س-أ, with the root verb خَسَأَ meaning \"he was abased or despised.\" اخْسَئُوا translates as \"be despised!\" or \"get away!\" and is used as a forceful command expressing disdain and dismissal. The root conveys themes of rejection, humiliation, and the act of being cast out or degraded. The connection lies in the harsh nature of the command, which signifies not just physical expulsion but also moral or social disgrace. It is a term that emphasizes the severity of dismissal, highlighting the rejection of those who have brought shame, acted in defiance, or earned contempt through their actions.",
  "542": "اِخْفِضْ and related words stem from the root خ-ف-ض, with the verb خَفَضَ meaning \"he lowered.\" اِخْفِضْ means \"lower,\" conveying humility, mercy, or restraint, as in lowering one's wings in compassion. The root relates to lowering, bringing down, or reducing in position, status, or intensity. It encompasses humbling individuals, inducing calmness, or lessening force. الْخَافِضُ, one of Allah’s (ﷻ) perfect names, means \"The Abaser\" or \"The One Who Lowers,\" highlighting His power to humble the arrogant and enact justice. The root emphasizes humility, compassion, and submission, reminding us to extend kindness while recognizing Allah’s (ﷻ) supreme authority.",
  "543": "اِخْلَعْ and related words stem from the root خ-ل-ع, with the root verb خَلَعَ meaning \"he took off\" or \"he removed.\" اِخْلَعْ means \"remove\" or \"take off,\" emphasizing the deliberate act of shedding, discarding, or separating oneself from something. The root conveys removal, separation, and displacement, often signifying a decisive break from what was once attached. This can symbolize letting go of burdens, abandoning negative traits, or even the physical act of removing a garment or object, highlighting the power of detachment in both material and abstract forms.",
  "544": "اِدَّارَأَ and related words stem from the root د-ر-أ, with the root verb دَرَأَ meaning \"he pushed away or repelled\" or \"he averted or warded off.\" اِدَّارَأَ means \"he disputed with another\" or \"he contended with someone else,\" emphasizing an act of opposition or conflict. The root revolves around repelling, preventing, resisting, and contention, conveying both warding off harm and the emergence or creation of something. Just as repelling involves forceful resistance, this word reflects the back-and-forth nature of disputes, where opposing sides push against each other in an attempt to assert dominance or avoid blame.",
  "545": "اِدَّارَكَ and related words stem from the root د-ر-ك, with the root verb دَرَكَ meaning \"it reached or attained\" or \"it overtook or caught up with.\" أَدْرَكَ means \"he fully reached\" or \"he fully overtook,\" while اِدَّارَكَ means \"he caught up with, overtook, or reached (something or someone) after delay,\" implying an accumulation or passage of time before attainment. The root revolves around reaching, comprehension, and consequences, conveying both physical arrival and intellectual realization. Just as something delayed eventually reaches its endpoint, this word reflects the idea of things unfolding gradually until their inevitable completion, whether in pursuit, realization, or the full impact of events.",
  "546": "اِدَّكَرَ and related words stem from the root ذ-ك-ر, with the root verb ذَكَرَ meaning \"he remembered\" or \"he mentioned.\" اِدَّكَرَ means \"he vividly remembered\" or \"he took heed,\" indicating a conscious act of recalling or being mindful. The connection emphasizes an active and deliberate remembrance, reflecting the root's focus on memory and mention.",
  "547": "ارْتَابُوا and related words stem from the root ر-ي-ب, with the root verb رَابَ meaning \"he doubted\" or \"he suspected.\" ارْتَابُوا means \"they doubted\" or \"they became suspicious.\" The connection lies in internalizing uncertainty, reflecting the root’s focus on skepticism. This term emphasizes the internal state of doubt that disrupts mental clarity, highlighting how doubt can cloud one's perception and decision-making, especially in matters requiring trust or certainty.",
  "548": "اِرْتَدَّ and related words stem from the root ر-د-د, with the root verb رَدَّ meaning \"he returned,\" \"he repelled,\" or \"he sent back.\" اِرْتَدَّ means \"he returned,\" \"he reverted,\" or \"he turned back.\" The connection reflects the action of returning or reverting to a previous state or place, embodying the root's essence of returning. It can also imply a spiritual or moral regression, highlighting the significance of steadfastness in one's beliefs and actions.",
  "549": "ارْتَضَى and related words stem from the root ر-ض-و, with the root verb رَضِيَ meaning \"he was pleased\" or \"he was content.\" ارْتَضَى means \"he chose with approval\" or \"he was well-pleased.\" The connection lies in the act of selecting something because it brings satisfaction or contentment, expanding upon the root's focus on pleasure and acceptance. This term emphasizes the deliberate choice rooted in contentment and approval, reflecting a deeper level of satisfaction with the selection made.",
  "550": "ارْتَقِبْ and related words stem from the root ر-ق-ب, with the root verb رَقَبَ meaning \"he watched\" or \"he observed.\" ارْتَقِبْ means \"watch!\" or \"wait!\" The connection lies in the command to be vigilant or to anticipate, embodying the root's emphasis on observation. This term encourages attentiveness and patience, urging one to remain alert to forthcoming events.",
  "551": "ازَّيَّنَتْ and related words stem from the root ز-ي-ن, with the root verb زَانَ meaning \"he adorned\" or \"he beautified.\" ازَّيَّنَتْ means \"it adorned itself\" or \"it became beautified,\" emphasizing a reflexive process where beautification occurs naturally or intrinsically. The root conveys themes of enhancement, embellishment, and attraction, reflecting the transformation that occurs when something becomes more appealing or attractive. ازَّيَّنَتْ highlights the natural adornment of the earth, such as when it flourishes with vegetation after rain, symbolizing renewal, growth, and the inherent beauty of creation.",
  "552": "ازْدَادُوا and related words stem from the root ز-ي-د, with the root verb زَادَ meaning \"he increased,\" \"he grew,\" or \"he added.\" ازْدَادُوا means \"they increased\" or \"they grew more,\" emphasizing an active and deliberate process of growth or augmentation. The form ازْدَادَ suggests a reflexive or intensified increase, often implying a continuous or compounding growth over time. The root conveys themes of progression, enhancement, and multiplication, highlighting a purposeful striving toward greater abundance or capability. The connection reflects the dynamic and self-driven aspect of increase, often tied to effort, perseverance, or divine facilitation.",
  "553": "اِزْدُجِرَ and related words stem from the root ز-ج-ر, with the verb زَجَرَ meaning \"he rebuked,\" \"he restrained,\" or \"he drove back.\" اِزْدُجِرَ is the passive form, meaning \"he was rebuked\" or \"he was forcefully restrained.\" The root conveys the idea of strong reprimand, driving something back, or imposing restraint. The connection lies in the forceful turning back or admonishment of an individual or entity, emphasizing the severity and authority in the act. This highlights a decisive act of control or discipline, reflecting the root’s core concept of enforcing restraint and imposing correction.",
  "554": "اِسْتَأْجَرَ and related words stem from the root أ-ج-ر, with the root verb أَجَرَ meaning \"he rewarded\" or \"he hired.\" اِسْتَأْجَرَ means \"he hired\" or \"he rented,\" specifically conveying the sense of seeking to hire someone or rent something. The connection lies in the action of contracting services or rental, reflecting the root’s focus on hiring, reward, and compensation. In the Qur'an, this term appears in stories where individuals hire others for work, highlighting principles of fair dealings, clear contractual agreements, and the importance of fulfilling one’s obligations.",
  "555": "اسْتَأْذَنَ and related words stem from the root أ-ذ-ن, with the root verb أَذِنَ meaning \"he listened\" or \"he permitted.\" اسْتَأْذَنَ means \"he sought permission.\" The connection involves actively requesting consent, reflecting the root's emphasis on listening and mutual respect. This form highlights humility and proper etiquette in seeking approval before proceeding with an action, emphasizing the value of respect and acknowledgment of authority.",
  "556": "اسْتَبَقَ and related words stem from the root س-ب-ق, with the root verb سَبَقَ meaning \"he preceded\" or \"he surpassed.\" اسْتَبَقَ means \"they raced each other\" or \"they strove to outdo one another.\" The connection lies in the mutual effort to surpass others, emphasizing competition and eagerness to excel. This reflects the root's concept of going ahead or being foremost, highlighting the dynamic nature of striving to be first or best in any endeavor.",
  "557": "اسْتَجَابَ and related words stem from the root ج-و-ب, with the root verb جَابَ meaning \"he cut through\" or \"he pierced.\" The root broadly conveys meanings of cutting, piercing, breaking through, or creating a path. أَجَابَ means \"he answered,\" referring to a straightforward or neutral response focused on the act of replying. In contrast, اسْتَجَابَ means \"he responded\" or \"he complied,\" emphasizing a deliberate and willing acceptance or fulfillment of a request. The nuance lies in اسْتَجَابَ reflecting a complete and purposeful response, characterized by attentiveness and fulfilling a call or duty. When referring to Allah (ﷻ), it signifies the perfect and complete fulfillment of needs with wisdom and care.",
  "558": "اسْتَجَارَ and related words stem from the root ج-و-ر, with the root verb جَارَ meaning \"he declined or deviated from the right course\" and جاوَرَ meaning \"he became a neighbor.\" أَجَارَ means \"he protected\" or \"he granted refuge.\" The root conveys meanings of deviation, injustice, proximity, and granting protection. اسْتَجَارَ means \"he sought protection\" or \"he asked for refuge,\" reflecting an act of seeking safety or assistance, often from a protector or neighbor. The root illustrates the human tendency to deviate while embodying the inclination to provide support and seek refuge. It emphasizes interconnectedness and reliance, not just within families but extending to neighbors and community.",
  "559": "اسْتَحَبُّوا and related words stem from the root ح-ب-ب, with the root verb حَبَّ meaning \"he was loved,\" and أَحَبَّ meaning \"he loved.\" اسْتَحَبُّوا means \"they preferred,\" emphasizing the act of choosing something out of affection or inclination. The root conveys themes of love, desirability, and attachment, which naturally extend to preference and prioritization. The connection lies in the idea that preference and related words stem from an inner affection or love for one option over another, highlighting the human tendency to gravitate toward what is most beloved or appealing.",
  "560": "اسْتَحَقَّ and related words stem from the root ح-ق-ق, with the root verb حَقَّ meaning \"it was true,\" \"it became established,\" or \"it was necessitated.\" اسْتَحَقَّ means \"he deserved\" or \"he was entitled to.\" The connection lies in actively seeking or obtaining what is rightfully due, embodying the root’s focus on truth, obligation, and certainty. This term reflects the pursuit of justice and the affirmation of legitimate rights, emphasizing the moral imperative to acknowledge and fulfill what is deserved.",
  "561": "اسْتَحْوَذَ and related words stem from the root ح-و-ذ, with the root verb حَاذَ meaning \"he surpassed or exceled over others\" or \"he was quick or swift.\" اسْتَحْوَذَ means \"he took full control\" or \"he dominated.\" The root conveys the idea of gaining possession, excelling, or moving quickly, often implying a competitive aspect or asserting authority. This term highlights a total and often overwhelming mastery, connecting to ideas of power and influence, whether physical, psychological, or strategic.",
  "562": "اِسْتَخَفَّ and related words stem from the root خ-ف-ف, with the root verb خَفَّ meaning \"he or it was light,\" referring to weight, movement, or manner. خَفَّفَ means \"he lightened,\" and تَخَفَّفَ means \"he lightened his load or burden.\" اِسْتَخَفَّ means \"he considered light or insignificant\" or \"he underestimated,\" implying disregard or belittlement. The root conveys lightness in weight, movement, and demeanor. The connection lies in how considering something insignificant mirrors the act of making it light, whether in seriousness or importance, highlighting a shift in perception.",
  "563": "اسْتَخْرَجَ and related words stem from the root خ-ر-ج, with the root verb خَرَجَ meaning \"he went out\" or \"he exited.\" اسْتَخْرَجَ means \"he sought to bring out\" or \"he extracted.\" The connection lies in the deliberate effort to uncover, retrieve, or extract something hidden or concealed. Unlike simple emergence, اسْتَخْرَجَ emphasizes an intentional process of drawing something out, reinforcing the root’s theme of bringing forth, whether through discovery, retrieval, or forced extraction.",
  "564": "اِسْتَخْلَفَ and related words stem from the root خ-ل-ف, with the root verb خَلَفَ meaning \"he succeeded\" or \"he came after.\" The root conveys succession, substitution, and contrast, where one thing takes the place of another, either in position, time, or responsibility. اِسْتَخْلَفَ means \"he appointed as successor\" or \"he made vicegerent,\" emphasizing the act of entrusting leadership or stewardship. This highlights the profound role of humanity as stewards on Earth, entrusted by Allah (ﷻ) to uphold justice and wisdom. This responsibility reflects both privilege and accountability, urging one to act with foresight and fairness.",
  "565": "اسْتَرَقَ and related words stem from the root س-ر-ق, with the root verb سَرَقَ meaning \"he stole.\" اسْتَرَقَ means \"he sought to steal stealthily\" or \"he eavesdropped.\" The connection lies in the enhanced form of the verb, indicating an attempt to acquire something secretly, particularly information. This reflects the root's emphasis on theft, extending it to the clandestine act of listening or spying.",
  "566": "اسْتَرْهَبُوا and related words stem from the root ر-ه-ب, with the root verb رَهِبَ meaning \"he feared\" or \"he was in awe.\" اسْتَرْهَبَ means \"he sought to frighten\" or \"he intimidated.\" اسْتَرْهَبُوا means \"they sought to frighten\" or \"they intimidated.\" The connection lies in the act of instilling fear in others, directly relating to the root's meaning. In the Qur'an, it reflects attempts by certain individuals to intimidate others from pursuing the truth.",
  "567": "اسْتَزَلَّ and related words stem from the root ز-ل-ل, with the root verb زَلَّ meaning \"he slipped\" or \"he erred.\" اسْتَزَلَّ means \"he sought to cause to slip\" or \"he attempted to lead astray.\" The root also includes themes of instability, faltering, and vulnerability to missteps. The connection lies in the intentional effort to make someone stumble or deviate, reflecting the root's focus on causing instability and error. This term highlights calculated attempts to mislead or deceive others, emphasizing the premeditated nature of such actions.",
  "568": "اسْتَسْقَىٰ and related words stem from the root س-ق-ي, with the root verb سَقَىٰ meaning \"he gave to drink.\" اسْتَسْقَىٰ means \"he sought to be given drink\" or \"he requested water.\" The connection lies in the act of seeking water to quench thirst, directly relating to the root's emphasis on providing drink.",
  "569": "اسْتَشْهِدُوا and related words stem from the root ش-ه-د, with the root verb شَهِدَ meaning \"he witnessed.\" اسْتَشْهِدُوا means \"seek witnesses\" or \"call for witnesses.\" The connection lies in the root's concept of witnessing and testifying. اسْتَشْهِدُوا reflects the act of requesting testimony or verification. It emphasizes the importance of witnesses in establishing truth and justice, urging the seeking of credible testimony in matters of importance.",
  "570": "اسْتَضْعَفُوا and related words stem from the root ض-ع-ف, with the root verb ضَعُفَ meaning \"he became weak.\" اسْتَضْعَفُوا means \"they oppressed\" or \"they considered (someone) weak.\" It refers to the act of subjugating others by exploiting their perceived weakness, treating them as inferior, or denying them power. This form conveys the act of deeming or causing someone to be in a state, aligning with the root’s focus on physical, emotional, or social weakness. This word highlights themes of oppression, exploitation, and social injustice, where strength is abused to dominate the vulnerable.",
  "571": "اسْتَطَاعَ and related words stem from the root ط-و-ع, with the root verb طَاعَ meaning \"he obeyed\" or \"he complied willingly.\" اسْتَطَاعَ means \"he was able\" or \"he was capable.\" This form conveys the concept of having the ability or power to do something. The connection to the root lies in the idea that ability arises from one's willingness or readiness to act. It reflects the notion that true capability is linked to one's internal compliance or alignment with purpose.",
  "572": "اسْتَطْعَمَ and related words stem from the root ط-ع-م, with the root verb طَعِمَ meaning \"he tasted\" or \"he ate.\" اسْتَطْعَمَ means \"he asked for food\" or \"he sought to be fed.\" The connection lies in seeking nourishment, directly relating to the root's emphasis on taste and sustenance. This term reflects the state of being in need and requesting help. It highlights the human condition of dependence and the importance of responding to those who seek assistance.",
  "573": "اسْتَعِذْ and related words stem from the root ع-و-ذ, with the root verb عَاذَ meaning \"he sought refuge.\" اسْتَعَاذَ means \"he sought refuge,\" particularly in Allah (ﷻ), while اسْتَعِذْ is the command form meaning \"Seek refuge.\" The connection lies in the act of earnestly seeking protection, reflecting the root's focus on taking shelter. This command highlights the importance of turning to Allah (ﷻ) for protection from evil and harm, reinforcing reliance on Him in facing challenges.",
  "574": "اسْتَعِينُوا and related words stem from the root ع-و-ن, with the root verb عَانَ meaning \"he helped,\" \"he assisted,\" or \"he supported.\" اسْتَعَانَ means \"he sought help,\" and اسْتَعِينُوا means \"seek help\" or \"request assistance.\" This form emphasizes the action of actively asking for support, typically in times of difficulty or need. The connection lies in the root’s emphasis on receiving or offering assistance, highlighting the human need for external aid and the importance of turning to others or to Allah (ﷻ) for support in overcoming challenges. This term emphasizes the value of cooperation and seeking the necessary resources to succeed or endure hardships.",
  "575": "اِسْتَعْجَلَ and related words stem from the root ع-ج-ل, with the root verb عَجِلَ meaning \"he was hasty\" or \"he hurried.\" اِسْتَعْجَلَ means \"he sought to hasten\" or \"he was impatient.\" The connection lies in actively seeking haste or pressing for quick results, reflecting the root's concept of urgency and impatience. It highlights the desire for immediate fulfillment.",
  "576": "اسْتَعْصَمَ and related words stem from the root ع-ص-م, with the root verb عَصَمَ meaning \"he protected\" or \"he held firmly.\" اسْتَعْصَمَ means \"he sought protection\" or \"he held fast seeking refuge.\" The connection lies in actively seeking to hold onto something secure for safety, reflecting the root's emphasis on protection and firmness. This term highlights the act of earnestly striving for preservation or safeguarding oneself from harm by clinging to a source of security.",
  "577": "اسْتَعْلَىٰ and related words stem from the root ع-ل-و, with the root verb عَلا meaning \"he rose\" or \"he ascended.\" اسْتَعْلَىٰ means \"he sought to rise,\" \"he strove to ascend,\" or \"he sought to exalt himself.\" It conveys the act of actively pursuing elevation, whether in position, authority, or dominance. The root’s themes of elevation and striving for superiority are evident, with a dual dimension: it can refer to legitimate efforts to achieve prominence or unjust self-exaltation and arrogance. This highlights the nuanced nature of seeking elevation, where the context determines whether it signifies noble ambition or excessive pride.",
  "578": "اسْتَعْمَرَ and related words stem from the root ع-م-ر, with the root verb عَمَرَ meaning \"he inhabited,\" \"he cultivated,\" or \"he caused to thrive.\" اسْتَعْمَرَ means \"he sought to populate,\" \"he developed,\" or \"he caused to prosper.\" The connection lies in actively seeking to build up and improve the land, reflecting the root's emphasis on habitation and flourishing. This term embodies humanity's role as stewards of the Earth, entrusted by Allah (ﷻ) to develop and maintain it responsibly, promoting growth and prosperity in alignment with divine guidance.",
  "579": "اسْتَغَاثَ and related words stem from the root غ-و-ث, with the root verb غَاثَ meaning \"he aided,\" \"succored,\" or \"relieved.\" اسْتَغَاثَ means \"he sought help,\" \"appealed for aid,\" or \"called for rescue.\" This form reflects the act of seeking assistance in times of distress. The connection lies in actively reaching out for aid, emphasizing the root's concept of providing relief. It highlights themes of vulnerability, reliance on others or on Allah (ﷻ), and the importance of compassion toward those in need.",
  "580": "اسْتَغْشَىٰ and related words stem from the root غ-ش-و, with the root verb غَشِيَ meaning \"he covered,\" \"he enveloped,\" or \"he came over (someone).\" اسْتَغْشَىٰ means \"he covered himself\" or \"he sought to be covered.\" The connection lies in the intentional act of seeking cover or concealment, directly relating to the root's meaning of covering. This term emphasizes the desire for protection or avoidance, possibly from fear or discomfort, highlighting a personal action to seek shelter or obscurity.",
  "581": "اسْتَغْفَرَ and related words stem from the root غ-ف-ر, with the root verb غَفَرَ meaning \"he forgave,\" \"he covered,\" or \"he concealed.\" اسْتَغْفَرَ means \"he sought forgiveness.\" The connection lies in the act of seeking to be forgiven or have sins covered, directly relating to the root's meaning. This term emphasizes the humility and repentance required in asking for Allah's (ﷻ) forgiveness, highlighting the importance of acknowledging one's faults.",
  "582": "اسْتَغْلَظَ and related words stem from the root غ-ل-ظ, with the root verb غَلُظَ meaning \"he was thick,\" \"coarse,\" or \"severe.\" اسْتَغْلَظَ means \"it became thick\" or \"it grew strong.\" This form indicates a transformation towards greater thickness or robustness. The connection lies in the process of seeking or attaining the state described by the root, emphasizing growth and intensification. It reflects the idea of something increasing in density or strength, symbolizing development and fortification.",
  "583": "اسْتَغْنَى and related words stem from the root غ-ن-ي, with the root verb غَنِيَ meaning \"he was rich,\" \"self-sufficient,\" or \"free from want.\" اسْتَغْنَى means \"he deemed himself self-sufficient\" or \"he dispensed with.\" This form reflects the act of seeking independence or considering oneself without need of others. The connection lies in the proactive pursuit of self-sufficiency, emphasizing themes of independence and sometimes arrogance. It highlights the human tendency to rely on oneself, potentially neglecting humility or dependence on Allah (ﷻ).",
  "584": "اسْتَفْتَحُوا and related words stem from the root ف-ت-ح, with the root verb فَتَحَ meaning \"he opened.\" اسْتَفْتَحُوا means \"they sought victory\" or \"they sought an opening,\" emphasizing the act of requesting success or judgment. The connection lies in seeking an \"opening\" or breakthrough from Allah (ﷻ), reflecting the root's concept of opening pathways. It highlights reliance on Allah's (ﷻ) assistance to overcome challenges and achieve triumph.",
  "585": "اِسْتَقامَ and related words stem from the root ق-و-م, with the root verb قامَ meaning \"he stood\" or \"he rose.\" The root conveys ideas of standing upright, rising, and maintaining balance. اِسْتَقامَ means \"he remained upright\" or \"he remained steadfast,\" reflecting an active effort to align with uprightness and stability. It embodies the root’s essence of balance and steadfastness, highlighting the ongoing pursuit of moral and spiritual uprightness. The term emphasizes striving for consistency in righteousness, justice, and adherence to truth in actions and character.",
  "586": "اسْتَقَرَّ and related words stem from the root ق-ر-ر, with the root verb قَرَّ meaning \"he settled,\" \"he remained,\" or \"he became cool.\" اسْتَقَرَّ means \"he settled\" or \"he became stable.\" The connection lies in the action of seeking and achieving a state of settlement or stability, reflecting the root's concept of establishing oneself firmly. This emphasizes the importance of stability, both physically and metaphorically, in one's life and affairs.",
  "587": "اِسْتَكْبَرَ and related words stem from the root ك-ب-ر, with the root verb كَبُرَ meaning \"he became great\" or \"he grew,\" encompassing concepts of greatness and magnitude. اِسْتَكْبَرَ means \"he was arrogant,\" \"he sought to be great,\" or \"he acted proudly,\" emphasizing the pursuit of greatness in a wrongful or excessive manner. The connection highlights the root's focus on magnitude, but in this form, it reflects a deliberate, negative distortion of growth—seeking self-exaltation or superiority at the expense of humility. This verb highlights the dual nature of greatness: when directed toward oneself, it leads to arrogance, but when directed toward Allah (ﷻ), it fosters reverence and submission.",
  "588": "اِسْتَكْثَرَ and related words stem from the root ك-ث-ر, with the root verb كَثُرَ meaning \"it became numerous,\" \"it increased,\" or \"it multiplied.\" اِسْتَكْثَرَ means \"he sought to increase,\" \"he desired abundance,\" or \"he considered (something) much.\" The form introduces the nuance of intent or effort, reflecting the human inclination to seek more or perceive something as plentiful. The connection to the root lies in the concept of pursuing multiplication or abundance, highlighting themes of desire, ambition, and the perception of sufficiency. This form captures both the act of striving for increase and the subjective evaluation of what is considered ample.",
  "589": "اسْتَمَعَ and related words stem from the root س-م-ع, with the root verb سَمِعَ meaning \"he heard\" or \"he listened.\" اسْتَمَعَ means \"he listened attentively\" or \"he sought to hear.\" The added prefix reflects an intentional effort to listen, not just passively hearing but actively seeking out and paying close attention. This deepens the root concept by highlighting the pursuit of understanding through attentive listening, emphasizing mindfulness and engagement in communication.",
  "590": "اِسْتَمْتَعَ and related words stem from the root م-ت-ع, with the root verb مَتَعَ meaning \"he enjoyed,\" \"he benefited,\" or \"he made use of.\" اِسْتَمْتَعَ means \"he sought benefit\" or \"he sought enjoyment,\" emphasizing the act of actively pursuing or deriving pleasure or utility. The connection lies in the conscious effort to experience or maximize that which provides benefit or delight, reflecting the root's concept of utility and satisfaction. It highlights the human tendency to seek out and indulge in sources of enjoyment or advantage, often tied to the transient nature of worldly life.",
  "591": "اسْتَمْسَكَ and related words stem from the root م-س-ك, with the root verb مَسَكَ meaning \"he held,\" and اسْتَمْسَكَ meaning \"he held firmly\" or \"he clung to.\" The connection lies in the intensified act of holding tightly, reflecting the root's core concept of grasping. This emphasizes determination and steadfastness, highlighting the importance of firmly adhering to beliefs or paths. In Islamic teachings, it signifies a strong commitment to faith and principles, embodying the concept of holding fast to the religion and its teachings, regardless of challenges.",
  "592": "اسْتَنصَرَ and related words stem from the root ن-ص-ر, with the root verb نَصَرَ meaning \"he helped.\" اسْتَنصَرَ means \"he sought help\" or \"he asked for assistance,\" emphasizing the act of actively requesting aid in a time of need. The connection lies in seeking the support necessary to overcome challenges, reflecting the root’s focus on help and collaboration. اسْتَنصَرَ highlights the human reliance on external assistance, whether divine or communal, highlighting humility and the recognition of one’s limitations.",
  "593": "اسْتَنْكَفُوا and related words stem from the root ن-ك-ف, with the root verb نَكِفَ meaning \"he was disdainful\" or \"proud.\" اسْتَنْكَفُوا means \"they pridefully refused\" or \"they were too proud to accept.\" The term reflects the action of rejecting something out of arrogance or pride. The connection to the root highlights themes of haughtiness and the refusal to submit or comply due to inflated self-regard. This emphasizes the moral lesson against arrogance and the importance of humility.",
  "594": "اسْتَهْوَتْ and related words stem from the root ه-و-ى, with the root verb هَوَىٰ meaning \"he fell,\" \"he descended,\" or \"he desired passionately.\" اسْتَهْوَتْ means \"she/it enticed\" or \"she/it caused to go astray,\" reflecting the act of alluring someone into following their desires. The connection lies in causing another to metaphorically fall or descend into misguidance, directly relating to the root's focus on inclination and descent. This term emphasizes the danger of being swayed by temptations or external influences, which can divert one from the path of righteousness.",
  "595": "اِسْتَوَىٰ and related words stem from the root س-و-ي, with the root verb سَوَّىٰ meaning \"he made equal,\" \"he balanced,\" or \"he completed.\" اِسْتَوَىٰ means \"he became level,\" \"he ascended,\" \"he established himself,\" or \"he became complete.\" The root encompasses themes of balance, symmetry, and completeness, emphasizing achieving a perfected state or position. اِسْتَوَىٰ in the Qur'an is used to describe Allah's (ﷻ) establishment over the Throne, symbolizing His authority, control, and perfection, reflecting the root's idea of ultimate harmony and completion.",
  "596": "اسْتَوْقَدَ and related words stem from the root و-ق-د, with the root verb وَقَدَ meaning \"it kindled\" or \"it ignited.\" اسْتَوْقَدَ means \"he sought to kindle\" or \"he lit for himself,\" emphasizing an active effort to ignite or produce fire. The connection lies in the root’s focus on the act of starting or sustaining a flame, symbolizing the pursuit of light, warmth, or energy. This term reflects the broader concept of striving to illuminate or sustain something essential, whether literal or metaphorical.",
  "597": "اسْتَيْأَسَ and related words stem from the root ي-أ-س, with the root verb يَئِسَ meaning \"he despaired\" or \"he lost hope.\" اسْتَيْأَسَ means \"he fell into despair\" or \"he became hopeless,\" emphasizing the transition into a state of hopelessness. The root conveys concepts of despair, abandonment, and disconnection from expectations, reflecting the emotional act of giving up all hope for relief or positive outcomes.",
  "598": "اسْتَيْسَرَ and related words stem from the root ي-س-ر, with the root verb يَسَرَ meaning \"it became easy.\" اسْتَيْسَرَ means \"he sought ease\" or \"he found it easy,\" emphasizing either the pursuit of simplicity or the natural attainment of ease in tasks. The root conveys broader concepts of ease, facilitation, simplicity, and accessibility, focusing on the removal of obstacles and the smooth accomplishment of tasks. The connection lies in the root’s focus on enabling manageable outcomes, whether through active seeking or ease naturally unfolding.",
  "599": "اسْتَيْقَنَتْ and related words stem from the root ي-ق-ن, with the root verb يَقِنَ meaning \"he was certain.\" اسْتَيْقَنَتْ means \"she or it became certain\" or \"she or it was convinced,\" emphasizing the deliberate process of realizing and affirming certainty. The root conveys broader concepts of stability, clarity, and firmness, highlighting an unshakable conviction free from doubt. The connection lies in reflecting the journey of attaining firm knowledge and conviction through conscious recognition and understanding, aligned with the root’s focus on clarity and stability in belief.",
  "600": "اُسْتُحْفِظُوا and related words stem from the root ح-ف-ظ, with the root verb حَفِظَ meaning \"he guarded,\" \"he protected,\" or \"he preserved.\" اسْتَحْفَظَ means \"he was made to guard,\" \"he was entrusted with.\" اُسْتُحْفِظُوا is a passive form meaning \"they were entrusted to preserve\" or \"they were charged with guarding.\" This reflects the responsibility given to individuals to protect or uphold something valuable, directly connecting to the root's emphasis on preservation. The term highlights themes of duty, trust, and accountability in safeguarding important matters.",
  "601": "اسْتُهْزِئَ and related words stem from the root ه-ز-أ, with the root verb هَزَأَ meaning \"he mocked,\" \"he ridiculed,\" or \"he scoffed.\" اسْتُهْزِئَ is a passive form meaning \"he was mocked\" or \"he was ridiculed.\" This term embodies the root's concept by indicating that someone has been subjected to scorn or derision. It reflects themes of disrespect and belittlement inherent in the root, highlighting the negative impact of mockery on the individual.",
  "602": "اسْتِبْدَالٌ and related words stem from the root ب-د-ل, with the root verb بَدَلَ meaning \"he exchanged\" or \"he substituted.\" اسْتِبْدَالٌ means \"seeking a substitute\" or \"replacement.\" This term emphasizes the act of actively seeking to exchange one thing for another, reflecting the root’s focus on substitution and transformation. The broader root concept involves replacing something with a perceived alternative, often implying a shift in preference or purpose.",
  "603": "اسْتِحْيَاءٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ي-ي, with the root verb حَيِيَ meaning \"he was shy\" or \"he felt modesty,\" reflecting restraint and humility. حَيَّا means \"he greeted,\" \"he honored or showed regard,\" or \"he acted with consideration.\" From this comes اسْتِحْيَاءٌ, meaning \"shyness\" or \"modesty,\" referring to refraining from an action out of deep shyness, respect, or a sense of dignity. The connection lies in the idea of being conscious of oneself and others, where modesty stems from awareness, honor, and refined conduct, aligning with the root’s themes of humility, regard, and restraint.",
  "604": "اِسْتِعْجالٌ and related words stem from the root ع-ج-ل, with the root verb عَجِلَ meaning \"he was hasty\" or \"he hurried.\" اِسْتِعْجالٌ means \"seeking haste\" or \"impatience.\" The term embodies the act of desiring immediate action, reflecting the root's concept of urgency. It emphasizes a state of impatience and the push for swift fulfillment.",
  "605": "اسْتِغْفارٌ and related words stem from the root غ-ف-ر, with the root verb غَفَرَ meaning \"he forgave,\" \"he covered,\" or \"he concealed.\" اسْتِغْفارٌ means \"seeking forgiveness.\" The connection lies in the ongoing action or process of asking for pardon, directly relating to the root's meaning. This term highlights the continuous need for repentance and turning back to Allah (ﷻ) for mercy.",
  "606": "اِسْتِكْبارٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ب-ر, with the root verb كَبُرَ meaning \"he became great\" or \"he grew.\" اِسْتِكْبارٌ means \"seeking arrogance\" or \"pride.\" It represents the state or act of seeking greatness for oneself in an arrogant manner. The connection lies in the pursuit of greatness that leads to self-exaltation, reflecting the root's concept of magnitude but emphasizing its negative manifestation. It serves as a caution against the moral failing of arrogance, highlighting the importance of humility.",
  "607": "اِسْمٌ and related words stem from the root س-م-و, with the root verb سَمَا meaning \"he was high\" or \"he elevated.\" اِسْمٌ means \"name.\" The connection is found in the idea that a name elevates the one who bears it, distinguishing and raising them in status or recognition. A name carries identity and can confer honor, reflecting the root's concept of elevation and prominence.",
  "608": "اِسْوَدَّتْ and related words stem from the root س-و-د, with the root verb اِسْوَدَّ meaning \"it became black\" or \"it turned dark.\" اِسْوَدَّتْ means \"it darkened\" or \"she became black,\" emphasizing a shift into darkness. The root also includes سَوَّدَ, meaning \"he blackened,\" often signifying disgrace or sorrow, and سَادَ, meaning \"he attained dignity.\" This contrast highlights the moral weight of actions, where honor can turn to disgrace through wrongdoing, as reflected in the Qur'an’s warnings about the consequences of dishonorable deeds.",
  "609": "اشْتَدَّتْ and related words stem from the root ش-د-د, with the root verb شَدَّ meaning \"he tightened\" or \"he strengthened.\" اشْتَدَّتْ means \"it became intense\" or \"it became severe,\" emphasizing an increase in strength or severity. The connection lies in the root's focus on tightening and intensifying, illustrating how situations can escalate in intensity.",
  "610": "اشْتَرَىٰ and related words stem from the root ش-ر-ى, with the root verb شَرَىٰ meaning \"he bought\" or \"he sold.\" اشْتَرَىٰ means \"he purchased\" or \"he acquired.\" The connection lies in the transactional nature of the root, involving exchange and procurement. This form emphasizes acquiring something for oneself. In a spiritual context, it can symbolize the choices individuals make, such as \"purchasing\" misguidance at the expense of guidance.",
  "611": "اشْتَعَلَ and related words stem from the root ش-ع-ل, with the root verb شَعَلَ meaning \"he kindled\" or \"he ignited.\" اشْتَعَلَ means \"it blazed up\" or \"it flared.\" The connection lies in the intensification of a flame or fire, reflecting the root's concept of ignition and burning. Metaphorically, it can represent the onset of passion, emotion, or even aging, as in the graying of hair like a spreading fire.",
  "612": "اشْتَمَلَتْ and related words stem from the root ش-م-ل, with the root verb شَمَلَ meaning \"he encompassed\" or \"he covered.\" اشْتَمَلَتْ means \"she encompassed\" or \"she wrapped herself.\" The connection lies in the root's concept of encompassing or enveloping, with a sense of totality or completeness. اشْتَمَلَتْ conveys the idea of fully covering or including all parts, emphasizing a comprehensive and all-encompassing action. The verb suggests an act of gathering, enveloping, or containing, with a focus on fully encompassing something or someone, often with the connotation of protection, care, or inclusion. This term emphasizes the thoroughness and holistic nature of the action.",
  "613": "اشْتَهَتْ and related words stem from the root ش-ه-و, with the root verb شَهِيَ meaning \"he desired\" or \"he craved.\" اشْتَهَتْ means \"she desired intensely\" or \"she craved.\" The connection lies in the root's concept of strong longing or appetite. اشْتَهَتْ emphasizes a deep personal yearning, reflecting the powerful pull of desires on the human soul. It illustrates how intense cravings can influence actions and decisions.",
  "614": "اشْمَأَزَّتْ and related words stem from the root ش-م-ز, with the root verb اشْمَأَزَّ meaning \"he felt aversion\" or \"he recoiled.\" اشْمَأَزَّتْ means \"she recoiled\" or \"she was filled with aversion.\" The connection lies in the root's concept of intense dislike or repulsion. اشْمَأَزَّتْ vividly describes a strong emotional reaction of turning away due to disgust, emphasizing the depth of the aversion felt.",
  "615": "اصْدَعْ and related words stem from the root ص-د-ع, with the root verb صَدَعَ meaning \"he split,\" \"he cleft,\" or \"he proclaimed openly.\" اصْدَعْ means \"proclaim!\" or \"declare openly!\" The connection lies in the root's concept of splitting or breaking through, metaphorically representing the act of making a clear and public declaration. By commanding اصْدَعْ, it urges one to boldly announce the truth without fear or hesitation. In the Qur'an, it instructs the Prophet Muhammad (ﷺ) to openly convey the message of Islam.",
  "616": "اصْطَادُوا and related words stem from the root ص-ي-د, with the root verb صَادَ meaning \"he hunted\" or \"he caught prey.\" اصْطَادُوا means \"they hunted\" or \"they caught.\" The connection lies in the act of seeking and capturing animals, either for sustenance or other permissible purposes. This term emphasizes the effort, skill, and intentionality involved in the pursuit and capture, reflecting the root's focus on striving and obtaining. In Islamic law, it pertains to the regulations surrounding hunting, particularly the restrictions during sacred periods or specific conditions.",
  "617": "اصْطَبِرْ and related words stem from the root ص-ب-ر, with the root verb صَبَرَ meaning \"he was patient\" or \"he endured.\" اصْطَبِرْ means \"be patient!\" or \"persevere!\" The connection lies in the root's concept of steadfastness. اصْطَبِرْ intensifies the call to patience, urging one to exert effort in enduring hardships. It emphasizes the importance of resilience and unwavering commitment in the face of challenges.",
  "618": "اِصْطَفَىٰ and related words stem from the root ص-ف-و, with the root verb صَفَا meaning \"it was pure,\" or \"it was clear.\" اِصْطَفَىٰ means \"he selected\" or \"he chose for himself.\" The connection lies in choosing the purest or best, reflecting the root's emphasis on purity and excellence. In the Qur'an, it denotes Allah's (ﷻ) selection of prophets and messengers from among the people, emphasizing the honor of being chosen for a noble purpose and the responsibility that comes with divine selection.",
  "619": "اصْطَنَعْتُ and related words stem from the root ص-ن-ع, with the root verb صَنَعَ meaning \"he made\" or \"he crafted.\" اصْطَنَعْتُ means \"I selected\" or \"I chose for myself.\" The connection lies in crafting or preparing something with care and intention, reflecting the root's emphasis on purposeful creation or selection. This term highlights the act of carefully choosing or preparing, similar to how one might craft or form something with purpose.",
  "620": "اضْطُرَّ and related words stem from the root ض-ر-ر, with the root verb ضَرَّ meaning \"he harmed\" or \"he injured.\" اضْطُرَّ is a passive form meaning \"he was compelled\" or \"he was forced,\" reflecting a state where harm or pressure leaves no choice. The connection lies in the idea that compulsion often results from harmful circumstances that constrain one's free will, directly relating to the root's emphasis on harm. This term highlights the severity of situations that strip individuals of options, emphasizing the impact of adversity on human agency.",
  "621": "اضْمُمْ and related words stem from the root ض-م-م, with the root verb ضَمَّ meaning \"he joined\" or \"he brought together.\" اضْمُمْ means \"join!\" or \"bring together!\" The connection lies in commanding the action of uniting or bringing parts into a whole, directly aligning with the root's focus on gathering or assembling elements.",
  "622": "اِطَّيَّرَ and related words stem from the root ط-ي-ر, with the root verb طَارَ meaning \"he flew.\" اِطَّيَّرَ means \"he took an omen\" or \"he regarded something as a bad omen.\" The connection lies in the ancient practice of interpreting the flight of birds to predict future events, where the direction or manner of a bird's flight was seen as a sign of good or bad fortune. This reflects the root's concept of flight extending metaphorically to seeking signs or omens, emphasizing human tendencies toward superstition instead of reliance on faith.",
  "623": "اِطْرَحُوا and related words stem from the root ط-ر-ح, with the root verb طَرَحَ meaning \"he threw,\" \"he discarded,\" or \"he rejected.\" اِطْرَحُوا means \"cast away!\" or \"discard!\" The connection lies in the act of throwing away or rejecting something, directly relating to the root's emphasis on discarding. This term conveys the idea of letting go of what is unnecessary or unwanted, emphasizing rejection or removal in a decisive, forceful manner.",
  "624": "اِطْمَأَنَّ and related words stem from the root ط-م-أ-ن, with the root verb طَمَأَنَ meaning \"he was tranquil\" or \"he felt secure.\" اِطْمَأَنَّ means \"he became calm\" or \"he felt reassured,\" emphasizing achieving inner peace. The connection lies in attaining tranquility, directly reflecting the root's concept of calmness. This term highlights profound serenity and contentment, often associated with spiritual fulfillment and trust in Allah (ﷻ).",
  "625": "اعْتَبِرُوا and related words stem from the root ع-ب-ر, with the root verb عَبَرَ meaning \"he crossed\" or \"he traversed.\" اعْتَبِرُوا means \"Reflect!\" or \"Take heed!\" The connection lies in urging someone to cross over from ignorance to understanding, encouraging deep reflection and learning from experiences. This metaphorically reflects the root's concept of crossing over, highlighting a mental journey toward insight and wisdom.",
  "626": "اِعْتَدَىٰ and related words stem from the root ع-د-و, with the root verb عَدَا meaning \"he transgressed,\" \"he exceeded limits,\" or \"he acted aggressively.\" اِعْتَدَىٰ means \"he committed aggression\" or \"he transgressed.\" The connection lies in the act of overstepping boundaries or violating rights, directly relating to the root's emphasis on transgression. This term highlights the moral prohibition against aggression and injustice, reminding us to respect limits set by divine law and to uphold righteousness.",
  "627": "اِعْتَرَفَ and related words stem from the root ع-ر-ف, with the root verb عَرَفَ meaning \"he knew\" or \"he recognized.\" اِعْتَرَفَ means \"he admitted,\" \"he confessed,\" or \"he acknowledged.\" The reflexive nature of this form indicates admitting knowledge of something, directly relating to the root's concept of knowing. This term emphasizes the moral importance of acknowledging one's faults or truths, highlighting humility and honesty in personal conduct.",
  "628": "اعْتَرَىٰ and related words stem from the root ع-ر-و, with the root verb عَرَا meaning \"it befell,\" \"it came upon,\" or \"it afflicted.\"  اعْتَرَىٰ means \"it seized\" or \"it overtook,\" adding the nuance of an event or condition not only befalling someone, but doing so in a way that is overpowering or unavoidable. اعْتَرَىٰ emphasizes the suddenness and the overwhelming nature of the affliction or event, suggesting that it comes upon a person with force or impact. While عَرَا refers to the more general occurrence of something affecting someone, اعْتَرَىٰ specifically highlights how the event or condition \"seizes\" the person, often without warning, making it a more intense and disruptive experience.",
  "629": "اعْتَزَلَ and related words stem from the root ع-ز-ل, with the root verb عَزَلَ meaning \"he separated,\" \"he isolated,\" or \"he removed.\" اعْتَزَلَ means \"he withdrew,\" \"he secluded himself,\" or \"he abstained.\" The nuance here is reflexive, indicating that one separates oneself from others or from certain activities. This connects to the root's concept of separation and removal, emphasizing the act of withdrawing or isolating oneself, often for contemplation, avoiding harm, or abstaining from wrongdoing.",
  "630": "اعْتَصَمُوا and related words stem from the root ع-ص-م, with the root verb عَصَمَ meaning \"he protected\" or \"he held firmly.\" اعْتَصَمُوا means \"they held fast\" or \"they adhered firmly.\" The connection lies in collectively clinging to something secure for protection, reflecting the root's emphasis on firmness and safeguarding. This term highlights the importance of unity and steadfastness in adhering to principles or seeking protection, especially in times of trial.",
  "631": "اعْتَمَرَ and related words stem from the root ع-م-ر, with the root verb عَمَرَ meaning \"he inhabited,\" \"he enlivened,\" or \"he visited.\" اعْتَمَرَ means \"he performed 'Umrah,\" the lesser pilgrimage to the Kaaba. The connection is in visiting and revitalizing the sacred House of Allah (ﷻ), reflecting the root's emphasis on enlivening and inhabiting holy places. Performing 'Umrah symbolizes spiritual rejuvenation and dedication, as believers seek to enrich their souls and strengthen their connection with the divine through this sacred journey.",
  "632": "اعْتِلُوا and related words stem from the root ع-ت-ل, with the root verb عَتَلَ meaning \"he dragged violently,\" \"he pushed roughly,\" or \"he treated harshly.\" اعْتِلُوا means \"drag violently.\" The connection lies in the forceful and rough handling of someone, reflecting the root's emphasis on harshness and brutality. In the Qur'anic context, it describes the angels seizing wrongdoers in a severe manner as a consequence of their deeds.",
  "633": "اِغْتَرَفَ and related words stem from the root غ-ر-ف, with the root verb غَرَفَ meaning \"he scooped up\" or \"he took a handful.\" اِغْتَرَفَ means \"he scooped up for himself\" or \"he drew up,\" often referring to water. The connection lies in the act of gathering or acquiring something by one's own effort. This term emphasizes personal initiative in obtaining what is needed, reflecting the root's focus on collecting and taking hold.",
  "634": "اغْسِلُوا and related words stem from the root غ-س-ل, with the root verb غَسَلَ meaning \"he washed\" or \"he cleansed.\" اغْسِلُوا is the command form, meaning \"wash.\" The connection lies in the act of cleansing or purifying, reflecting the root's focus on removing impurities. This term highlights the significance of physical purification in Islam, serving as a prerequisite for acts of worship such as prayer. It symbolizes spiritual readiness, reinforcing the relationship between outward cleanliness and inner devotion.",
  "635": "اغْلُظْ and related words stem from the root غ-ل-ظ, with the root verb غَلُظَ meaning \"he was thick,\" \"coarse,\" or \"severe.\" اغْلُظْ means \"be stern,\" \"be severe,\" or \"intensify.\" This command instructs someone to adopt harshness or severity. The connection lies in actively embodying the root's concept of thickness or sternness, emphasizing a deliberate shift towards firmness. It reflects situations where strictness is necessary, highlighting the balance between compassion and severity in response to circumstances.",
  "636": "اِفْتَدَىٰ and related words stem from the root ف-د-ي, with the root verb فَدَىٰ meaning \"he ransomed\" or \"he redeemed.\" اِفْتَدَىٰ means \"he ransomed himself\" or \"he sought to redeem himself,\" highlighting the act of securing one's own freedom or salvation by offering something of value. The connection lies in personal responsibility and sacrifice, embodying the root's concept of redemption. This term emphasizes the proactive effort to rectify a situation, stressing the individual's role in seeking liberation or forgiveness.",
  "637": "افْتَرَىٰ and related words stem from the root ف-ر-ي, with the root verb فَرَىٰ meaning \"he cut,\" \"he split,\" or \"he fabricated.\" افْتَرَىٰ means \"he fabricated,\" \"he invented falsely,\" or \"he forged a lie.\" Broader root meanings emphasize the idea of cutting, cleaving, or reshaping something. The connection lies in fabricating lies as a metaphorical act of \"cutting into\" the truth, distorting or reshaping it into falsehoods. This term reflects the destructive nature of falsehood, likening it to severing integrity and reassembling it into something misleading.",
  "638": "افْتِرَاءٌ and related words stem from the root ف-ر-ي, with the root verb فَرَىٰ meaning \"he cut,\" \"he split,\" or \"he fabricated.\" افْتِرَاءٌ means \"fabrication,\" \"falsehood,\" or \"forgery.\" Broader root meanings highlight the act of cutting, cleaving, or shaping. The connection lies in crafting something deceitful, representing the deliberate creation of lies or falsehoods. This term highlights the intent behind fabrication, likening it to the act of cutting away truth to shape something untrue and misleading.",
  "639": "اقْتَتَلَ and related words stem from the root ق-ت-ل, with the root verb قَتَلَ meaning \"he killed.\" اقْتَتَلَ means \"they fought each other\" or \"they engaged in mutual killing.\" The connection lies in reciprocal action derived from the root's concept of killing. It emphasizes mutual combat or warfare, highlighting conflict and aggression between parties, and the destructive consequences of enmity.",
  "640": "اقْتَحَمَ and related words stem from the root ق-ح-م, with the root verb قَحَمَ meaning \"he plunged,\" \"he rushed headlong,\" or \"he entered recklessly.\" اقْتَحَمَ means \"he forced his way in,\" \"he plunged into,\" or \"he faced something head-on.\" The root conveys themes of boldness, urgency, and the willingness to confront challenges or difficulties directly. This form emphasizes deliberate and often arduous effort in overcoming obstacles, whether physical or metaphorical. It highlights the determination required to traverse steep or difficult paths, highlighting the courage and persistence needed to confront significant challenges and the consequences of such actions.",
  "641": "اقْتَدِ and related words stem from the root ق-د-و, with the root verb قَدَا meaning \"he followed,\" \"he emulated,\" or \"he took as an example.\" اقْتَدِ means \"Follow!\" or \"Emulate!\" emphasizing deliberate adherence to a model or guide. The root encapsulates themes of imitation, alignment, and the continuity of actions passed down. This term highlights the profound impact of role models and the responsibility of following a path, whether toward righteousness or misguidance. It emphasizes that the example chosen to follow shapes behavior, character, and outcomes, reflecting the root’s duality of leading and following.",
  "642": "اقْتَرَبَ and related words stem from the root ق-ر-ب, with the root verb قَرُبَ meaning \"he was near\" or \"he became close,\" denoting a state of inherent proximity without necessarily implying action. In contrast, اقْتَرَبَ means \"he drew near\" or \"he approached,\" emphasizing a deliberate and active effort to reduce distance. Broader root meanings encompass concepts of proximity, approach, and connection, whether physical, emotional, or spiritual. The distinction lies in قَرُبَ describing a passive state of nearness, while اقْتَرَبَ highlights intentional action to achieve closeness.",
  "643": "اقْتَرَفَ and related words stem from the root ق-ر-ف, with the root verb قَرَفَ meaning \"he peeled off,\" \"he scraped,\" or \"he falsely accused.\" اقْتَرَفَ means \"he committed,\" \"he perpetrated,\" or \"he earned,\" often referring to sinful acts. The connection lies in the metaphor of peeling or stripping away, symbolizing how each sin gradually removes layers of purity, leaving the individual exposed. This reflects a broader concept of moral erosion—where sins metaphorically \"scrape away\" at the soul, deepening a person’s spiritual vulnerability.",
  "644": "اقْصِدْ and related words stem from the root ق-ص-د, with the root verb قَصَدَ meaning \"he intended,\" \"he aimed,\" or \"he directed himself.\" اقْصِدْ is a command form meaning \"intend,\" \"aim,\" or \"be moderate,\" emphasizing deliberate and purposeful direction. The connection lies in the act of focusing one's efforts or maintaining balance in actions, avoiding extremes. This term highlights the importance of intentionality in aligning one’s actions with a clear goal or purpose while embodying moderation and restraint. It highlights the value of pursuing a righteous and balanced path, reflecting the root's emphasis on clarity, precision, and steadiness in achieving objectives.",
  "645": "اكْتَالُوا and related words stem from the root ك-ي-ل, with the root verb كَالَ meaning \"he measured\" or \"he weighed.\" اكْتَالُوا means \"they took a measure\" or \"they received by measure,\" emphasizing the act of obtaining a specific, measured quantity for themselves. The connection lies in the process of measuring commodities, particularly in the context of trade, where the subject actively acquires goods in a calculated amount. This term highlights the importance of fairness and accuracy in transactions, reflecting ethical principles in commerce to ensure equity and honesty in the exchange of goods.",
  "646": "اِكْتَتَبَ and related words stem from the root ك-ت-ب, with the root verb كَتَبَ meaning \"he wrote,\" \"he prescribed,\" or \"he decreed.\" اِكْتَتَبَ means \"he had written down\" or \"he caused to be written down,\" reflecting a nuance of acquiring writing for one's own purpose or benefit. This form emphasizes personal involvement in recording or transcribing, where the act of writing becomes self-directed and intentional. It highlights the root concept of writing while adding the dimension of individual initiative.",
  "647": "اكْتَسَبَ and related words stem from the root ك-س-ب, with the root verb كَسَبَ meaning \"he earned,\" \"he gained,\" or \"he acquired.\" اكْتَسَبَ means \"he earned for himself\" or \"he personally acquired,\" with the reflexive form emphasizing personal effort and responsibility in obtaining something. This connects to the root’s concept by highlighting the active pursuit and accountability in earning, whether for one’s benefit or detriment.",
  "648": "The particle ال serves multiple purposes, most commonly translating to \"the.\" It is used as a particle of determination, distinguishing a noun as definite or known, and can also denote an entire category or species. By acting as a prefix, ال transforms an indefinite noun into a definite one. In the Qur'an, ال is used extensively to specify and emphasize particular concepts, individuals, or entities, highlighting their significance.",
  "649": "اللَّاتُ refers to one of the main pre-Islamic idols worshipped by the Arabs, particularly by the tribe of Thaqif in Ta'if. Alongside al-Uzza and Manat, al-Lat was considered a goddess of fertility and prosperity, and the idol's shrine was a significant religious center. The Qur'an critiques the worship of these idols, emphasizing the Islamic principle of monotheism and the rejection of idolatry. The story of al-Lat, al-Uzza, and Manat illustrates the transition from polytheism to monotheism, highlighting the importance of worshiping Allah (ﷻ) alone.",
  "650": "اللَّهُ and related words stem from the root أ-ل-ه, with the root verb أَلَهَ meaning \"he worshipped\" or \"he adored.\" اللَّهُ is derived from إِلٰهٌ (god) combined with ال (the), meaning \"the one and only true God.\" The root conveys worship, seeking refuge, and absolute devotion, reflecting the deep bond between the worshiper and the Divine. اللَّهُ encompasses all perfect attributes of majesty, mercy, and power, signifying the ultimate source of guidance, protection, and sustenance. اللَّهُ is the One and Only, the Absolute, the Eternal, the only one worthy of complete love, reverence, and submission.",
  "651": "The relative pronoun الَّذِي means \"who,\" \"which,\" or \"that.\" It connects clauses by relating descriptions to their subjects, providing essential details about people or things being discussed. Its function is crucial for clarity, precision, and cohesion in sentences, allowing more complex ideas to be communicated effectively. In the Qur'an, الَّذِي plays a vital role in linking concepts, offering depth and specificity to Allah's (ﷻ) guidance and narratives.",
  "652": "اِلْتَفَّتِ and related words stem from the root ل-ف-ف, with the root verb لَفَّ meaning \"he wrapped,\" \"he wound,\" or \"he folded.\" اِلْتَفَّتِ means \"it wrapped around,\" \"it entwined,\" or \"it became intertwined.\" The connection lies in the action of wrapping or folding upon itself, reflecting the root's emphasis on enveloping or entwining. This term often describes things becoming closely bound or twisted together, emphasizing the closeness and inseparability of the elements involved. In context, it vividly depicts the intertwining or heaviness of legs in the throes of death, symbolizing the inevitable meeting with one's fate and the overwhelming reality of that moment.",
  "653": "اِلْتَقَمَ and related words stem from the root ل-ق-م, with the root verb لَقِمَ meaning \"he took a mouthful,\" \"he ate,\" or \"he swallowed.\" اِلْتَقَمَ means \"he swallowed,\" \"he took a mouthful.\" The connection lies in the act of taking something into the mouth and consuming it, reflecting the root's emphasis on ingestion and engulfing. This term illustrates the action of completely taking in or absorbing, as in the story of Prophet Jonah (ﷺ) being swallowed by the whale, emphasizing themes of overwhelming forces and surrender to divine will.",
  "654": "اِلْتَقَىٰ and related words stem from the root ل-ق-ي, with the root verb لَقِيَ meaning \"he met,\" \"he encountered,\" or \"he found.\" This root conveys the concept of coming together or facing something or someone. اِلْتَقَىٰ means \"he met\" or \"he encountered,\" emphasizing a mutual meeting where both parties actively come together, highlighting reciprocal encounters. This deepens the root concept by illustrating how meetings are mutual experiences that foster connection or confrontation, resonating with the essence of interaction and engagement.",
  "655": "اِلْتَمِسُوا and related words stem from the root ل-م-س, with the root verb لَمَسَ meaning \"he touched,\" \"he felt,\" or \"he perceived by touch.\" اِلْتَمَسَ means \"he sought out,\" \"he requested,\" or \"he asked for,\" and اِلْتَمِسُوا means \"seek out.\" The connection between seeking and touching lies in the shared idea of reaching or attempting to make contact, whether physically or metaphorically. Both involve an active effort to engage with or obtain something. This term highlights the pursuit of knowledge, assistance, or guidance, emphasizing deliberate effort driven by need or desire.",
  "656": "الْعُزَّىٰ and related words stem from the root ع-ز-ز, with the root verb عَزَّ meaning \"he was mighty,\" \"he was strong,\" or \"he was powerful.\" الْعُزَّىٰ means \"the mighty one\" or \"the most mighty,\" and was the name of a prominent goddess worshipped by the pre-Islamic Arabs. The connection lies in attributing might, power, and honor to this deity, reflecting the root’s focus on strength and prestige. The rejection of such idols highlights the belief in Allah’s (ﷻ) unmatched might, sovereignty, and absolute uniqueness, emphasizing that true might belongs to Him alone.",
  "657": "الْغَوْا and related words stem from the root ل-غ-و, with the root verb لَغَا meaning \"he spoke vainly,\" \"he uttered nonsense,\" or \"he made noise.\" الْغَوْا means \"utter nonsense,\" \"speak vainly,\" or \"speak frivolously.\" The connection lies in the act of producing meaningless or distracting sounds, reflecting the root's emphasis on vain speech and deliberate disruption. This word highlights behaviors that interfere with meaningful communication, often used to signify intentional disrespect or attempts to nullify important speech.",
  "658": "الْيَسَعُ is the name of Prophet Elisha (ﷺ), derived from Hebrew with אל (El) meaning \"God\" and ישע (yasha‘) meaning \"to save\" or \"deliver.\" He is mentioned among the prophets chosen and honored by Allah (ﷻ) for their righteousness and steadfastness in guiding their people. His name, meaning \"God saves,\" reflects his mission of delivering his community from misguidance and leading them to worship Allah (ﷻ) alone. His inclusion among the great prophets emphasizes his role in preserving Allah's (ﷻ) guidance and salvation.",
  "659": "اِمْتَازُوا and related words stem from the root م-ي-ز, with the root verb مَازَ meaning \"he separated,\" \"he distinguished,\" or \"he set apart.\" اِمْتَازُوا means \"separate yourselves\" or \"stand apart.\" This reflects a deliberate act of setting oneself apart or being distinguished from others. In the Qur'an, it is used as a command for the wicked to separate from the righteous, emphasizing themes of accountability and moral distinction. The root also conveys the idea of clarity and defining boundaries, reflecting a purposeful separation between what is good and bad, right and wrong.",
  "660": "اِمْتَحَنَ and related words stem from the root م-ح-ن, with the root verb مَحَنَ meaning \"he tested\" or \"he tried.\" اِمْتَحَنَ means \"he examined,\" \"he tested thoroughly,\" or \"he subjected to trial.\" The connection lies in putting someone or something through a process to assess quality, strength, or authenticity, directly relating to the root's concept of testing. It emphasizes the importance of trials in proving worthiness or revealing true nature.",
  "661": "امْتَلَأَ and related words stem from the root م-ل-أ, with the root verb مَلَأَ meaning \"he filled.\" امْتَلَأَ specifically means \"he was filled\" or \"it became full,\" denoting a state of being completely filled or saturated. According to nuanced root meanings, مَلَأَ extends beyond physical filling to encompass metaphorical concepts such as the filling of spaces, hearts, or minds with emotions, knowledge, or other intangible qualities. The root also conveys ideas of abundance, completeness, and saturation, emphasizing the transition from emptiness to fullness.",
  "662": "امْرَأَ and related words stem from the root م-ر-أ, with the root verb مَرَأَ meaning \"he digested (food).\" امْرَأَ is not commonly used in Arabic and appears in rare contexts. It is closely related to امْرُؤٌ, meaning \"man\" or \"person.\" The connection lies in the root’s emphasis on digestion and vitality, symbolizing human sustenance and life processes. Unlike امْرُؤٌ and related terms, امْرَأَ carries a more formal and emphatic tone, often used to denote an individual's moral standing or character. It highlights not just the physical role of sustaining life but also the broader implications of a person’s behavior, reputation, or qualities, making it distinct in its usage and connotation.",
  "663": "اِمْرَأَةٌ and related words stem from the root م-ر-أ, with the root verb مَرَأَ meaning \"he digested (food).\" اِمْرَأَةٌ means \"woman\" or \"wife.\" The connection metaphorically lies in the role of women in nurturing and sustaining life, akin to digestion, which nourishes and maintains health. The word highlights the central role of women in creating harmony and continuity within families and societies. This connection ties the physical process of digestion to the symbolic nurturing and support often associated with women.",
  "664": "امْرُؤٌ stems from the root م-ر-أ, with the root verb مَرَأَ meaning \"he digested (food).\" امْرُؤٌ means \"man\" or \"person.\" The term emphasizes the individual’s role in consuming and processing life’s resources, tying digestion to survival and vitality. It highlights human attributes like resilience and adaptability, representing the ability to face life’s challenges and thrive. The term also reflects the individual as a self-reliant entity, standing independently yet connected to the processes of life that sustain existence.",
  "665": "امْرِئٍ stems from the root م-ر-أ, with the root verb مَرَأَ meaning \"he digested (food).\" امْرِئٍ means \"man\" or \"person.\" It carries a relational nuance, often used to describe a person within a specific context or in connection to others. This reflects the interdependent aspects of human life, emphasizing relationships, responsibilities, and the role of individuals as part of a broader social or familial framework. It ties the root's emphasis on sustenance to the interconnectedness of human existence.",
  "666": "امْسَحُوا and related words stem from the root م-س-ح, with the root verb مَسَحَ meaning \"he wiped,\" \"he rubbed,\" or \"he anointed.\" امْسَحُوا means \"wipe!\" or \"rub!\" This form reflects the act of passing one’s hand over a surface, often for purposes like cleaning, physical contact, or ritual purification. The root emphasizes deliberate and purposeful contact, as seen in practices such as wiping during ablution or actions related to spiritual healing. This connection highlights the root's association with touch as an essential and transformative act in contexts of cleansing and spiritual renewal.",
  "667": "انْبِعَاثَهُمْ and related words stem from the root ب-ع-ث, with the root verb بَعَثَ meaning \"he sent,\" often referring to sending a messenger or something significant. It also means \"he awakened\" or \"put in motion,\" particularly in stirring someone from sleep or inactivity, and can signify \"resurrection\" in the Qur’an. انْبِعَاثَهُمْ refers to the state of being sent forth or rising into action, highlighting readiness and mobilization. The root conveys themes of awakening, motion, and purpose, emphasizing the transition from stillness to action, whether in fulfilling a mission or preparing for spiritual accountability.",
  "668": "انْتَبَذَتْ and related words stem from the root ن-ب-ذ, with the root verb نَبَذَ meaning \"he discarded\" or \"he threw away.\" انْتَبَذَتْ means \"she withdrew\" or \"she secluded herself.\" The form indicates a reflexive action, suggesting distancing oneself. The connection lies in the idea of setting something aside, here applied to oneself withdrawing from others. This reflects themes of seclusion or retreat, possibly for reflection or to avoid undesirable influences, highlighting the personal choice to step away from distractions.",
  "669": "انْتَثَرَتْ and related words stem from the root ن-ث-ر, with the root verb نَثَرَ meaning \"he scattered\" or \"he dispersed.\" انْتَثَرَتْ means \"it scattered\" or \"it was dispersed,\" often referring to the widespread dispersion of things from a central point. The root also includes meanings of spreading, distributing, and separating, symbolizing diffusion and the breaking apart of a unified whole. This connection reflects the transient nature of worldly matters, emphasizing the impermanence and dispersal inherent in life, and often evokes themes of disorder or natural scattering.",
  "670": "انْتَصَرَ and related words stem from the root ن-ص-ر, with the root verb نَصَرَ meaning \"he helped.\" انْتَصَرَ means \"he defended himself\" or \"he was victorious,\" emphasizing self-defense and achieving triumph through one’s efforts. The connection lies in securing justice or vindication, directly relating to the root’s focus on triumph and support. انْتَصَرَ highlights themes of resilience and justice, reflecting the balance between seeking assistance and taking responsibility for one’s own success.",
  "671": "انْتَقَمَ and related words stem from the root ن-ق-م, with the root verb نَقَمَ meaning \"he resented,\" \"he avenged,\" or \"he punished.\" انْتَقَمَ means \"he took revenge\" or \"he exacted retribution,\" emphasizing the deliberate act of seeking justice through punishment. The root conveys themes of indignation, dissatisfaction, and retaliation, reflecting a response to perceived wrongdoing. انْتَقَمَ highlights the concept of justice being served through retributive actions, highlighting a balance between wrongdoing and its consequences.",
  "672": "انْتَهَى and related words stem from the root ن-ه-ي, with the root verb نَهَى meaning \"he forbade\" or \"he prevented.\" انْتَهَى means \"he refrained,\" \"he ceased,\" or \"he ended.\" The connection lies in bringing something to a stop or refraining from action, reflecting the root's emphasis on prohibition and cessation. It highlights the importance of self-restraint and adhering to moral boundaries.",
  "673": "انْتِقَامٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ق-م, with the root verb نَقَمَ meaning \"he resented,\" \"he avenged,\" or \"he took revenge.\" انْتِقَامٌ refers to \"revenge,\" \"retribution,\" or \"vengeance,\" emphasizing the act of punishing wrongdoing. The root reflects the intense response to perceived injustice or harm, highlighting the pursuit of justice through retaliation. انْتِقَامٌ captures the essence of accountability, where consequences are enacted to address grievances or restore balance.",
  "674": "اِنْسَلَخَ and related words stem from the root س-ل-خ, with the root verb سَلَخَ meaning \"he stripped off,\" \"he flayed,\" or \"he removed (skin).\" اِنْسَلَخَ means \"he slipped away,\" \"he withdrew,\" or \"he shed (as a snake sheds its skin).\" The connection lies in the process of removing or separating oneself from something, reflecting the root's concept of stripping away. It conveys the idea of departure or detachment, often implying a complete separation from a former state or condition, symbolizing transformation or abandonment.",
  "675": "اِنْشَقَّ and related words stem from the root ش-ق-ق, with the root verb شَقَّ meaning \"he split\" or \"he cleft.\" اِنْشَقَّ means \"it was split\" or \"it split open by itself.\" This form reflects an action occurring without direct external cause. The connection lies in the root's emphasis on splitting or dividing. اِنْشَقَّ vividly portrays something opening up or breaking apart naturally, highlighting the inevitable occurrence of division.",
  "676": "انشُزُوا and related words stem from the root ن-ش-ز, with the root verb نَشَزَ meaning \"he rose,\" \"he elevated,\" or \"he moved apart.\" انشُزُوا is a command form meaning \"rise up,\" \"stand up,\" or \"move to a higher place.\" The root conveys themes of elevation, readiness, and movement. In certain contexts, it can also imply creating space or accommodating others, emphasizing social responsiveness. This term highlights the act of rising physically or metaphorically to fulfill a need or responsibility.",
  "677": "اِنْصَرَفُوا and related words stem from the root ص-ر-ف, with the root verb صَرَفَ meaning \"he turned away\" or \"he departed.\" اِنْصَرَفُوا means \"they turned away\" or \"they departed.\" The connection lies in the act of moving away from something, symbolizing a departure or withdrawal, whether physically or metaphorically. This term conveys the idea of leaving, disengaging, or retreating from a place, situation, or course of action.",
  "678": "اِنْطَلَقَ and related words stem from the root ط-ل-ق, with the root verb طَلَقَ meaning \"he released\" or \"he freed.\" اِنْطَلَقَ means \"he set out\" or \"he proceeded,\" emphasizing beginning a journey or action freely. The connection lies in being released to move forward, directly reflecting the root's concept of liberation. This term highlights the initiation of purposeful action with freedom and resolve.",
  "679": "اِنْفَجَرَتْ and related words stem from the root ف-ج-ر, with the root verb فَجَرَ meaning \"it burst forth\" or \"it gushed out.\" اِنْفَجَرَتْ means \"it burst forth\" or \"it erupted,\" often used to describe water emerging forcefully. The connection lies in the sudden and powerful emergence from within, aligning with the root's idea of breaking or splitting open. This term vividly illustrates dynamic action, emphasizing the natural force and energy inherent in phenomena like springs or emotions erupting.",
  "680": "اِنْفَطَرَتْ and related words stem from the root ف-ط-ر, with the root verb فَطَرَ meaning \"he cleft,\" \"he split,\" or \"he created.\" اِنْفَطَرَتْ means \"it was cleft asunder\" or \"it split open,\" describing the act of breaking apart or being divided. The root conveys a dual nature: the act of cleaving to create and originate, and the eventual breaking down or splitting apart as part of a greater purpose. اِنْفَطَرَتْ is used to describe the splitting of the sky on the Day of Judgment, symbolizing the end of this temporary world and the preparation for the eternal hereafter. This connection highlights that the universe was not only created through cleaving but was also designed to be cleft apart when its purpose is fulfilled.",
  "681": "انْفَلَقَ and related words stem from the root ف-ل-ق, with the root verb فَلَقَ meaning \"he split,\" \"he cleaved,\" or \"he caused to break open.\" انْفَلَقَ means \"it split asunder\" or \"it burst open.\" The connection emphasizes the action of something splitting itself, highlighting a natural or sudden division. This term can reflect miraculous events, such as the parting of the sea, symbolizing the power of divine intervention causing something to open up.",
  "682": "اِنْفِصَامٌ and related words stem from the root ف-ص-م, with the root verb فَصَمَ meaning \"he broke,\" \"he split,\" or \"he severed.\" اِنْفِصَامٌ means \"breaking,\" \"shattering,\" or \"splitting apart.\" The connection lies in the act of something coming apart or being broken, reflecting the root's emphasis on severance. This term highlights the fragility of bonds or structures that can be broken, often used metaphorically for relationships or covenants.",
  "683": "انْقَلَبَ and related words stem from the root ق-ل-ب, with the root verb قَلَبَ meaning \"he turned over,\" \"he inverted,\" or \"he changed.\" انْقَلَبَ means \"he returned,\" \"he turned back,\" or \"he was overturned,\" emphasizing the action of turning or transitioning from one state to another. The root highlights themes of transformation and reversal. In a broader sense, it can symbolize returning to a previous state, whether favorable or unfavorable, or the shifting of fortunes, serving as a reminder of the fleeting and ever-changing nature of worldly life.",
  "684": "اِنْكَدَرَتْ and related words stem from the root ك-د-ر, with the root verb كَدِرَ meaning \"it became turbid,\" \"it became dull,\" or \"it became gloomy.\" اِنْكَدَرَتْ means \"it fell,\" \"it scattered,\" or \"it dimmed,\" often used to describe celestial bodies like stars. The root emphasizes the idea of disturbance, loss of clarity, or dimming of brilliance. اِنْكَدَرَتْ conveys imagery of stars falling from their positions or losing their light, symbolizing disruption, cosmic upheaval, or the fading of an established order. This reflects themes of transformation, highlighting the inevitable decline or transition that signifies the end of a significant era.",
  "685": "انْحَرْ and related words stem from the root ن-ح-ر, with the root verb نَحَرَ meaning \"he slaughtered\" or \"he sacrificed (an animal by cutting its throat).\" انْحَرْ means \"sacrifice!\" or \"offer sacrifice.\" The connection lies in the act of offering a ritual sacrifice to Allah (ﷻ), highlighting themes of devotion, submission, and gratitude. This emphasizes the importance of worship through prescribed acts, symbolizing commitment and thankfulness.",
  "686": "انْهَارَ and related words stem from the root ه-و-ر, with the root verb هَارَ meaning \"it collapsed\" or \"it crumbled.\" انْهَارَ means \"it collapsed\" or \"it fell down,\" describing the complete action of structural failure. The root emphasizes falling apart or disintegrating due to weakness or instability. This term reflects the fragility of constructs, highlighting the inevitable collapse of anything lacking a solid foundation, whether physical, moral, or spiritual. It highlights the importance of stability and integrity in ensuring endurance and avoiding ruin.",
  "687": "اِنۢبَجَسَتْ and related words stem from the root ب-ج-س, with the root verb بَجَسَ meaning \"he opened a way or a channel,\" or \"he caused to gush forth,\" often in reference to the emergence of water or another substance. اِنۢبَجَسَتْ means \"it gushed forth\" or \"it burst forth,\" referring to a sudden breaking open from which something flows. The connection lies in the imagery of something splitting or bursting to release a flow, reflecting the root’s concept of release after pressure or containment. This term embodies the powerful moment of emergence, where something hidden or confined finds an outlet to pour forth freely.",
  "688": "اِنۢبَعَثَ and related words stem from the root ب-ع-ث, with the root verb بَعَثَ meaning \"he sent,\" often referring to sending a messenger or something important. It also means \"he awakened\" or \"put in motion,\" especially when stirring someone from sleep or inactivity. In the Qur’an, بَعَثَ can also signify \"resurrection.\" اِنۢبَعَثَ refers to the action of someone being sent forth or arising from a state of rest or inactivity. This term emphasizes an active response to a call or task, symbolizing a person’s awakening or mobilization for a specific purpose, whether physical or spiritual.",
  "689": "اهْتَدَىٰ and related words stem from the root ه-د-ي, with the root verb هَدَىٰ meaning \"he guided\" or \"he led aright.\" اهْتَدَىٰ means \"he was guided\" or \"he found guidance.\" As a reflexive form, it emphasizes the personal effort involved in seeking and embracing guidance. This term highlights the active role of the individual in pursuing the correct path, reflecting themes of self-awareness, self-improvement, and enlightenment. By embodying the journey of internal transformation, اهْتَدَىٰ showcases the dynamic relationship between seeking truth and receiving direction, highlighting the personal responsibility inherent in accepting guidance.",
  "690": "اهْتَزَّتْ and related words stem from the root ه-ز-ز, with the root verb هَزَّ meaning \"he shook,\" \"he moved,\" or \"he agitated.\" اهْتَزَّتْ means \"it shook\" or \"it quivered.\" This term connects to the root's concept by describing something that has vibrated or trembled, often indicating vitality or responsiveness. It reflects themes of movement and liveliness inherent in the root, emphasizing the dynamic nature of the subject.",
  "691": "اهْجُرْ and related words stem from the root ه-ج-ر, with the root verb هَجَرَ meaning \"he left,\" \"he forsook,\" \"he abandoned,\" \"he shunned,\" and also \"he spoke irrationally or uttered nonsense.\" اهْجُرْ, meaning \"Abandon!\" or \"Forsake!\" reflects the root’s concept of deliberate separation from something undesirable. The root encompasses physical departure (هِجْرَة, migration), social disengagement, and irrational speech, all tied by the idea of deviation or departure. Even in the context of nonsensical speech, it signifies a departure from coherence. اهْجُرْ thus calls for forsaking harmful actions, associations, or irrationality, aligning with the root’s broader theme of purposeful detachment to uphold clarity and integrity.",
  "692": "The preposition بِ means \"by,\" \"with,\" or \"in.\" It is a key word used to link other words and clarify their relationship in a sentence. بِ can show how something is done (means), why something happens (cause), or who or what is involved (accompaniment). It helps add detail and precision, often explaining the method, cause, or company in which an action takes place.",
  "693": "بَاءَ and related words stem from the root ب-و-أ, and as the root verb, it means \"he returned\" or \"he withdrew.\" It can also imply “returning with something,” particularly a burden or responsibility. بَاءَ often highlights the act of accepting guilt or facing consequences, as if one returns bearing the weight of accountability. The root suggests a return to a previous state, often with the acceptance of outcomes tied to one’s actions.",
  "694": "بَائِسٌ and related words stem from the root ب-أ-س, with the root verb بَئِسَ encompassing meanings such as \"he was wretched,\" \"he suffered misfortune,\" \"he was distressed,\" and \"he was mighty or strong in war or fight.\" بَائِسٌ means \"miserable,\" \"wretched,\" or \"afflicted,\" capturing a state of severe hardship or distress. The connection to the root’s broader meanings can be seen in the intensity of the affliction: just as might and resilience are required in battle, a similar strength is needed to endure profound suffering. ",
  "695": "بَابٌ and related words stem from the root ب-و-ب, with the root verb بَوَّبَ meaning \"he divided into distinct kinds\" or \"he arranged, classified, or set in order.\" بَابٌ refers to a door, gate, or entrance—a physical opening or passage. Metaphorically, it signifies a way, method, or opportunity. In classical usage, it extends to sections or chapters in books, symbolizing entry points to various subjects or areas of knowledge. This connection reflects the essence of بَابٌ as an opening or access point, whether physical, intellectual, or metaphorical, emphasizing its role in facilitating transitions, organization, and discovery.",
  "696": "بَابِلُ refers to \"Babel\" or \"Babylon,\" the ancient city in modern-day Iraq renowned for its grandeur and historical significance. In Babylonian culture, البَابِلِىُّ referred to the planet Jupiter, associated with their chief deity Marduk, symbolizing power, creation, and order. Babylon was a hub of idolatry, with Marduk embodying authority. It is where the Angels Harut (ﷺ) and Marut (ﷺ) were sent to test the people by teaching magic while warning against its misuse. Babylon came to symbolize corruption and destruction, illustrating the consequences of turning away from Allah's (ﷻ) guidance.",
  "697": "باخِعٌ and related words stem from the root ب-خ-ع, with the root verb بَخَعَ meaning \"he killed himself\" or \"he exerted himself to the utmost,\" particularly in a state of overwhelming effort or distress. باخِعٌ translates as \"one who destroys themselves,\" \"one who destroys themselves out of grief,\" or \"one who overwhelms themselves,\" describing someone consumed by grief or pushing themselves to extreme limits. The connection lies in self-inflicted distress or emotional harm, where excessive sorrow or effort leads to internal collapse.",
  "698": "بادٍ and related words stem from the root ب-د-و, with the root verb بَدَا meaning \"he or it became apparent\" or \"he or it appeared.\" بادٍ translates as \"visible\" or \"apparent,\" emphasizing the quality of being openly seen or manifest. The root conveys the concept of something coming into view, emerging, or revealing itself, capturing both the physical visibility and the idea of clarity or obviousness.",
  "699": "بَادُونَ and related words stem from the root ب-د-و, with the root verb بَدَا meaning \"he or it became apparent,\" \"he or it appeared,\" or \"he or it came into view.\" بَادُونَ means \"those dwelling in the desert,\" referring to people living outside cities in rural or nomadic settings. The root conveys themes of exposure, visibility, and emergence, reflecting the lifestyle of those in open environments like deserts or plains. This connection highlights a way of life tied to nature, simplicity, and survival in exposed surroundings, emphasizing both appearance and being revealed.",
  "700": "بَادِيَ and related words stem from the root ب-د-و, with the root verb بَدَا meaning \"he or it became apparent\" or \"he or it appeared.\" بَادِيَ refers to something outwardly visible or apparent, often emphasizing initial or surface-level impressions. The term highlights external visibility, contrasting with deeper or internal realities. When applied to a person, بَادِيَ implies someone who reacts to or is influenced by first impressions, relying on the immediately visible or apparent without deeper consideration.",
  "701": "بارَكَ and related words stem from the root ب-ر-ك, with the root verb بَرَكَ meaning \"he or it was firm, steady, or fixed,\" or \"he or it continued, remained, or stayed.\" This foundational sense of stability connects to بارَكَ, meaning \"he blessed\" or \"he bestowed blessings,\" implying not merely a gift but a blessing that fosters enduring growth and sustenance. Symbolically, بَرَكَ is also linked to بَرَك (a pool of water), a rare source of life in desert contexts. Thus, بارَكَ evokes a blessing that promotes spiritual or material growth, multiplying beyond ordinary means and continually providing benefit.",
  "702": "بارِئٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ر-أ, with the root verb بَرَأَ meaning \"he created,\" \"he brought into being,\" or \"he made free from fault.\" الْبَارِئُ, one of Allah’s (ﷻ) perfect names, means \"the Maker,\" specifically emphasizing the act of bringing creation into existence in a perfect and unique form. The root conveys themes of creation, precision, and freedom from defects, highlighting Allah’s (ﷻ) perfection and meticulous care in creating. This name highlights His ability to bring forth flawless and purposeful creations with unmatched precision.",
  "703": "بَارِدٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ر-د, with the root verb بَرَدَ meaning \"he became cold\" or \"he cooled.\" بَارِدٌ translates as \"cold\" or \"cool,\" describing the absence of heat. The root encompasses more than physical temperature, extending to a sense of calmness, relief, or tranquility that accompanies coolness. In broader contexts, بَارِدٌ can imply soothing or refreshing qualities, suggesting a state free from agitation or intensity, where coolness brings comfort and peace.",
  "704": "بَارِزُونَ and related words stem from the root ب-ر-ز, with the root verb بَرَزَ meaning \"he or it became apparent,\" \"manifest,\" or \"appeared in the open.\" بَارِزُونَ translates as \"those who are apparent\" or \"those who stand out,\" describing someone or something visible, prominent, or exposed. The root also suggests emerging from concealment or stepping into visibility, often with boldness. In some contexts, بَارِزُونَ may imply individuals who are exposed or vulnerable, as well as those who distinguish themselves by coming into view.",
  "705": "بارِزَةٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ر-ز, with the verb بَرَزَ meaning \"he or it became apparent,\" \"manifest,\" or \"appeared in the open.\" بارِزَةٌ translates as \"something prominent\" or \"something that stands out,\" describing something visible or fully exposed, either physically or figuratively. The root suggests not only visibility but also emergence from a hidden state, emphasizing something that is now openly seen, bold, or unmissable. In some contexts, بارِزَةٌ can imply something brought forth deliberately or something that distinguishes itself by coming into the spotlight.",
  "706": "بَازِغٌ and related words stem from the root ب ز غ, with the root verb بَزَغَ meaning \"it rose\" or \"it appeared,\" especially referring to the rising of celestial bodies like the sun or moon. بَازِغٌ means \"one that begins to rise\" or \"something that appears,\" emphasizing the initial phase of an ascent or emergence. This word suggests the start of something visible and significant, like the moon or the first light at dawn.",
  "707": "بَازِغَةٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ز-غ, with the root verb بَزَغَ meaning \"it rose\" or \"it appeared,\" often referring to the rising of celestial bodies like the sun or moon. بَازِغَةٌ means \"one that begins to rise\" or \"something that emerges,\" highlighting the start of an ascent or appearance. This word emphasizes the initial phase of something becoming visible and prominent, much like the sun or the dawn breaking over the horizon.",
  "708": "باسِرَةٌ and related words stem from the root ب-س-ر, with the root verb بَسَرَ meaning \"he was quick\" or \"he acted prematurely,\" and also \"he frowned\" or \"contracted his face in dislike.\" باسِرَةٌ describes a grim or frowning face, conveying distress, anxiety, or displeasure. The connection to acting prematurely suggests a reaction to something overwhelming, where the expression reveals inner turmoil or dread. In the Qur'an, باسِرَةٌ is used to depict faces marked by anguish or fear, highlighting how hastily rejecting the truth results in a state of visible distress and regret.",
  "709": "باسِطٌ and related words stem from the root ب-س-ط, with the root verb بَسَطَ meaning \"he spread it\" or \"he expanded, extended, or widened it.\" باسِطٌ means \"one who spreads out\" or \"one who extends,\" describing something that expands or extends, literally and metaphorically. The root also conveys ease and openness, emphasizing physical expansion and emotional or spiritual openness. الْبَاسِطُ, one of Allah’s (ﷻ) perfect names, means \"The Extender,\" signifying His power to extend blessings, sustenance, or mercy to His creation. This name reflects Allah’s (ﷻ) boundless generosity and care, emphasizing His ability to expand provisions, opportunities, or understanding according to His wisdom.",
  "710": "بَاسِقَاتٍ and related words stem from the root ب-س-ق, with the verb بَسَقَ meaning \"it became tall, full-grown, or exceedingly tall,\" often describing palm trees. It can also imply \"he excelled them or was superior to them.\" بَاسِقَاتٍ describes something tall or towering, typically referring to palm trees that have reached great heights. This term emphasizes exceptional growth and prominence, symbolizing something that excels in stature and stands out due to its impressive, elevated form. It reflects rising to an admirable, almost majestic level, drawing on the palm tree’s graceful, superior height.",
  "711": "بَاشِرُوهُنَّ and related words stem from the root ب-ش-ر, with the root verb بَشَرَ meaning \"to remove the outer layer,\" and by extension, \"to make bare or expose.\" بَاشِرُوهُنَّ means \"make direct contact with them (spouses)\" or \"have an intimate relationship,\" specifically in the context of marriage. This root conveys themes of directness, closeness, and connection, emphasizing the intimate bond between spouses. The connection to بَشَرَ highlights the physical closeness between spouses, reflecting the natural and nurturing aspects of intimacy. This closeness is both physical and emotional, fostering comfort and a deeper bond, aligning with the positive and uplifting associations of the root.",
  "712": "بَاطِلٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ط-ل, with the root verb بَطَلَ meaning \"it was or became false, untrue, incorrect, fictitious, spurious, unfounded, or unsound.\" بَاطِلٌ means \"falsehood,\" \"vanity,\" or \"futility,\" describing something that lacks truth, substance, or enduring value. It conveys the idea of emptiness or meaninglessness, often in contrast to truth or righteousness. بَاطِلٌ suggests that something is inherently void, ephemeral, or deceptive—appearing substantial but ultimately without real worth or purpose, leading only to waste or misguidance.",
  "713": "بَاطِنَةٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ط-ن, with the root verb بَطَنَ meaning \"he or it was hidden, concealed, or inward,\" emphasizing aspects of concealment or depth. بَاطِنَةٌ refers to the \"inner part\" or \"hidden aspect\" of something, whether a matter, place, or condition. It describes what is concealed from view, existing beneath the surface, and often points to deeper, unseen realities that require reflection or insight to understand fully. The root conveys themes of inwardness and depth, highlighting the importance of looking beyond the surface to uncover true meaning.",
  "714": "بَاعِدْ and related words stem from the root ب-ع-د, with the root verb بَعُدَ meaning \"he became distant, remote, or aloof,\" or \"he withdrew far away,\" indicating physical, temporal, or spiritual distance. بَاعَدَ means \"he caused distance\" or \"he created separation,\" emphasizing an intentional effort to increase distance between entities. بَاعِدْ is a command meaning \"create distance\" or \"separate,\" often reflecting a deliberate action to detach or remove oneself from harmful states, influences, or conditions. The root conveys themes of separation, detachment, and removal, suggesting both physical and metaphorical distancing as a means of achieving safety, clarity, or purification.",
  "715": "بَاغٍ and related words stem from the root ب-غ-ى, with the root verb بَغَىٰ meaning \"he sought, desired, or aimed for something,\" or \"he sought beyond the limits.\" بَاغٍ means \"one who seeks wrongfully\" or \"acts beyond rightful limits,\" describing someone who oversteps boundaries in pursuit of selfish or unjust goals. The root conveys themes of seeking, ambition, and transgression, emphasizing the consequences of crossing moral or legal limits. In the Qur'an, بَاغٍ is associated with rebellion and oppression, condemning those who disrupt justice and cause harm through excessive or wrongful desires.",
  "716": "باقٍ and related words stem from the root ب-ق-ي, with the root verb بَقِيَ meaning \"he remained,\" \"he endured,\" or \"he stayed behind.\" باقٍ describes something that is \"enduring,\" \"lasting,\" or \"remaining,\" emphasizing the quality of persistence or permanence within it. This term embodies the concept of continuity and the inherent nature of certain things to withstand change or decay, remaining unaffected over time. It reflects the idea of what is meant to endure, often suggesting a lasting significance or an essential presence that persists.",
  "717": "بَالٌ and related words stem from the root ب-و-ل, which refers to a state, condition, or case, particularly concerning a person’s mental state, thoughts, or circumstances. The word بَالٌ is often used in classical Arabic and Qur'anic contexts to describe an individual’s inner concerns, preoccupations, or overall situation, whether reflecting ease or distress. This root emphasizes the significance of a person’s inner awareness and attentiveness to their condition, highlighting the interplay between their external circumstances and internal responses. It highlights the importance of mindfulness and recognizing one’s situation as part of a broader divine plan.",
  "718": "بالِغٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ل-غ, with the root verb بَلَغَ meaning \"he reached\" or \"he attained.\" بالِغٌ means reaching, attaining, or arriving at a destination or goal. It also conveys the sense of achieving a state of completion, such as reaching puberty or maturity. This term reflects not just physical arrival but the fulfillment of a stage or condition, implying growth, completeness, or readiness as one progresses to a new phase.",
  "719": "بالِغَةٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ل-غ, with the root verb بَلَغَ meaning \"he reached\" or \"he attained.\" بالِغَةٌ means \"reaching,\" \"attaining,\" or \"coming to\" a point or state, and often refers to something that is \"mature,\" \"fully developed,\" or \"eloquent.\" In classical usage, بالِغَةٌ is frequently associated with speech or expression that is powerful and complete, conveying ideas with full clarity and impact. The term highlights reaching an ideal state of completeness or maturity, whether in communication, actions, or achievements.",
  "720": "بَايَعْتُمْ and related words stem from the root ب-ي-ع, with the root verb بَاعَ meaning \"he sold.\" بَايَعَ means \"he exchanged commodities\" or \"he pledged allegiance.\" بَايَعْتُمْ means \"you all pledged allegiance,\" referring to a formal and binding agreement between two or more parties. The root concept of exchange emphasizes the idea of giving something valuable in return for a commitment, reflecting mutual trust and serious obligation. This term captures the weight of allegiance, where each party offers something significant, symbolizing loyalty, dedication, and a shared purpose.",
  "721": "بَأْسٌ and related words stem from the root ب-أ-س, with the root verb بَئِسَ meaning \"he was mighty or strong in war\" as well as \"he was wretched,\" \"suffered misfortune,\" or \"was distressed.\" بَأْسٌ translates as \"strength\" or \"might,\" particularly in contexts of war, intense struggle, or punishment. The connection lies in the intensity shared by combat, hardship, and divine wrath, as it often refers to Allah’s (ﷻ) punishment upon those who disbelieve. This duality emphasizes the resilience required to endure trials while reminding of the consequences of transgressing and rejecting faith.",
  "722": "بَأْسَاءُ and related words stem from the root ب-أ-س, with the root verb بَئِسَ meaning \"he was mighty or strong in war\" and also \"he was wretched,\" \"suffered misfortune,\" or \"was distressed.\" بَأْسَاءُ translates as \"adversity\" or \"hardship,\" especially in contexts of trials and tribulations. The connection lies in experiencing intense hardship, reflecting the root’s association with both suffering and resilience. بَأْسَاءُ highlights life’s severe trials, emphasizing patience, perseverance, and reliance on Allah (ﷻ) during challenging times.",
  "723": "بَئِيسٌ and related words stem from the root ب-أ-س, with the root verb بَئِسَ meaning \"he was mighty or strong in war\" as well as \"he was wretched,\" \"suffered misfortune,\" or \"was distressed.\" بَئِيسٌ translates as \"formidable\" or \"mighty,\" denoting a force that is intimidating and inspires caution due to its strength. The connection lies in the intensity and strength inherent in the root, which conveys awe-inspiring power. This term highlights not only physical might but also a presence that demands respect and restraint.",
  "724": "بَثٌّ and related words stem from the root ب-ث-ث, with the root verb بَثَّ meaning \"he scattered\" or \"he spread.\" بَثٌّ translates as \"scattering\" or \"distress,\" referring specifically to a deep sorrow or grief that compels one to share it with a companion. The connection lies in the root's concept of scattering, which here applies to the release of emotions that are difficult to contain. This term captures the human need to share profound sadness, reflecting the idea of relieving grief by expressing it, especially to Allah (ﷻ).",
  "725": "بَثَّ and related words stem from the root ب-ث-ث and, as the root verb, means \"he scattered\" or \"he spread.\" It denotes distributing something widely, often by dispersing it over an area. The connection lies in the root’s broader implications of scattering, as it can also mean releasing inner emotions, such as sorrow, that were once contained. In this way, بَثَّ encompasses both physical dispersal and the metaphorical scattering of distress, as one’s inner calm \"breaks apart\" and is spread outward.",
  "726": "بَحِيرَةٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ح-ر, with the root verb بَحَرَ meaning \"he cleaved\" or \"he made a fissure,\" often referring to a slit or cut. بَحِيرَةٌ specifically refers to a she-camel in pre-Islamic Arabia whose ear was slit as part of a ritual dedication to idols. The connection lies in the act of cutting, symbolizing separation, as the camel was excluded from normal use and devoted to idol worship. Allah (ﷻ) condemns such practices in the Qur'an, calling them baseless fabrications, and emphasizes adherence to His divine guidance over false customs and superstition.",
  "727": "بَحْرٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ح-ر, with the root verb بَحَرَ meaning \"he cleaved\" or \"he made a fissure.\" بَحْرٌ translates as \"sea\" or \"ocean,\" referring to a vast, expansive body of water. The connection lies in the concept of cleaving or cutting through, as the sea is a vast, open space with seemingly endless depth, as if \"cleaving\" through the earth itself. This term reflects the idea of boundlessness and depth, capturing both the physical vastness of the sea and the awe it inspires, symbolizing expansiveness and mystery.",
  "728": "بَخِلَ and related words stem from the root ب-خ-ل, with the root verb بَخِلَ meaning \"he was miserly\" or \"he withheld.\" The root broadly encompasses withholding or denying something that could be shared, indicating a reluctance to give or support generously. This includes not only financial resources but also knowledge, help, or any form of goodwill, reflecting a broader sense of stinginess or selfishness. In the Qur’an, بَخِلَ critiques the negative quality of selfishness, often highlighting the failure to recognize blessings as provisions meant to be shared for communal well-being.",
  "729": "بَخْسٌ and related words stem from the root ب-خ-س, with the root verb بَخَسَ meaning \"he diminished\" or \"he gave short measure.\" بَخْسٌ translates as \"deficiency\" or \"deprivation,\" particularly in the context of withholding or undervaluing what is due. The connection lies in the concept of reducing or failing to provide the rightful measure, embodying the root’s essence of diminishing value. This term emphasizes themes of fairness and honesty, as it conveys the harm caused by depriving something or someone of their full and proper due.",
  "730": "بَدا and related words stem from the root ب-د-و, with the root verb بَدَا meaning \"he or it appeared\" or \"he or it became visible.\" بَدا means \"it became clear\" or \"it appeared,\" referring to the act of something coming to light or becoming manifest. The root conveys themes of revelation, realization, and the emergence of what was hidden, emphasizing the process of truths or realities becoming apparent. بَدا reflects the unfolding of understanding, whether through personal insights or the gradual unveiling of events.",
  "731": "بَدَأَ and related words stem from the root ب-د-أ, which is the root verb meaning \"he began\" or \"he commenced,\" particularly in initiating something for the first time. This root conveys the concept of starting from an original point, often from nothing. ٱلْمُبْدِئُ, one of Allah’s (ﷻ) beautiful names, means \"The Originator\" or \"The Initiator,\" highlighting Allah’s (ﷻ) unique role in bringing all things into existence. This name highlights Allah’s (ﷻ) position as the ultimate source of creation, inspiring us to reflect on and be grateful for the life and blessings He has bestowed.",
  "732": "بَدَلًا and related words stem from the root ب-د-ل, with the root verb بَدَلَ meaning \"he exchanged\" or \"he substituted.\" بَدَلٌ means \"substitute\" or \"replacement.\" This term conveys the idea of one thing taking the place of another, directly reflecting the root’s focus on exchange and substitution. It emphasizes an intentional replacement, where one item or concept is actively chosen to stand in for another.",
  "733": "بَدَنٌ and related words stem from the root ب-د-ن, with the root verb بَدُنَ meaning \"he became stout\" or \"he became heavy in body,\" often indicating physical strength or robustness. بَدَنٌ translates as \"body,\" particularly emphasizing the physical form, mass, and substance of a being. The root carries a broader focus on the tangible, corporeal aspect, suggesting both the sturdiness and weight of the body. This term highlights the materiality and strength associated with physical existence, linking directly to the root’s themes of substantiality and physical presence.",
  "734": "بَدِيعٌ and related words stem from the root ب-د-ع, with the root verb بَدَعَ meaning \"he created without precedent.\" بَدِيعٌ conveys originality and creation with no prior example. ٱلْبَدِيعُ, one of Allah’s (ﷻ) beautiful names, means \"The Originator\" of the heavens and the earth, emphasizing His unmatched creativity and the marvel of creation without any model. This name signifies Allah (ﷻ) as the source of all originality, bringing forth unique creations that are beyond imitation and exemplifying divine innovation.",
  "735": "بَدَّلَ and related words stem from the root ب-د-ل, with the root verb بَدَلَ meaning \"he exchanged\" or \"he substituted.\" بَدَّلَ means \"he changed\" or \"he altered,\" intensifying the action of substitution. This form conveys a more deliberate and impactful alteration, often suggesting a complete or substantial change rather than a simple exchange. The connection lies in the purposeful act of transforming or replacing something, emphasizing the responsibility and effect of making such a change.",
  "736": "بَدْرٌ and related words stem from the root ب-د-ر, with the root verb بَدَرَ meaning \"he hastened,\" \"he appeared suddenly,\" or \"it rose like the full moon.\" بَدْرٌ refers to the \"full moon\" and is also the name of the site of the first major battle in Islamic history, the Battle of Badr. Just as the full moon rises suddenly and reaches its peak brightness, the Battle of Badr marked the transformative emergence of the Muslims, who triumphed under Allah’s (ﷻ) guidance despite overwhelming odds. This victory symbolized the maturity of their faith and mission, illuminating the path forward like the brilliance of a full moon.",
  "737": "بَدْوٌ and related words stem from the root ب-د-و, with the root verb بَدَا meaning \"he or it became apparent\" or \"he or it appeared.\" بَدْوٌ refers to the desert or nomadic life, emphasizing openness, exposure, and visibility. The root conveys themes of revelation and clarity, which connect to the starkness and simplicity of desert life, where little is hidden. بَدْوٌ reflects the resilience required to live in such an environment and the deep relationship with nature that fosters spiritual contemplation and a unique way of life.",
  "738": "بَراءٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ر-أ, with the root verb بَرَأَ meaning \"he became free from\" or \"he disassociated from.\" بَراءٌ means \"disassociation\" or \"freedom from obligation,\" emphasizing a state of being absolved, pure, or unburdened. The root conveys themes of separation, absolution, and purity, highlighting the act of being cleared from fault, blame, or association with wrongdoing. بَراءٌ highlights the significance of disassociating from negative attributes or actions, reflecting the importance of moral and spiritual purity.",
  "739": "بَراءَةٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ر-أ, with the root verb بَرَأَ meaning \"he became free from\" or \"he disassociated from.\" بَراءَةٌ means \"disassociation\" or \"freedom from obligation,\" emphasizing formal separation or absolution. The root conveys themes of freedom, purity, and detachment, focusing on being cleared of blame, guilt, or responsibility. بَراءَةٌ reflects the act of formally declaring freedom or dissociation, often tied to matters of justice and accountability.",
  "740": "بَرَدٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ر-د, with the root verb بَرَدَ meaning \"he became cold\" or \"he cooled.\" بَرَدٌ specifically refers to hail, the icy precipitation that falls from the sky. The root reflects more than just physical coldness, encompassing a sense of sharpness and intensity associated with coolness or ice. In the context of hail, بَرَدٌ signifies not only the coldness but also the sudden, forceful arrival of icy particles, often linked to power and awe in nature. This concept aligns with the root’s association with abrupt cooling and the invigorating, even startling, effect of coldness in various forms.",
  "741": "بَرَزُوا and related words stem from the root ب-ر-ز, with the root verb بَرَزَ meaning \"he or it emerged\" or \"he or it became prominent.\" بَرَزُوا refers to the act of coming forth, emerging, or becoming visible, suggesting something previously concealed or subtle now coming into full view. The root carries nuances of clarity and prominence, highlighting the shift from obscurity to openness or visibility. بَرَزُوا can also imply a sense of stepping forward or making a presence known, suggesting both physical emergence and figurative prominence, such as an idea or person gaining attention or distinction.",
  "742": "بَرَكَاتٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ر-ك, with the root verb بَرَكَ meaning \"he or it was firm, steady, or fixed,\" or \"he or it continued, remained, or stayed.\" بَرَكَاتٌ (plural of بَرَكَةٌ) means \"blessings\" or \"abundant blessings.\" It suggests multiple acts of divine favor that bring continuous and multiplied growth or enrichment. The root’s connection to stability and increase is reinforced here, implying blessings that provide enduring benefit. Symbolically, بَرَكَاتٌ also relates to بَرَك (a pool of water), a source of life in desert landscapes, reflecting blessings that sustain, nurture, and flourish over time.",
  "743": "بَرِقَ and related words stem from the root ب-ر-ق, with the root verb بَرَقَ meaning \"it shone, gleamed, or glistened.\" بَرِقَ specifically means \"the eyes glistened, became wide, or fixedly open due to fright,\" reflecting a reaction to something overwhelming or terrifying. The connection to the root lies in the concept of dazzling brightness or startling intensity, where brilliance or suddenness leaves one in shock or fixation. This term captures the impact of an overpowering encounter, whether physical, like the dazzling light of a flash, or emotional, like intense fear. The root conveys themes of brilliance, intensity, and the power to captivate or stun, emphasizing the transformative effect of such experiences.",
  "744": "بَرِيءٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ر-أ, with the root verb بَرَأَ meaning \"he became free from,\" \"he disassociated from,\" or \"he separated himself.\" بَرِيءٌ means \"innocent\" or \"free from guilt,\" highlighting a state of being exonerated and untainted by wrongdoing. The root conveys themes of purity, detachment, and freedom from faults, emphasizing complete separation from blame, harm, or imperfection. This reflects the idea of being unblemished and morally clear, symbolizing a state of vindication and independence from any form of guilt or responsibility for wrongdoing, while highlighting a profound sense of moral and ethical integrity.",
  "745": "بَرِيَّةٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ر-أ, with the root verb بَرَأَ meaning \"he created\" or \"he brought into being.\" بَرِيَّةٌ means \"creatures\" or \"creation,\" referring specifically to living beings brought into existence by Allah (ﷻ). The root emphasizes the act of creation that occurs without any prior model or similitude, showcasing Allah’s (ﷻ) unparalleled power and originality in originating life. بَرِيَّةٌ highlights the diversity and interconnectedness of all living beings as unique manifestations of Allah’s (ﷻ) creative power, reflecting His wisdom, care, and perfection in bringing forth creation in balance and harmony.",
  "746": "بَرٌّ and related words stem from the root ب-ر-ر, with the root verb بَرَّ meaning \"he was devoted\" or \"he was kind.\" بَرٌّ describes a person who is upright, devoted, and good-hearted, fulfilling their duties to Allah (ﷻ) and to others, embodying integrity, kindness, and faithfulness. The term also means a vast tract of land, symbolizing expansiveness; just as land stretches far, so should a person’s goodness extend generously. ٱلْبَرُّ, one of Allah’s (ﷻ) perfect names, means \"The Most Kind,\" reflecting His infinite kindness and compassion that encompass all creation, encouraging us to mirror this vastness in our own acts of goodness.",
  "747": "بَرَّأَ and related words stem from the root ب-ر-أ, with the root verb بَرَأَ meaning \"he became free from\" or \"he disassociated from.\" بَرَّأَ means \"he acquitted\" or \"he absolved,\" reflecting the act of clearing someone from blame and restoring their integrity. The connection to the root lies in the idea that disassociating from something, such as wrongdoing or imperfection, leads to being exonerated from it. This conveys themes of purity, justice, and fairness, emphasizing that true freedom from blame is achieved through separation from faults, restoring honor and trust.",
  "748": "بَرْدٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ر-د, with the root verb بَرَدَ meaning \"he became cold\" or \"he cooled.\" بَرْدٌ refers to coldness or coolness, often associated with the comfort or relief provided by a cool environment. The root concept extends beyond physical temperature, encompassing a sense of refreshment, tranquility, and relief from discomfort or heat. بَرْدٌ can therefore imply not only a physical coolness but also a calming or soothing effect, often bringing a sense of peace or alleviation.",
  "749": "بَرْزَخٌ and related words stem from the unique root ب-ر-ز-خ, which specifically denotes a barrier or divider that separates two entities. بَرْزَخٌ refers to a boundary or partition that both separates and protects, creating a distinct division between two realms or states. In the Qur’an, it signifies the barrier between life and the afterlife or between bodies of water, highlighting the concept of an unseen but impenetrable divide that maintains the integrity of each side.",
  "750": "بَرْقٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ر-ق, with the root verb بَرَقَ meaning \"it shone, gleamed, or glistened.\" بَرْقٌ specifically refers to lightning, the brilliant flash that illuminates the sky with sudden, intense brightness. The root conveys not only light but also the suddenness and power of something brief yet striking. بَرْقٌ symbolizes dazzling clarity and awe, as lightning appears abruptly, capturing attention and evoking wonder and fear.",
  "751": "بَسَرَ and related words stem from the root ب-س-ر, and as the root verb, it means \"he was quick\" or \"he acted before the proper time.\" It also means \"he frowned, contracted his face, or displayed his teeth in intense dislike or hatred.\" The connection between these meanings lies in the idea that hasty or premature actions can lead to frustration or regret, which often manifest as expressions of displeasure. This root suggests that rushing into decisions driven by emotion often results in visible signs of inner turmoil, reflecting discomfort or anxiety.",
  "752": "بَسَطَ and related words stem from the root ب-س-ط, with the root verb بَسَطَ meaning \"he spread it\" or \"he expanded, extended, and made it wide or ample.\" بَسَطَ refers to making something expansive or spread out, both physically and metaphorically. The root conveys ease, openness, abundance, and accessibility, reflecting the idea of unfolding something to its full capacity. This connection highlights how بَسَطَ symbolizes actions or conditions that allow growth, generosity, and opportunity, whether in space, resources, or intangible aspects like emotions or understanding.",
  "753": "بَسٌّ and related words stem from the root ب-س-س, with the root verb بَسَّ meaning \"he broke it, crumbled it, or bruised it,\" often used to describe crushing or breaking wheat. بَسٌّ refers to the act of breaking or crumbling into pieces, suggesting a process of reducing something to smaller, fragmented parts. The root conveys a sense of forceful breaking down, implying both physical fragmentation and, by extension, a potential loss of wholeness or cohesion. In the Qur'an, بَسٌّ evokes imagery of destruction or dispersal, symbolizing things being shattered or scattered under pressure.",
  "754": "بَسْطٌ and related words stem from the root ب-س-ط, with the root verb بَسَطَ meaning \"he spread it\" or \"he expanded, extended, or made it wide or ample.\" بَسْطٌ means \"expansion\" or \"extension,\" reflecting the root’s concept of spreading or increasing something. This word emphasizes an act of making space, abundance, or capacity, whether in physical area or abstract qualities like generosity. The root conveys openness, ease, and accessibility, connecting بَسْطٌ to the idea of providing ample room for growth, increase, and extension in all forms.",
  "755": "بَشَرٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ش-ر, with the root verb بَشَرَ meaning \"to remove the outer layer,\" and by extension, \"to make bare or expose.\" بَشَرٌ refers to human beings, emphasizing their physical form, particularly their skin (بَشَرَةٌ), symbolizing their tangible and earthly nature. This connection highlights humans' physical vulnerability and exposure, reflecting their reliance on the materials Allah (ﷻ) bestowed as blessings to maintain dignity. The root conveys ideas of openness, clarity, and exposure, symbolizing humanity's dual nature—physically limited and exposed, yet made for spiritual growth, reflecting the connection between their earthly existence and their higher purpose.",
  "756": "بَشِيرٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ش-ر, with the root verb بَشِرَ meaning \"he rejoiced\" or \"he was cheerful.\" بَشِيرٌ means \"one who brings good news\" or \"a bearer of glad tidings,\" emphasizing the role of delivering joyful news that uplifts and transforms the listener. The root conveys themes of joy, positivity, and emotional renewal, reflected in the comforting and hopeful presence of a بَشِيرٌ. Unlike مُبَشِّرٌ, which emphasizes actively spreading glad tidings, بَشِيرٌ represents a more natural and inherent source of hope and reassurance. The term reflects both the message and its emotional impact, inspiring hope and joy.",
  "757": "بَسْطَةٌ and related words stem from the root ب-س-ط, with the root verb بَسَطَ meaning \"he spread it,\" \"he expanded, extended, or made it wide or ample.\" بَسْطَةٌ builds directly on this concept, referring to \"abundance\" or \"extensiveness,\" particularly in terms of stature, strength, or provision. Just as بَسَطَ implies spreading or enlarging, بَسْطَةٌ conveys the idea of being expanded or made wide in capacity. In the Qur'an, it describes those granted increased strength, stature, knowledge, or provisions, emphasizing a divine bestowal of growth and abundance, whether physical, intellectual, or material.",
  "758": "بَصَرٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ص-ر, with the root verb بَصُرَ meaning \"he saw\" or \"he was endowed with mental perception, belief, firm belief, knowledge, understanding, intelligence, or skill.\" بَصَرٌ refers to \"the sense of sight\" and the eye but also extends to \"insight\" or \"understanding.\" This term captures both physical sight and deeper perception, where seeing is linked to awareness and clarity. The root reflects discernment, suggesting that vision encompasses sensory experience and intellectual insight, leading to the ability to distinguish truth from illusion.",
  "759": "بَصَلٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ص-ل, which is unique in that it gives rise to words associated with stripping or separating layers. بَصَلٌ refers to \"onion,\" a plant composed of multiple layers, and is closely related to تَبْصِيلٌ, meaning \"the act of stripping or peeling,\" as one would peel an onion. This root reflects the process of uncovering or removing layers, symbolizing exposure or divestment, as in the peeling away of outer surfaces to reveal what lies beneath.",
  "760": "بَصُرَتْ and related words stem from the root ب-ص-ر, with the root verb بَصُرَ meaning \"he saw\" or \"he was endowed with mental perception, belief, firm belief, knowledge, understanding, intelligence, or skill.\" بَصُرَتْ means \"she observed\" or \"she saw clearly,\" emphasizing a type of vision that includes insight and understanding. This term also sugests a deep perception that allows for clarity and discernment. The root concept here connects seeing with inner awareness, indicating that بَصُرَتْ reflects a perception that reveals or understands truth beyond surface appearances.",
  "761": "بَصِيرٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ص-ر, with the verb بَصُرَ meaning \"he saw, perceived, or discerned.\" بَصِيرٌ refers to \"one who sees clearly\" or \"one endowed with insight.\" ٱلْبَصِيرُ, one of Allah's (ﷻ) perfect names, means \"The All-Seeing,\" signifying His ability to see all things, visible and hidden. The root conveys concepts of clarity, awareness, and perception, emphasizing not just physical sight but deep understanding and discernment. This name reminds us to live with integrity, as Allah (ﷻ) sees every action, intention, and hidden aspect of our lives.",
  "762": "بَصِيرَةٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ص-ر, with the root verb بَصُرَ meaning \"he saw\" or \"he was endowed with mental perception, firm belief, knowledge, understanding, intelligence, or skill.\" بَصِيرَةٌ refers to clear insight or enlightenment—a conviction of the heart or mind grounded in knowledge and purpose. The root conveys themes of clarity, understanding, and discernment, emphasizing the ability to perceive truth deeply. بَصِيرَةٌ also means \"witness,\" as true inner clarity becomes a testimony to one’s beliefs and actions, reflecting one’s authentic inner state, whether for or against oneself.",
  "763": "بَطَرٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ط-ر, with the root verb بَطِرَ meaning \"he rejoiced greatly, or excessively, and behaved insolently and ungratefully due to wealth, displaying pride, arrogance, and boastfulness.\" بَطَرٌ refers to acting arrogantly, especially in response to blessings, showing ingratitude or boastfulness. The root conveys themes of excess, arrogance, and ungratefulness, emphasizing how unchecked pride and ingratitude distort blessings into a cause for destructive arrogance and conceit.",
  "764": "بَطَشْتُمْ and related words stem from the root ب-ط-ش, with the root verb بَطَشَ meaning \"he took hold strongly\" or \"he seized violently, often in anger.\" بَطَشْتُمْ means \"you all seized\" or \"you all struck with force.\" The root conveys themes of strength, dominance, and intensity, emphasizing acts of overpowering or subduing with might. It reflects a forceful and decisive action, often marked by aggression or retribution.",
  "765": "بَطَلَ and related words stem from the root ب-ط-ل, and as the root verb, it means \"it was or became false, untrue, wrong, incorrect, fictitious, spurious, unfounded, or unsound.\" بَطَلَ describes the process of something becoming void, ineffective, or worthless. The root conveys themes of invalidation, futility, and deception, highlighting the collapse of what was perceived as true or valuable. It reflects the idea of exposing falsehoods or stripping away illusions to reveal their lack of substance or reality.",
  "766": "بَطَنَ and related words stem from the root ب-ط-ن, and as the root verb, it means \"he or it was hidden, concealed, or inward,\" while بَطُنَ means \"he was big in the belly due to overeating.\" These meanings reflect both fullness and concealment, emphasizing what lies deep within, as the contents of the belly are hidden. In a negative sense, بَطَنَ suggests that hidden immoralities, like the concealed harm of overeating, can damage the inner self. Just as overeating causes hidden physical ailments, concealed immoralities act as spiritual diseases that corrupt from within. The root conveys themes of inwardness and depth, linking the physical and spiritual consequences of hidden actions.",
  "767": "بَطِرَتْ and related words stem from the root ب-ط-ر, with the root verb بَطِرَ meaning \"he rejoiced greatly or excessively and behaved insolently and ungratefully due to wealth, displaying pride, arrogance, and boastfulness.\" بَطِرَتْ, the feminine form used for feminine nouns, describes acting arrogantly and ungratefully, particularly in response to blessings. The root conveys themes of excessive pride, ingratitude, and recklessness, highlighting how such behavior disrupts gratitude and humility. This connection emphasizes the moral decline that arises when blessings are met with arrogance rather than thankfulness.",
  "768": "بَطْشٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ط-ش, with the root verb بَطَشَ meaning \"he took hold of it strongly\" or \"he seized violently, often in anger.\" بَطْشٌ refers to \"striking power\" or \"overwhelming force,\" emphasizing decisive strength used to dominate or subdue. The root conveys themes of power, intensity, and domination, reflecting forceful control and the ability to crush opposition. بَطْشٌ captures both physical might and authoritative power capable of swift, unyielding action that leaves no resistance.",
  "769": "بَطْشَةٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ط-ش, with the root verb بَطَشَ meaning \"he took hold of it strongly\" or \"he seized violently, assaulted in anger.\" بَطْشَةٌ refers to \"an assault\" or \"a violent seizure,\" specifically describing a single, decisive act of seizing or delivering a sudden, forceful blow. This term emphasizes not just physical strength but the intensity and abruptness of the action, capturing the idea of a swift, overpowering strike meant to subdue or decisively impact.",
  "770": "بَطْنٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ط-ن, with the root verb بَطَنَ meaning \"he or it was hidden, concealed, or inward,\" and بَطُنَ meaning \"he was big in the belly due to overeating,\" reflecting themes of fullness and concealment. بَطْنٌ refers to the \"belly\" or \"abdomen,\" symbolizing what is hidden within. Metaphorically, it represents an inner, concealed aspect, pointing to unseen depths. In pregnancy, the belly contains a blessing from Allah (ﷻ), while overeating brings hidden harm, reflecting the dual nature of what is concealed—both a source of blessing and potential harm.",
  "771": "بَعَثَ and related words stem from the root ب-ع-ث, and as the root verb, it means \"he sent,\" often referring to sending a messenger or something significant. It also means \"he roused\" or \"awakened,\" especially when stirring someone from sleep or inactivity, and it signifies \"resurrection\" in the Qur’an. ٱلْبَاعِثُ, one of Allah’s (ﷻ) perfect names, means \"The Resurrector,\" highlighting His power to raise the dead on the Day of Judgment. The root conveys themes of awakening, motion, and purpose, reflecting Allah’s (ﷻ) mercy in sending messengers to guide humanity and His ability to bring both spiritual and physical revival.",
  "772": "بَعُدَتْ and related words stem from the root ب-ع-د, with the root verb بَعُدَ meaning \"he became distant, remote, far off, or aloof\" or \"he withdrew far away or estranged himself,\" signifying physical, temporal, or spiritual distance. بَعُدَتْ is the feminine form, describing becoming distant or remote. The root conveys themes of separation and detachment, emphasizing the idea of moving away from closeness. In contrast, بَعِدَتْ means \"it perished\" or \"it was ruined,\" highlighting a final and irreversible state of destruction. While both involve distance, بَعُدَتْ focuses on becoming distant, whereas بَعِدَتْ denotes a complete and final separation.",
  "773": "بَعُوضَةٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ع-ض, with the root verb بَعَضَ meaning \"it bit or annoyed,\" referring to gnats or mosquitos. بَعَّضَ means \"he divided into parts or portions.\" بَعُوضَةٌ refers to a \"mosquito\" or \"gnat,\" a tiny creature known for taking only a small fraction of blood. The connection to the root reflects the mosquito’s nature of taking a minute portion, symbolizing smallness and insignificance. In the Qur’an, بَعُوضَةٌ highlights something seemingly trivial yet purposeful, illustrating Allah’s (ﷻ) profound wisdom in even the smallest creations.",
  "774": "بَعِيدٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ع-د, with the root verb بَعُدَ meaning \"he became distant, remote, or aloof\" or \"he withdrew far away,\" encompassing physical, temporal, and spiritual separation. بَعِيدٌ means \"distant\" or \"far,\" describing anything remote in space, time, understanding, or belief. The root implies not only physical separation, but an inner sense of estrangement from something significant. Metaphorically, بَعِيدٌ suggests a state distant from Allah (ﷻ) or morally removed, evoking detachment from clarity and closeness to truth.",
  "775": "بَعْثٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ع-ث, with the root verb بَعَثَ meaning \"he sent,\" often referring to sending a messenger or dispatching something significant. It also means \"he raised\" or \"he awakened,\" particularly in stirring someone from sleep or stillness. In the Qur’an, بَعْثٌ is associated with يَوْمُ الْبَعْثِ (the Day of Resurrection), where Allah (ﷻ) \"raises\" the dead, showcasing His power to restore life. The root conveys themes of motion, awakening, and purpose, emphasizing both physical resurrection and the act of being sent or chosen for a divine mission, highlighting Allah’s (ﷻ) authority and mercy in guiding and reviving His creation.",
  "776": "The particle بَعْدُ means \"after,\" \"following,\" or \"later,\" indicating something that occurs later in time or sequence. It emphasizes temporal distance, where one event follows another, either immediately or gradually. In the Qur'an, بَعْدُ highlights the progression of events, changes in states, or persistent behaviors, often urging reflection on what comes after divine guidance, warnings, or actions. The connection to the root ب-ع-د (to distance) lies in portraying one moment as separated from another, inviting awareness of consequences and transitions. This term reminds readers to reflect on the passage of time, the outcomes of past choices, and the importance of preparing for what follows.",
  "777": "بَعْضٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ع-ض, with the root verb بَعَّضَ meaning \"he divided into parts or portions, distinct and separate from one another.\" بَعْضٌ means \"a part of,\" \"a portion,\" or \"some,\" emphasizing separation from a larger whole. The root conveys ideas of division and distinction, suggesting both physical partitioning and abstract differentiation. It highlights the interconnected relationship between individual parts and the larger whole they collectively form, reflecting balance and order within division.",
  "778": "بَعْلٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ع-ل, with the root verb بَعَلَ meaning \"he became a husband,\" and similarly, بَعَلَتْ is used for a woman, meaning \"she became a wife.\" بَعْلٌ primarily refers to \"a husband,\" while بَعْلَةٌ signifies \"a wife.\" بَعْلٌ also denotes \"a lord, master, owner, possessor, head, chief, ruler, or person of authority,\" extending to any figure deserving of obedience. It is also associated with Ba'l, an idol made of gold worshipped in ancient cultures. The root conveys themes of authority, possession, and responsibility, highlighting a relationship of care, guidance, and obedience, whether between spouses, rulers, or other figures of authority.",
  "779": "بَغَىٰ and related words stem from the root ب-غ-ى, with the root verb بَغَىٰ meaning \"he sought, desired, or aimed for something,\" or \"he sought beyond the limits.\" In the Qur'an, it emphasizes exceeding boundaries, often linked to oppression, rebellion, or wrongful ambition. The root conveys themes of pursuit, transgression, and overreach, reflecting human tendencies to follow desires excessively. بَغَىٰ highlights the act of seeking to deviate others from the truth, leading them away from Allah’s (ﷻ) guidance, and serves as a warning against the destructive nature of unrestrained ambition or injustice.",
  "780": "بَغِىٌّ and related words stem from the root ب-غ-ى, with the root verb بَغَىٰ meaning \"he sought, desired, or aimed for something,\" or \"he sought beyond the limits.\" It also conveys meanings of injustice, oppression, and seeking excess, highlighting actions that deviate from moderation or fairness. بَغِىٌّ specifically refers to a woman who transgresses intimate boundaries, often translated as \"immoral woman\" or \"unchaste.\" The connection to the root emphasizes the act of seeking desires unlawfully or excessively, reflecting both physical transgression and moral deviation.",
  "781": "بَغْتَةٌ and related words stem from the root ب-غ-ت, with the root verb بَغَتَ meaning \"he, or it, came upon or happened suddenly and unexpectedly, without prior knowledge or cause, and surprised (him or it).\" بَغْتَةٌ refers to something occurring abruptly or without warning, emphasizing an element of surprise and immediacy. The root conveys themes of suddenness, unpredictability, and disruption, capturing events that occur without preparation and bring immediate consequences. بَغْتَةٌ highlights the limits of human foresight and the inevitability of moments that challenge complacency or certainty.",
  "782": "بَغْضَاءُ and related words stem from the root ب-غ-ض, with the root verb بَغَضَ meaning \"he or it was or became hateful\" or \"he felt aversion.\" بَغْضَاءُ refers to \"intense hatred, enmity, or aversion,\" emphasizing a deep emotional detestation that can manifest in relationships or actions. The root conveys themes of emotional rejection, antipathy, and estrangement, highlighting the breakdown of harmony and connection. بَغْضَاءُ highlights the destructive nature of hatred, reflecting the root's emphasis on the intensity of feelings that lead to division and discord.",
  "783": "بَغْيٌ and related words stem from the root ب-غ-ى, with the root verb بَغَىٰ meaning \"he sought, desired, or sought beyond the limits.\" بَغْيٌ means \"exceeding limits\" or \"the desire to exceed limits,\" referring to overstepping moral or legal boundaries through excessive desire or unjust ambition. The root conveys themes of pursuit, transgression, and injustice, emphasizing wrongful actions driven by excessive or selfish motives. In the Qur'an, بَغْيٌ is strongly condemned, particularly when it involves oppression, rebellion, or the pursuit of power through unjust means, highlighting it as a severe moral failing.",
  "784": "بَقَرٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ق-ر, with the root verb بَقَرَ meaning \"he split or cut open\" or \"he made wide or ample.\" بَقَرٌ refers to \"cattle\" or \"oxen,\" encompassing both male and female. While other terms for cattle exist, بَقَرٌ is used in the Qur'an with a connection to its root meaning of \"splitting.\" This is reflected in how the polytheists of Arabia divided livestock into lawful and unlawful categories and in the prohibitions placed on the Children of Israel. Additionally, male oxen, often altered to prevent reproduction and used exclusively for labor, further emphasize the concept of splitting or division, reinforcing the root's inherent significance.",
  "785": "بَقَرَةٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ق-ر, with the root verb بَقَرَ meaning \"he split or cut open,\" or \"he made wide or ample.\" بَقَرٌ refers to cattle or oxen in general, while بَقَرَةٌ specifically denotes a \"cow.\" The act of splitting relates to the animal’s belly, often in the context of sacrifice or provision. In the Qur'an, this word reflects the root’s concept of splitting both literally and symbolically. In the story of the Children of Israel, they were commanded to sacrifice and divide a cow, embodying splitting as an act of obedience. Similarly, in the king's dream, the division of resources through strategic planning prepared Egypt for famine, emphasizing how splitting serves as a means of provision and survival.",
  "786": "بَقِيَ and related words stem from the root ب-ق-ي, and as the root verb, it means \"he remained,\" \"he endured,\" or \"he stayed behind.\" It conveys the concept of something persisting or existing after others have ceased or been removed. The root emphasizes continuity, preservation, and resilience, contrasting what is fleeting with what endures. بَقِيَ highlights the enduring value of things that persist over time, symbolizing timeless worth and resilience in the face of change.",
  "787": "بَقِيَّةٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ق-ي, with the root verb بَقِيَ meaning \"he remained,\" \"he endured,\" or \"he stayed behind.\" بَقِيَّةٌ refers to \"the remainder,\" \"the rest,\" or \"something left over,\" focusing on what is preserved or remains after other parts are removed or used. The root reflects themes of endurance, value, and preservation, emphasizing how remnants hold significance, continuity, and resilience, serving as lasting symbols even after much has passed or changed.",
  "788": "بَقْلٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ق-ل, with the root verb بَقَلَ meaning \"it appeared\" or \"it sprouted.\" بَقْلٌ refers to \"vegetables,\" \"herbs,\" or \"greens\"—plants that grow directly from the ground, distinct from shrubs or trees, and are typically seasonal. The root concept of “appearing” connects to the way these plants sprout visibly from the earth in their season, symbolizing renewal, sustenance, and the earth’s bounty. These plants, which emerge quickly and briefly, emphasize a cycle of provision and growth that appears only at appointed times.",
  "789": "بَكَتْ and related words stem from the root ب-ك-ى, with the root verb بَكَىٰ meaning \"he cried\" or \"he wept.\" بَكَتْ translates to \"she or it cried\" or \"she or it wept,\" expressing sorrow, vulnerability, or emotional release. This root suggests more than simple crying, linking tears to inner grief or longing. بَكَتْ also appears metaphorically, describing entities that are grammatically feminine in Arabic, such as the sky, as though they are weeping.",
  "790": "بَكَّةُ and related words stem from the root ب-ك-ك, with the root verb بَكَّ meaning \"he crowded\" or \"he pressed closely.\" بَكَّةُ is an ancient name for Mecca, the holy city where pilgrims gather in large numbers. The connection lies in the crowdedness of the sacred site, not only during pilgrimage but throughout the year, symbolizing unity and devotion. The root meaning also highlights Mecca’s significance as a divinely appointed destination for pilgrims since its inception.",
  "791": "بَلَاءٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ل-و, with the root verb بَلَا meaning \"he tried, proved, or tested,\" referring to testing in a general sense to reveal the nature of someone or something. بَلَاءٌ refers to a trial or test, often indicating a challenge that tests endurance, faith, or character. This term can encompass both hardships and blessings, as each serves as a means of examining a person’s response and resilience. The root meaning of \"smelting\" enhances this concept, suggesting that trials function as a refining process, exposing and purifying inner qualities, much like metal is purified to reveal its true essence.",
  "792": "بَلاغٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ل-غ, with the root verb بَلَغَ meaning \"he reached\" or \"he attained.\" بَلاغٌ refers to the act of delivering, conveying, or communicating a message, with an emphasis on clear and effective transmission. Root meanings also suggest the idea of reaching completeness, implying that بَلاغٌ involves fully delivering a message so that it reaches its intended purpose or audience. This term, therefore, captures both the process of communication and the completeness or eloquence with which the message is conveyed.",
  "793": "بَلَدٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ل-د, with the root verb بَلَدَ meaning \"he remained, stayed, abode, or dwelt in a place.\" بَلَدٌ refers to a country, land, region, city, town, or village, encompassing any portion of the earth, whether cultivated, inhabited, or desolate. The connection to the root verb بَلَدَ emphasizes a place where one settles or remains, capturing the idea of a designated area where people live, work, and belong. This contrasts with مَدِينَةٌ, which specifically denotes a city or town with organized and structured aspects of populated areas.",
  "794": "بَلَغَ and related words stem from the root ب-ل-غ, and as the root verb, it means \"he reached\" or \"he attained.\" بَلَغَ conveys the idea of arriving at a certain point, whether physically, as in reaching a destination, metaphorically, as in achieving a goal, or in terms of maturity. The root emphasizes completeness and fulfillment, suggesting that one has reached an intended end or state, whether in age, knowledge, or purpose. This term embodies the concept of attaining full development or achieving a definitive outcome.",
  "795": "بَلَوْنَا and related words stem from the root ب-ل-و, with the root verb بَلَا meaning \"he tried, proved, or tested,\" referring to testing in a general sense to reveal the nature of someone or something. بَلَوْنَا means \"We tested\" and generally refers to Allah’s (ﷻ) broad, ongoing testing of His creation to assess their faith, patience, or resilience. This term emphasizes the experience of undergoing trials, focusing on the individual’s response and growth. The root also includes \"smelting,\" as in purifying metal through intense heat—each test, like smelting, refines and reveals one’s true essence.",
  "796": "بَلِيغٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ل-غ, with the root verb بَلَغَ meaning \"he reached\" or \"he attained,\" and بَلَّغَ meaning \"he caused to reach\" or \"he conveyed.\" بَلِيغٌ refers to speech or communication that is sharp, penetrating, and highly effective in conveying meaning. It describes words that are impactful and persuasive, reaching deeply into the hearts of listeners. This term suggests language that is both clear and purposeful, producing a powerful effect by reaching its audience with precision and intent. Root meanings emphasize that بَلِيغٌ signifies eloquence that achieves its purpose, leaving a lasting impression.",
  "797": "بَلَّغْتَ and related words stem from the root ب-ل-غ, with the root verb بَلَغَ meaning \"he reached\" or \"he attained,\" and بَلَّغَ meaning \"he caused to reach\" or \"he conveyed.\" بَلَّغْتَ means \"you conveyed\" or \"you delivered,\" emphasizing the deliberate act of delivering a message or information so it reaches its intended destination clearly and faithfully. The term highlights the responsibility of accurate and complete communication, ensuring the message is conveyed without distortion or omission. It reflects intentionality and purpose, emphasizing the importance of effective delivery in fulfilling the duty of conveying truth or guidance.",
  "798": "بَلْدَةٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ل-د, with the root verb بَلَدَ meaning \"he remained, stayed, abode, or dwelt in a place.\" بَلْدَةٌ represents land or territory, encompassing various forms of inhabited or desolate areas, such as a town, village, or broader region. Unlike مَدِينَةٌ, which specifically denotes a city or town with organized and structured aspects of populated areas, بَلْدَةٌ suggests a more flexible notion of space, highlighting themes of residence and rootedness. This term, therefore, captures the idea of a settled, lasting place.",
  "799": "بَنَانٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ن-ن, with the root verb أَبَنَّ meaning \"he remained, continued, stayed, or abode in a place.\" The root conveys ideas of continuity, connection, and stability. بَنَانٌ specifically refers to the fingertips, symbolizing precision, dexterity, and the ability to grasp and hold. The connection to the root lies in the fingertips' role in maintaining contact, providing stability, and remaining in place to achieve delicate or purposeful tasks. This reflects the intricate balance of strength and precision in the fingertips, highlighting their significance in both physical and symbolic terms as tools of human capability and expression, demonstrating the wisdom in their creation.",
  "800": "بَنَىٰ and related words stem from the root ب-ن-ي, and as the root verb, it means \"he built, framed, or constructed.\" بَنَىٰ refers to the action of building or constructing something, whether a physical structure or in a metaphorical sense, such as building relationships, families, or communities. The term emphasizes creating or forming something with a solid foundation, symbolizing strength, stability, and continuity, whether in material or abstract forms.",
  "801": "بَنَّاءٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ن-ي, with the root verb بَنَىٰ meaning \"he built, framed, or constructed.\" The root encompasses the ideas of assembling, raising, or creating something with intention and precision. بَنَّاءٌ means \"builder\" or \"architect,\" referring to someone actively engaged in constructing physical structures, such as homes or buildings. Conceptually, it extends to signify one who establishes or fortifies something, whether tangible or abstract, emphasizing skill, effort, and purpose. This ties to the broader root meanings of formation, growth, and fostering stability, reflecting the builder’s role in laying foundations that support and endure.",
  "802": "بَهِيجٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ه-ج, with the root verb بَهَجَ meaning \"he, or it, became beautiful\" or \"radiant and joyful.\"  بَهِيجٌ means \"beautiful\" or \"radiantly joyful\" and is often used to describe plants that appear vibrant and lush, as well as people with a bright, joyful demeanor. This root also conveys ideas of brightness, delight, and cheerful appearance. This word reflects how beauty and brightness naturally inspire joy, capturing the uplifting effect of something visually pleasing and full of life.",
  "803": "بَهِيمَةٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ه-م, referring to animals, particularly livestock or creatures of land and sea, characterized by their lack of complex reasoning or speech. The root conveys notions of simplicity, uniformity, and obscurity. Related terms like بَهْمٌ refer to young, dependent animals, symbolizing innocence and reliance, while بَهِيمٌ denotes purity and completeness, such as an unblemished color or the total darkness of night. The term بَهِيمَةٌ reflects the instinctive and straightforward nature of animals, emphasizing their purity, dependence, and essential role in maintaining the balance of creation.",
  "804": "بَهْجَةٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ه-ج, with the root verb بَهَجَ meaning \"he, or it, became beautiful\" or \"cheerful and bright.\" بَهْجَةٌ means \"beauty\" or \"splendor,\" refers to the vivid beauty of nature, like plants that appear lush and glowing, or the joyful expression on a person’s face. This term conveys the idea of something that brings happiness through its vivid, inspiring beauty, reflecting the impact of natural radiance on the human spirit.",
  "805": "بَوَارٌ and related words stem from the root ب-و-ر, with the root verb بَارَ meaning \"he perished.\" بَوَارٌ refers to total ruin, destruction, or perdition, emphasizing an irreversible decay or collapse. This root also conveys the sense of something becoming barren, stagnant, or lifeless, capturing a state of complete futility. Unlike بُورٌ, which can suggest a gradual decline, بَوَارٌ implies a swift and final state of devastation, highlighting a catastrophic end with no hope of recovery, often due to neglect or inherent futility.",
  "806": "بَوَّأَ and related words stem from the root ب-و-أ, with the root verb بَاءَ meaning \"he returned\" or \"he withdrew.\" بَوَّأَ builds on this by meaning \"to settle\" or \"to place someone in a dwelling,\" suggesting an act of providing someone with a stable, prepared place. This placement emphasizes a secure and deliberate settlement, where one can find stability, comfort, and a sense of belonging. The connection to the root reflects the idea of giving someone a place to return to, suited to their needs and intended for their peace and establishment.",
  "807": "بَياتٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ي-ت, with the root verb بَاتَ meaning \"he spent the night\" or \"he stayed overnight,\" and also implying actions that occur \"at night.\" The term بَياتٌ refers to \"a coming upon the enemy by night\" or \"a sudden attack during the night,\" emphasizing stealth and strategic advantage under the cover of darkness. This connection to the root highlights the association with nighttime activity, secrecy, and precise timing, reflecting calculated actions when the enemy is unsuspecting or vulnerable.",
  "808": "بَيَانٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ي-ن, with the root verb بَانَ meaning \"it became separated, severed, disunited, or cut off,\" or \"it became apparent, manifest, evident, or clear\" or \"it became distinct,\" implying separation from others. بَيَانٌ means \"clarity,\" \"expression,\" or \"explanation,\" focusing on the act of making something understandable or revealing it in a clear, distinct way. The root concept highlights separating truth from falsehood or illuminating something hidden, capturing the essence of communication that brings clarity and understanding.",
  "809": "بَيَّتَ and related words stem from the root ب-ي-ت, with the root verb بَاتَ meaning \"he spent the night,\" or \"he stayed overnight,\" and can also imply actions that occurs \"at night.\" بَيَّتَ means \"he carried out an action by night\" or \"he performed the affair at night.\" When used with a direct object pronoun, as in بَيَّتَهُ (him) or بَيَّتَهُمْ (them), it means \"he attacked him by night\" or \"he ambushed them secretly at night.\" بَيَّتَ implies actions that are carefully planned or executed under the cover of darkness, away from public knowledge. It can refer to secretive or deliberate planning, with a focus on preparation, forethought, and concealment.",
  "810": "بَيَّنَ and related words stem from the root ب-ي-ن, with the root verb بَانَ meaning \"it became separated, severed, disunited, or cut off,\" or \"it became apparent, manifest, evident, or clear\" or \"it became distinct,\" implying separation from others. بَيَّنَ means \"he clarified\" or \"he made clear,\" emphasizing the action of explaining or revealing something in a way that removes ambiguity. The root conveys the idea of making distinctions or bringing out details, highlighting the act of illuminating truth by separating it from confusion or obscurity.",
  "811": "بَيِّنٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ي-ن, with the root verb بَانَ meaning \"it became separated, severed, disunited, or cut off,\" or \"it became apparent, manifest, evident, or clear\" or \"it became distinct,\" implying separation from others. بَيِّنٌ means \"clear\" or \"evident,\" frequently describing something obvious or unmistakable. The root suggests the idea of distinctness, as if something stands out plainly from confusion or ambiguity, embodying clarity in a way that leaves no doubt.",
  "812": "بَيِّنَةٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ي-ن, with the root verb بَانَ meaning \"it became separated, severed, disunited, or cut off,\" or \"it became apparent, manifest, evident, or clear\" or \"it became distinct,\" implying separation from others. بَيِّنَةٌ means \"clear evidence\" or \"proof,\" referring to something that decisively demonstrates or reveals the truth. The root also conveys the idea of something standing apart in clarity, as if separated from confusion or obscurity, emphasizing evidence that is unmistakable and leaves no room for doubt.",
  "813": "بَيْتٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ي-ت, with the root verb بَاتَ meaning \"he spent the night\" or \"he stayed overnight,\" and also implying actions occurring \"at night.\" بَيْتٌ refers to a house, dwelling, or tent, extending to a place of residence or shelter, symbolizing security and rest. It also describes the Kaaba in Mecca, \"بَيْتُ الله\" (the House of Allah ﷻ), highlighting its role as a sacred sanctuary for worship. The connection to the root emphasizes a place of rest, protection, and tranquility, paralleling the night’s association with repose. This highlights the house as a sanctuary—both a physical refuge and a profound place of devotion.",
  "814": "بَيْضٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ي-ض, with the root verb بَاضَ meaning \"it laid eggs.\" بَيْضٌ refers to eggs and also conveys the idea of a container or receptacle, as an egg encloses and nurtures life within. This term embodies both the fragility and protective nature of an egg, symbolizing a vessel for creation, potential, and new beginnings. Its delicate, enclosed form represents purity and life, often associated with something hidden, untouched, and shielded from impurities. These qualities reflect inner beauty and carefully preserved innocence, emphasizing the egg's role as a metaphor for both physical and symbolic renewal.",
  "815": "بَيْعٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ي-ع, with the root verb بَاعَ meaning \"he sold,\" and بَايَعَ meaning \"he exchanged commodities.\" بَيْعٌ means \"sale\" or \"trade,\" referring specifically to the act of selling, buying, or exchanging goods. The root concept emphasizes mutual benefit and the reciprocal exchange of value, where each party offers something to obtain something else. This term reflects the foundational principles of fairness, agreement, and mutual advantage in economic and social interactions, highlighting the balance and cooperation inherent in such exchanges.",
  "816": "The noun بَيْنَ means \"between,\" \"among,\" \"before,\" \"in front of,\" or \"ahead of,\" referring to spatial, temporal, or conceptual separation. It is often used in the Qur’an to describe distinctions between people, times, or concepts, emphasizing separations or comparisons. It also appears in forms like مِنْ بَيْنِ (\"from between\") or بَيْنِي وَبَيْنَكَ (\"between me and you\"), indicating a physical or metaphorical gap or distance. From the root ب-ي-ن, with the root verb بَانَ meaning \"it became apparent\" or \"it became distinct,\" the connection emphasizes separation that clarifies boundaries.",
  "817": "بُخْلٌ and related words stem from the root ب-خ-ل, with the root verb بَخِلَ meaning \"he was miserly\" or \"he withheld.\" بُخْلٌ signifies \"stinginess\" or \"miserliness,\" capturing the trait of an unwillingness to share or extend generosity. This term embodies a consistent attitude of withholding what could benefit others, whether material resources or other forms of support. In the Qur’an, بُخْلٌ is often associated with a failure to use blessings as intended for communal good, highlighting the moral deficiency of greed and self-centeredness.",
  "818": "بُرُوجٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ر-ج, with the root verb بَرَجَ meaning \"he became prominent\" or \"he became visible.\" بُرُوجٌ, the plural of بُرْجٌ, refers to towers, fortresses, or constellations—structures that stand out and are elevated. The term emphasizes visibility, prominence, and protection, as these structures are built to be noticeable and defendable. In the Qur'an, بُرُوجٌ describes celestial fortresses or signs in the heavens, showcasing the power and majesty of Allah’s (ﷻ) creation.",
  "819": "بُرِّزَتْ and related words stem from the root ب-ر-ز, with the root verb بَرَزَ meaning \"he became apparent,\" \"he became manifest,\" or \"he appeared openly.\" بُرِّزَتْ is a passive form, meaning \"it was made manifest\" or \"it was brought forth.\" The root conveys visibility and emergence, suggesting that something previously hidden is now exposed. بُرِّزَتْ implies an unveiling or revelation with impact, highlighting something brought to light in a striking or deliberate manner.",
  "820": "بُرْهَانٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ر-ه-ن, with the root verb بَرْهَنَ meaning \"he proved\" or \"he demonstrated,\" emphasizing the act of making something clear through evidence. بُرْهَانٌ refers to \"clear evidence\" or \"decisive proof,\" something undeniable in its clarity. The connection lies in the idea of making truth both firm and transparent, as proving something renders it unquestionably established. In the Qur'an, بُرْهَانٌ often signifies divine proof or guidance, showing truth with an unmistakable clarity that demands acceptance.",
  "821": "بُسَّتْ and related words stem from the root ب-س-س, with the root verb بَسَّ meaning \"he broke it, crumbled it, or bruised it,\" often applied to the crushing of wheat. بُسَّتْ is a passive form, meaning \"it was crushed\" or \"it was broken down.\" This word evokes the imagery of something forcefully shattered or reduced to fragments. In the Qur'an, بُسَّتْ describes the scattering or pulverizing of mountains, symbolizing complete destruction or dispersal under immense force, leaving no structure intact.",
  "822": "بُشِّرَ and related words stem from the root ب-ش-ر, with the root verb بَشِرَ meaning \"he rejoiced\" or \"he was cheerful,\" and بَشَّرَ meaning \"he gave glad tidings\" or \"he informed of good news.\" بُشِّرَ is a passive form, meaning \"he was given glad tidings\" or \"he was informed of good news.\" This form emphasizes not only the reception of positive news but also its uplifting and transformative effect on the recipient. The joy associated with بُشِّرَ brings emotional relief, hope, and encouragement, reflecting the root's themes of joy, renewal, and positivity. It highlights how receiving glad tidings inspires comfort and optimism, extending beyond the mere delivery of information.",
  "823": "بُشْرًا and related words stem from the root ب-ش-ر, with the root verb بَشِرَ meaning \"he rejoiced\" or \"he was cheerful.\" بُشْرًا refers to \"glad tidings\" or \"good news,\" emphasizing the uplifting and positive nature of the message. This term conveys more than mere information—it carries a promise or assurance that brings immediate joy, relief, and hope. While بُشْرًا focuses on the present impact of good news, brightening the spirit and inspiring optimism, it contrasts with بُشْرَى, which often implies more enduring and transformative blessings. The connection lies in the root’s themes of joy, renewal, and emotional upliftment, reflecting the profound ability of good news to inspire hope and positivity.",
  "824": "بُشْرَى and related words stem from the root ب-ش-ر, with the root verb بَشِرَ meaning \"he rejoiced\" or \"he was cheerful.\" بُشْرَى refers to \"glad tidings\" or \"good news,\" often carrying a deep and lasting impact, such as divine promises or blessings. Unlike بُشْرًا, which emphasizes immediate joy, بُشْرَى conveys news that transforms, bringing profound reassurance and enduring hope. In the Qur'an, بُشْرَى frequently signifies glad tidings of divine favor, fulfillment, or promises, reflecting a joy rooted in Allah’s (ﷻ) mercy and guidance, with lasting spiritual significance.",
  "825": "بُعْثِرَ and related words stem from the root ب-ع-ث-ر, with the verb بَعْثَرَ meaning \"he took, drew, or pulled a thing out and exposed it\" or \"he raised and scattered it, turning it over.\" The root conveys themes of exposure, upheaval, and scattering, involving both extracting hidden things and dispersing them. بُعْثِرَ, as a passive form, means \"that which is exposed.\" In the Qur'an, it describes the uncovering of graves or hidden secrets on the Day of Judgment, emphasizing the revelation of all that was once concealed, with no place left for anything to remain hidden.",
  "826": "بُعْدَ and related words stem from the root ب-ع-د, with the root verb بَعُدَ meaning \"he became distant, remote, or aloof,\" or \"he withdrew far away,\" signifying physical, temporal, or spiritual distance. بُعْدَ means \"the distance of\" or \"the remoteness of\" when used in construct, highlighting separation or a gap between things with a specific focus. In contrast, بُعْدًا is an emphatic form, translated in the Qur’an as \"away with,\" expressing a strong condemnation or curse, invoking the complete removal or destruction of something. This dual usage reflects both the neutral idea of distance and its intensified, negative connotation.",
  "827": "بُقْعَةٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ق-ع, with the root verb بَقَعَ meaning \"he spotted\" or \"he stained.\" بُقْعَةٌ refers to a \"spot,\" \"patch,\" or \"piece of land.\" In the Qur'an, بُقْعَةٌ is used to describe a \"blessed spot,\" highlighting locations where significant divine events took place. This connects to the root meaning by implying that Allah (ﷻ) “marks” certain places on Earth as special or sanctified. Just as a spot or stain draws attention on a surface, these \"blessed spots\" stand out due to their unique purpose and spiritual significance.",
  "828": "بُكِيًّا and related words stem from the root ب-ك-ى, with the root verb بَكَىٰ meaning \"he cried\" or \"he wept.\" بُكِيًّا means \"weeping\" or \"crying,\" describing the act of shedding tears as an outward release of sorrow, regret, or deep emotion. This root conveys vulnerability and the human need to express inner pain or longing. In its broader context, بُكِيًّا reflects not only physical tears but a range of deep emotional expressions such as empathy, humility, sincerity, and more.",
  "829": "بُكْرَة and related words stem from the root ب-ك-ر, with the root verb بَكَرَ meaning \"he did something early,\" \"he went forth early in the morning, in the first part of the day,\" or \"he hastened.\" بُكْرَة means \"early morning,\" specifically referring to that particular time of day when activities begin, reflecting the time itself rather than the act of beginning early. The root conveys themes of renewal, readiness, and the importance of early beginnings, symbolizing the energy and promise associated with starting early, when one is focused and alert, setting a purposeful tone for the day.",
  "830": "بُنَىٌّ and related words stem from the root ب-ن-ي, with the root verb بَنَىٰ meaning \"he built, framed, or constructed.\" بُنَىٌّ is a form of ابْنٌ, meaning \"little son\" or \"dear son.\" Used as a term of endearment, it affectionately addresses a young son, reflecting care and closeness in family relationships. The root’s sense of \"building\" connects here to nurturing bonds within the family, where approaching a child with gentleness rather than anger builds harmony. This term highlights the wisdom of fostering love and understanding, especially in important discussions.",
  "831": "بُنْيانٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ن-ي, with the root verb بَنَىٰ meaning \"he built, framed, or constructed.\" بُنْيانٌ refers to a \"structure\" or \"building,\" describing something constructed, whether a physical building or a metaphorical structure, such as a resilient community or system. The word emphasizes strength and stability, highlighting that both physical and abstract structures require a solid foundation to endure and remain steadfast. ",
  "832": "بُهِتَ and related words stem from the root ب-ه-ت, with the root verb بَهَتَ meaning \"he was confused, perplexed, or amazed, unable to see his right course.\" بُهِتَ is a passive form meaning \"he was made to be confounded\" or \"struck dumb,\" describing someone silenced by an external shock or unexpected revelation, left mentally paralyzed and unable to respond. The root also conveys the idea of being stunned into silence, overwhelmed by a sudden realization.",
  "833": "بُهْتَانٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ه-ت, with the root verb بَهَتَ meaning \"he was confused, perplexed, or amazed, unable to see his right course.\" بُهْتَانٌ means \"slander\" or \"false accusation,\" referring to a shocking, baseless claim meant to harm or malign someone’s character. The root’s sense of leaving one speechless or bewildered highlights the severe impact of slander, which disorients and devastates the accused, leaving them defenseless and confused by the unexpected attack.",
  "834": "بُورٌ and related words stem from the root ب-و-ر, with the root verb بَارَ meaning \"he perished.\" بُورٌ signifies something in a state of ruin or gradual failure. It reflects the condition of being bad, spoiled, or devoid of good, and in classical Arabic, it can refer to land or markets that have become barren or lifeless, emphasizing a process of becoming useless over time rather than instant destruction.",
  "835": "بِئْرٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ءَ-ر, with the root verb بَأَرَ meaning \"he dug a well.\" بِئْرٌ translates as \"well\" or \"pit.\" The connection lies in the act of excavating to access essential resources, reflecting the root’s themes of depth, persistence, and establishment. This term highlights the effort involved in reaching a vital source beneath the surface, symbolizing resourcefulness and the human drive to create access to life-sustaining provisions.",
  "836": "بِئْسَ and related words stem from the root ب-أ-س, with the root verb بَئِسَ meaning \"he was mighty or strong in war\" as well as \"he was wretched,\" \"suffered misfortune,\" or \"was distressed.\" بِئْسَ is used as an expression of strong condemnation, meaning \"how evil is...\" The connection lies in emphasizing the intensity of disapproval, reflecting the root’s association with misfortune and distress. بِئْسَ serves as a rhetorical device to convey the severity of morally reprehensible actions, highlighting lessons on right and wrong through impactful language.",
  "837": "بِدَارٌ and related words stem from the root ب-د-ر, with the root verb بَدَرَ meaning \"he hastened\" or \"he did something quickly.\" بِدَارٌ signifies \"haste\" or \"prompt action.\" While the root conveys swiftness and a readiness to act, it also encompasses the idea of rashness or impulsive action that may lead to harm if not checked by wisdom. This word can therefore imply an eagerness that disregards consequences, urging caution against actions driven by self-interest or greed that negatively impact others.",
  "838": "بِدْعٌ and related words stem from the root ب-د-ع, with the root verb بَدَعَ meaning \"he originated,\" \"he created without precedent,\" or \"he introduced something new.\" بِدْعٌ translates to \"innovation\" or \"something unprecedented,\" emphasizing originality and the creation of something distinct from what existed before. The root conveys the concept of bringing forth something entirely novel, highlighting both the act of initiating and the uniqueness of what is introduced.",
  "839": "بِرٌّ and related words stem from the root ب-ر-ر, with the root verb بَرَّ meaning \"he was devoted\" or \"he was kind.\" بِرٌّ signifies goodness, piety, or righteousness in one’s conduct. This term conveys moral excellence, emphasizing loyalty, integrity, and compassion, particularly in fulfilling obligations with kindness and gentleness, especially toward parents. The root suggests steadfastness in these virtues, making بِرٌّ a continual expression of devotion and righteousness.",
  "840": "بِساطٌ and related words stem from the root ب-س-ط, with the root verb بَسَطَ meaning \"he spread it,\" \"he expanded, extended, or made it wide or ample.\" بِساطٌ means \"something spread out and even\" or \"wide and spacious,\" often referring to a surface like a carpet or mat. This term conveys the idea of something laid flat, accessible, and ample, offering a sense of comfort, ease, and hospitality. In classical Arabic, بِساطٌ symbolizes an inviting, expansive surface that accommodates others, often linked to generosity and openness.",
  "841": "بِضاعَةٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ض-ع, with the root verb بَضَعَ meaning \"he cut\" or \"he divided.\" بِضاعَةٌ refers to a small, humble amount of merchandise, often perceived as modest or of limited worth. The root concept of division or separation suggests that بِضاعَةٌ represents something set aside or distinct from a larger whole, reflecting its typically modest size or perceived insignificance. This term conveys an item or portion that, while humble, serves a practical purpose, symbolizing simple sustenance or limited resources.",
  "842": "بِضْعٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ض-ع, with the root verb بَضَعَ meaning \"he cut\" or \"he divided.\" بِضْعٌ means \"a few\" or \"a number between three and nine,\" indicating a limited but notable portion. This term conveys an indefinite smallness, reflecting a sense of division or segmentation from a larger whole. It emphasizes that this quantity, while minor, is distinct and deliberately measured, often used in contexts where a specific but small number is set apart from a greater total.",
  "843": "بِطَانَةٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ط-ن, with the root verb بَطَنَ meaning \"he or it was hidden, concealed, or inward.\" بِطَانَةٌ refers to the \"lining\" or \"close confidants,\" derived from the inner layer of clothing that touches the skin. This term emphasizes intimacy and confidentiality, as a trusted friend or associate, like a garment’s inner lining, is privy to one’s deepest thoughts, secrets, and plans. بِطَانَةٌ reflects a close, inward relationship that offers both protection and the privilege of inner knowledge, symbolizing trust and discretion.",
  "844": "بِغَاءُ and related words stem from the root ب-غ-ى, with the root verb بَغَىٰ meaning \"he sought, desired, or aimed for something,\" or \"he sought beyond the limits.\" بِغَاءُ specifically refers to the act of prostitution, reflecting a pursuit of personal gain through illicit means. The root conveys themes of seeking, transgression, and exceeding boundaries, emphasizing how بِغَاءُ represents a form of desire that violates moral and social limits, turning pursuit into an act of serious transgression.",
  "845": "بِغَالٌ and related words stem from the root ب-غ-ل, with the root verb بَغُلَ meaning \"he pretended to be unintelligent or became submissive and humble.\" بِغَالٌ refers to \"mules,\" hybrid animals born from a horse and donkey. Mules are prized for their strength and endurance in carrying loads and transportation. Despite their intelligence and independence, they exhibit loyalty and cooperation when treated with respect and kindness, reflecting the root meanings of submissiveness and humbleness. This connection highlights their adaptability and willingness to serve under thoughtful guidance.",
  "846": "بِكْرٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ك-ر, with the root verb بَكَرَ meaning \"he did something early,\" \"he went forth early in the morning, in the first part of the day; or between the time of the prayer of daybreak and sunrise,\" or \"he hastened.\" بِكْرٌ refers to things that are \"first\" or in their original state, such as a virgin, a firstborn child, a young animal, or something untouched, like an unpierced pearl or a cow that has not conceived. The root conveys themes of primacy, freshness, and newness, reflecting the idea of being at the beginning or in an unaltered condition, much like the verb’s emphasis on starting early or being first in time.",
  "847": "بِناءٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ن-ي, with the root verb بَنَىٰ meaning \"he built, framed, or constructed.\" بِناءٌ can refer to a \"roof\" or \"ceiling,\" such as that of a house or chamber. It also means the \"act of building\" or \"construction,\" describing the process of creating or forming something. The term emphasizes both the protective covering and the action of building itself, highlighting stability and shelter. Remarkably, Allah (ﷻ) uses this word in the Qur'an to refer to the sky as a ceiling, highlighting His ongoing act of maintaining and sustaining it for our benefit.",
  "848": "بِنْتٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ن-ي, with the root verb بَنَىٰ meaning \"he built, framed, or constructed.\" The root conveys notions of assembling, forming, and strengthening, which connect deeply to the meaning of بِنْتٌ, meaning \"daughter.\" A daughter symbolizes an integral part of family lineage and continuity, much like a key component in a carefully constructed structure. She represents the nurturing and perpetuation of family heritage, contributing to its stability and endurance.",
  "849": "بِيَعٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ي-ع, with the root verb بَاعَ meaning \"he sold,\" and بَايَعَ meaning \"he exchanged commodities.\" بِيَعٌ (plural of بِيعَةٌ) refers to churches, specifically places of worship for Christians. The connection to the root reflects the concept of dedication or commitment, much like a sale or exchange involves offering something valuable. In this context, a church symbolizes a space consecrated for worship and devotion, representing a profound spiritual commitment and the offering of oneself in service to faith.",
  "850": "The word تَاللّٰهِ combines the preposition تَ (meaning \"by\") with \"Allah\" (ﷻ), forming an oath meaning \"By Allah!\" This expression intensifies a declaration, conveying strong emphasis or solemn swearing by Allah (ﷻ), often with even greater force than وَاللَّهِ (\"By Allah\"). It reflects deep conviction, sincerity, and seriousness, used to assert truthfulness or highlight the gravity of a situation.",
  "851": "تَّائِبُونَ and related words stem from the root ت-و-ب, with the root verb تَابَ meaning \"he repented\" or \"he returned [to God] from sin to obedience.\" تَّائِبُونَ means \"ones who repent\" or \"repentants.\" The root conveys not just a change in behavior but a heartfelt return and realignment with one’s purpose, emphasizing \"turning back\" to a state of purity and devotion. تَّائِبُونَ highlights a continuous, sincere effort to return to Allah (ﷻ), presenting repentance as a renewing process and a journey of humility, where one seeks forgiveness and commits to Allah's (ﷻ) guidance.",
  "852": "تَائِبَاتٌ and related words stem from the root ت-و-ب, with the root verb تَابَ meaning \"he repented\" or \"he returned [to God] from sin to obedience.\" تَائِبَاتٌ means \"repentant women\" or \"ones who repent.\" The root emphasizes a heartfelt return, symbolizing a transformative process of moving from wrongdoing to purity and devotion. تَائِبَاتٌ highlights women who are actively engaged in repentance, reflecting humility and a sincere commitment to align their lives with Allah's (ﷻ) guidance.",
  "853": "تَابَ and related words stem from the root ت-و-ب, and as the root verb, it means \"he repented\" or \"he returned [to God] from sin to obedience.\" This term also includes Allah’s (ﷻ) acceptance of repentance and forgiveness. The root conveys a deep act of turning back, where a person returns to Allah (ﷻ) after sin, and Allah (ﷻ) responds with mercy. تَابَ thus embodies both repentance and Allah’s (ﷻ) compassionate acceptance, highlighting the mutual nature of repentance and Allah’s (ﷻ) readiness to forgive those who sincerely return to Him.",
  "854": "تَابِعٌ and related words stem from the root ت-ب-ع, with the root verb تَبِعَ meaning \"he followed.\" تَابِعٌ means \"follower\" or \"one who follows,\" describing someone who follows another in belief, action, or guidance. Additionally, تَابِعٌ can refer to the elderly members or servants of a family, highlighting the sense of following within a hierarchy. The broader root meanings of تَبِعَ, including persistence and continuity, suggest that تَابِعٌ conveys the role of one who consistently aligns with another’s path or command, whether in action, belief, or service.",
  "855": "تَارَةٌ and related words stem from the root ت-و-ر, with the root verb تَاوَرَ meaning \"he returned to [him/it], time after time\" or \"it recurred,\" conveying the idea of something happening again or coming back around. تَارَةٌ means \"time\" or \"occasion,\" reflecting the concept of recurrence inherent in the original verb. The connection lies in the cyclical nature of events—just as something returns, so does an occasion or moment in time repeat or reoccur. In the Qur'an, تَارَةً is used to express repeated instances or actions, such as in the phrase \"تَارَةً أُخْرَى\" (another time).",
  "856": "تَارِكٌ and related words stem from the root ت-ر-ك, with the root verb تَرَكَ meaning \"he left\" or \"he abandoned.\" تَارِكٌ means \"one who leaves\" or \"abandoner,\" describing someone who forsakes or relinquishes something, whether material possessions, actions, or beliefs. The root emphasizes a decisive separation or disconnection, highlighting the role of a person who consciously withdraws or distances themselves from an attachment or responsibility, sometimes to make way for new intentions or paths.",
  "857": "التَّالِيَاتُ and related words stem from the root ت-ل-و, with the root verb تَلَا meaning \"he followed\" or \"he recited.\" التَّالِيَاتُ specifically refers to \"those who recite,\" emphasizing deliberate and purposeful articulation or following in sequence. In the Qur'an, this word is interpreted as describing angels, highlighting their role in reciting divine messages, glorifying Allah (ﷻ), and delivering His revelations to prophets. The connection to تَلَا reflects their structured and obedient nature, symbolizing their role as intermediaries in preserving and conveying the purity of divine guidance.",
  "858": "تَأَخَّرَ and related words stem from the root أ-خ-ر, with the root verb أَخَّرَ meaning \"he delayed.\" تَأَخَّرَ means \"he was delayed,\" or \"he lagged behind.\" The connection lies in the subject experiencing delay or being behind others, embodying the root's concept of being late or subsequent. تَأَخَّرَ can refer to physical movement, temporal delay, or falling short in duties. In a moral context, it highlights the importance of striving to keep pace with obligations and not allowing oneself to fall behind in matters of faith and good deeds.",
  "859": "تَأَذَّنَ and related words stem from the root أ-ذ-ن, with the root verb أَذِنَ meaning \"he listened\" or \"he permitted.\" تَأَذَّنَ means \"he declared\" or \"he proclaimed.\" The connection lies in the shift from receiving information to making a formal, authoritative announcement, reflecting the root’s emphasis on communication and permission. Unlike أَذَّنَ, which refers to a general call (such as the adhan), تَأَذَّنَ implies a more official declaration, signaling important developments. This form highlights declarations that command attention and convey authority.",
  "860": "تَأْثِيمٌ and related words stem from the root أ-ث-م, with the root verb أَثِمَ meaning \"he sinned\" or \"committed a misdeed.\" تَأْثِيمٌ means \"causing sin\" or \"leading to sin,\" and can also refer to actions that incur blame or accusation of sin. The root conveys the idea of hindrance and deprivation, emphasizing how sinful actions disrupt harmony and moral integrity. In the Qur'an, تَأْثِيمٌ is used to describe the absence of sinful speech in Paradise, highlighting the purity of interactions in the Hereafter and inspiring believers to strive for purity in their speech and actions in this life.",
  "861": "تَأْجُرَ and related words stem from the root أ-ج-ر, with the root verb أَجَرَ meaning \"he rewarded\" or \"he hired.\" تَأْجُرَ means \"you reward\" or \"you hire,\" emphasizing the act of offering compensation or employing services. The connection lies in the root’s focus on fair recompense, highlighting the ethical responsibility to ensure justice in rewarding or hiring others. This form highlights the importance of fairness and integrity in transactions and relationships.",
  "862": "تَأْسَ and related words stem from the root أ-س-و, with the root verb أَسَا meaning \"he treated a wound,\" \"he remedied,\" or \"he made peace,\" and أَسِيَ meaning \"he grieved\" or \"he mourned.\" تَأْسَ means \"you grieve\" or \"you sorrow.\" The connection lies in the balance between emotional distress and healing. While the root reflects sorrow and mourning, it also emphasizes the possibility of remedy and peace, suggesting that grief, a natural part of life, can be overcome through seeking support, particularly in faith, which offers comfort and solace.",
  "863": "تَأْسِرُونَ and related words stem from the root أ-س-ر, with the root verb أَسَرَ meaning \"he bound,\" \"he braced,\" or \"he tied,\" indicating restraint or securing something firmly. تَأْسِرُونَ means \"you all capture\" or \"you all take prisoner.\" The connection lies in the act of seizing or restraining another, reflecting the root’s focus on captivity and confinement. This verb conveys the sense of physically binding someone, capturing them and restraining their freedom.",
  "864": "تَأْوِيلٌ and related words stem from the root أ-و-ل, with the root verb آلَ meaning \"he returned\" or \"he resorted to,\" and أَوِلَ meaning \"he was first or foremost\" and أَوَّلَ meaning \"he interpreted\" or \"he explained\", especially in uncovering the essence or intended outcome of something. تَأْوِيلٌ means \"interpretation\" or \"explanation,\" particularly of a deeper or ultimate meaning. The root also implies leading to an outcome or bringing back to an origin, highlighting تَأْوِيلٌ as the process of uncovering the true purpose or reality behind words or events, returning them to their intended meaning.",
  "865": "تَؤُزُّ and related words stem from the root أ-ز-ز, with the root verb أَزَّ meaning \"he incited\" or \"he urged,\" involving forceful motion or noise. تَؤُزُّ means \"it incites,\" \"it agitates,\" or \"it urges persistently.\" أَزَّ is used in phrases like \"أَزٌّ القِدْرُ\" to describe a boiling pot’s sound or \"أَزَّ النَّارَ\" meaning to kindle a fire, showing that incitement often intensifies something already agitated. Metaphorically, it represents provoking someone unsettled, as devils incite disbelievers, amplifying inner turmoil. تَؤُزُّ highlights the persistent, relentless nature of such incitement.",
  "866": "تَبَابٌ and related words stem from the root ت-ب-ب, with the root verb تَبَّ meaning \"he, or it, suffered loss, perished, or died.\" تَبَابٌ refers to \"ruin,\" \"loss,\" or \"destruction,\" conveying the idea of something leading to total ruin or a state of irreversible loss. The root encompasses broader meanings such as decay, decline, and downfall, illustrating how the concept of perishing or loss can manifest in various forms of deterioration or collapse.",
  "867": "تَبارٌ and related words stem from the root ت-ب-ر, with the root verb تَبَرَ meaning \"he or it perished.\" تَبارٌ means \"destruction\" and reflects the theme of inevitable ruin or downfall. The word conveys not only the idea of physical destruction but also the notion of moral or existential collapse, highlighting a state beyond recovery or redemption. Through its connection to the root, تَبارٌ suggests a finality to the destruction emphasizing the state of being in complete and final destruction, one that leaves no trace of what was, and highlighting the profound consequence of loss.",
  "868": "تَبارَكَ and related words stem from the root ب-ر-ك, with the root verb بَرَكَ meaning \"he or it was firm, steady, or fixed,\" or \"he or it continued, remained, or stayed.\" بارَكَ means \"he blessed,\" while تَبارَكَ means \"He is exalted\" or \"He is greatly blessed.\" Reflecting the root's sense of continuity and stability, تَبارَكَ emphasizes Allah's (ﷻ) enduring exaltation and His ability to bestow ongoing blessings. In the Qur'an, تَبارَكَ highlights Allah’s (ﷻ) unmatched power and infinite attributes, affirming Him as the eternal source of all blessings and magnifying His supreme status.",
  "869": "تَبَايَعْتُمْ and related words stem from the root ب-ي-ع, with the root verb بَاعَ meaning \"he sold,\" and بَايَعَ meaning \"he exchanged commodities.\" تَبَايَعْتُمْ means \"you mutually sold and bought with each other,\" referring to the reciprocal act of making a deal or agreement, especially in trading or bartering between two or more parties. This term emphasizes mutual participation in a transaction, where both sides actively engage in a fair exchange, each offering something of value to obtain something in return. It reflects the concept of shared commitment and balanced interactions, highlighting the cooperative nature of such agreements.",
  "870": "تَبَتَّلْ and related words stem from the root ب-ت-ل, with the root verb بَتَلَ meaning \"he cut off\" or \"he devoted himself entirely.\" تَبَتَّلْ in this form translates as \"devote yourself exclusively,\" emphasizing a complete focus on worship. The connection lies in cutting off ties with worldly distractions to dedicate oneself solely to Allah (ﷻ), reflecting the root’s concept of separation. This term highlights sincere devotion and spiritual seclusion, encouraging a life centered around faith and renewal of one’s relationship with Allah (ﷻ).",
  "871": "تَبَرَّأَ and related words stem from the root ب-ر-أ, with the root verb بَرَأَ meaning \"he became free from\" or \"he disassociated from,\" and بَرَّأَ meaning \"he acquitted\" or \"he declared free from guilt.\" تَبَرَّأَ means \"he disassociated himself\" or \"he declared himself free from,\" referring to the deliberate act of renouncing association, responsibility, or blame. The connection to the root lies in the emphasis on separation, where تَبَرَّأَ reflects a conscious effort to distance oneself from falsehood or wrongdoing. The root conveys themes of freedom, purity, and disassociation, highlighting the ethical responsibility to maintain integrity by rejecting harmful connections.",
  "872": "تَبَرَّجْنَ and related words stem from the root ب-ر-ج, with the root verb بَرَجَ meaning \"he became prominent\" or \"he became visible.\" تَبَرَّجْنَ translates as \"they openly displayed their beauty or adornment,\" emphasizing an intentional act of making oneself prominent or noticeable. The term carries the broader root ideas of visibility and prominence, often seen in structures like towers, which are built to stand out. In this context, it highlights the deliberate choice to bring what is usually private into open view, shifting from modesty to self-display.",
  "873": "تَبَرُّجٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ر-ج, with the root verb بَرَجَ meaning \"he became prominent\" or \"he became visible.\" تَبَرُّجٌ translates as \"the act of openly displaying beauty or adornment,\" emphasizing a deliberate act of self-display. The root conveys ideas of prominence and visibility, often associated with structures like towers or fortresses, designed to stand out. تَبَرُّجٌ, therefore, highlights a shift from privacy to visibility, where what is typically modest or private is revealed openly, embodying a choice to make oneself noticeable.",
  "874": "تَبَسَّمَ and related words stem from the root ب-س-م, with the root verb بَسَمَ meaning \"he smiled\" or \"he showed his teeth in smiling.\" تَبَسَّمَ is an intensified or reflexive form of the verb, meaning \"he smiled,\" often implying a slight, gentle, or thoughtful smile. This root conveys themes of lightness, clarity, and joy, reflecting a smile born from inner contentment, ease, or reflection. In classical Arabic, تَبَسَّمَ conveys a smile arising from contemplation or satisfaction, hinting at a quiet, heartfelt joy.",
  "875": "تَبَعٌ and related words stem from the root ت-ب-ع, with the root verb تَبِعَ meaning \"he followed.\" تَبَعٌ means \"followers\" or \"those who follow,\" referring to groups who follow a leader or a specific path. This term, connected to the broader root meanings of continuity and organized pursuit, suggests a collective adherence to a shared purpose or leadership, often indicating loyalty or commitment within a group context.",
  "876": "تَبَيَّنَ and related words stem from the root ب-ي-ن, with the root verb بَانَ meaning \"it became separated, severed, disunited, or cut off\" or \"it became apparent, manifest, evident, or clear,\" implying a sense of distinction or separation. بَيَّنَ means \"he made apparent, manifest, or clear,\" while تَبَيَّنَ means \"he realized\" or \"it became clear, apparent, or evident,\" describing the process of reaching clarity, often after doubt or uncertainty. The root conveys separating truth from falsehood or distinguishing one thing from another, highlighting the emergence of clarity as distinctions become evident and confusion lifts, leading to realization and understanding.",
  "877": "تَبِعَ and related words stem from the root ت-ب-ع, which is the root verb form meaning \"he followed.\" It denotes the action of following, pursuing a path, or adhering to guidance. The broad root meanings include not only the physical act of following but also a persistent, intentional pursuit, indicating that تَبِعَ involves choosing to align one’s actions with another’s or with a defined course.",
  "878": "تَبِيدَ and related words stem from the root ب-ي-د, with the root verb بَادَ meaning \"he or it perished\" or \"he or it became cut off or extinct.\" تَبِيدَ means \"that it will perish\" or \"that it ceases to exist,\" emphasizing the potential for complete disappearance or ruin. This root conveys a sense of utter destruction or a final end, where something is wiped out entirely. The term captures the fragility of existence, highlighting how something that seems enduring can vanish or be lost without a trace.",
  "879": "تَبِيعٌ and related words stem from the root ت-ب-ع, with the root verb تَبِعَ meaning \"he followed.\" تَبِيعٌ means \"follower,\" \"pursuer,\" or \"seeker of justice.\" It often refers to someone who follows with a specific intent, such as seeking recompense or accountability, reflecting a determined pursuit. The broader sense of continuity and commitment in تَبِعَ highlights that تَبِيعٌ represents someone who persistently seeks or follows with purpose, especially in contexts of justice or retribution.",
  "880": "تَبَّ and related words stem from the root ت-ب-ب, and as the root verb, it means \"he, or it, suffered loss, perished, or died.\" تَبَّ signifies the act of perishing or coming to ruin, often as a consequence of wrongdoing or rebellion against Allah's (ﷻ) guidance. The root carries broader meanings such as decay, decline, and downfall, which are connected to the notion of suffering loss or demise. These related meanings emphasize the multifaceted nature of perishing, whether through moral failings, natural decay, or societal collapse.",
  "881": "تَبَّرَ and related words stem from the root ت-ب-ر, with the root verb تَبَرَ meaning \"he or it perished,\" conveying the idea of ruin or being reduced to nothing. تَبَّرَ means \"he broke it, crumbled it, or destroyed it completely,\" or \"he did away with it.\" This term emphasizes a deliberate and comprehensive act of destruction, suggesting an active force that causes total obliteration. It extends the root's concept of perishing to an intentional act of dismantling or erasing, highlighting the intensity and all-encompassing nature of destruction that leaves behind nothing but ruin and emptiness.",
  "882": "تَبْتَئِسْ and related words stem from the root ب-أ-س, with the root verb بَئِسَ meaning \"he was mighty or strong in war\" as well as \"he was wretched,\" \"suffered misfortune,\" or \"was distressed.\" تَبْتَئِسْ translates as \"you grieve\" or \"you are distressed,\" referring to a state of sorrow, trouble, or emotional burden. The connection lies in the experience of hardship, reflecting the root’s association with distress and adversity. This term highlights the deep emotional impact of being weighed down by sadness or difficult circumstances.",
  "883": "تَبْتِيلٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ت-ل, with the root verb بَتَلَ meaning \"he cut off\" or \"he devoted himself entirely.\" تَبْتِيلٌ translates as \"complete devotion\" or \"severing,\" referring to cutting off distractions for focused worship. The connection lies in spiritual refinement, where severing ties with worldly attachments fosters a deeper relationship with Allah (ﷻ). This term emphasizes pure worship and detachment from material concerns, aligning with the root’s essence of severance.",
  "884": "تَبْدِيلٌ and related words stem from the root ب-د-ل, with the root verb بَدَلَ meaning \"he exchanged\" or \"he replaced.\" تَبْدِيلٌ translates as \"change\" or \"alteration.\" This term conveys a deliberate process of transformation or substitution, often involving a conscious choice to modify or replace something. The root’s broader concept includes not only a simple exchange but the idea of replacement with something different in quality or state—whether better or worse. Thus, تَبْدِيلٌ can imply a shift that results in improvement, degradation, or simply a significant departure from the original.",
  "885": "تَبْذِيرٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ذ-ر, with the root verb بَذَرَ meaning \"he scattered\" or \"he sowed seeds.\" تَبْذِيرٌ refers to \"wastefulness\" or \"extravagance,\" emphasizing the act of squandering resources indiscriminately, much like scattering seeds without purpose. The root conveys themes of distribution and scattering, which, when done irresponsibly, lead to wastefulness. تَبْذِيرٌ serves as a caution against excess and irresponsibility, reflecting the Qur'anic emphasis on moderation, accountability, and wise stewardship of wealth and blessings.",
  "886": "تَبْصِرَةٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ص-ر, with the root verb بَصُرَ meaning \"he saw\" or \"he was endowed with mental perception, belief, firm belief, knowledge, understanding, intelligence, or skill.\" تَبْصِرَةٌ refers to \"a means of insight or instruction,\" something that guides one toward understanding or awakening. This term suggests a tool or method that brings clarity, enabling someone to perceive truth or gain deep awareness. تَبْصِرَةٌ thus serves as a pathway to inner vision and discernment, often used for teachings or signs that inspire reflection and comprehension.",
  "887": "تَتَجَافَىٰ and related words stem from the root ج-ف-و, with the root verb جَفَا meaning \"it did not keep to its place\" or \"it withdrew.\" تَتَجَافَىٰ means \"it relinquishes,\" emphasizing a deliberate and conscious act of moving away or shunning. The root conveys themes of separation, estrangement, and avoidance, often involving intentional effort to leave something behind. تَتَجَافَىٰ highlights the active process of relinquishing or detaching, reflecting resolve and purposeful action.",
  "888": "تَتَقَلَّبُ and related words stem from the root ق-ل-ب, with the root verb قَلَبَ meaning \"he turned over,\" \"he inverted,\" or \"he changed.\" تَتَقَلَّبُ means \"it turns about,\" \"it fluctuates,\" or \"it changes,\" emphasizing continuous movement or transformation. The root reflects the dynamic nature of change and instability. It can signify the shifting of conditions or the turning of hearts, highlighting the transient and ever-changing nature of human states and experiences.",
  "889": "تَتْبِيبٌ and related words stem from the root ت-ب-ب, with the root verb تَبَّ meaning \"he, or it, suffered loss, perished, or died.\" تَتْبِيبٌ means \"to cause destruction\" or \"to bring about ruin,\" emphasizing the act of causing someone or something to fall into ruin or destruction. The root includes broader meanings such as decay, decline, and downfall, connecting to the act of instigating destruction or loss. These related meanings illustrate the far-reaching effects of actions leading to failure or downfall, showing how تَتْبِيبٌ not only signifies destruction but also the underlying processes of decline.",
  "890": "تَتْبِيرٌ and related words stem from the root ت-ب-ر, with the root verb تَبَرَ meaning \"he or it perished.\" تَتْبِيرٌ means \"destruction\" and highlights the act of bringing about utter ruin. The word encompasses both physical and moral devastation, pointing to the consequences of reckless actions leading to an irreparable end. By drawing from the root's sense of perishing, تَتْبِيرٌ conveys the weight of finality in destruction, where nothing is left intact or untouched by the obliteration. It emphasizes the active process of causing complete and total destruction, focusing on the act that leads to utter devastation.",
  "891": "تَتْرَا and related words stem from the root و-ت-ر, with the root verb وَتَرَ meaning \"he came singly\" or \"he was alone.\" تَتْرَا means \"successively\" or \"one after another.\" The connection lies in the idea of individual units following one after the other in sequence, directly relating to the root's emphasis on singularity. This term captures the notion of successive arrivals or events occurring in order, highlighting continuity and regularity.",
  "892": "تَثْبِيتٌ and related words stem from the root ث-ب-ت, with the root verb ثَبَتَ meaning \"he continued,\" \"endured,\" or \"remained firm.\" تَثْبِيتٌ signifies \"strengthening\" or \"confirmation,\" highlighting the act of reinforcing or establishing firmness. The root meaning implies that through steadfastness and resilience, particularly in challenging situations, one's resolve and faith are solidified and strengthened, highlighting a state of unwavering stability and certainty.",
  "893": "تَثْرِيبٌ and related words stem from the root ث-ر-ب, with the root verb ثَرَبَ meaning \"he blamed, punished, or chastised for an offense or a crime.\" The root also conveys the sense of removal or scraping away, suggesting a deeper nuance of removing faults or cleansing wrongs. تَثْرِيبٌ means \"blame\" or \"reproach,\" but in contexts like the Qur'an, it highlights the act of withholding blame and replacing it with forgiveness. This term highlights the moral virtue of letting go of reproach to cleanse relationships and foster reconciliation.",
  "894": "تَجَسَّسُوا and related words stem from the root ج-س-س, with the root verb جَسَّ meaning \"he felt it with his hand to test and judge it,\" \"he investigated or scrutinized news,\" or \"he spied.\" تَجَسَّسُوا means \"they spied\" or \"they sought out information.\" The root embodies themes of deliberate probing or investigation, often with the intent to uncover hidden matters. This action carries a negative connotation, particularly when it involves prying into private or concealed affairs. تَجَسَّسُوا reflects the root’s focus on uncovering what is hidden, highlighting the moral implications of violating trust or intruding on privacy.",
  "895": "تَجَلَّىٰ and related words stem from the root ج-ل-و, with the root verb جَلَا meaning \"he removed, uncovered, or made clear,\" and \"it became clear or manifest.\" تَجَلَّىٰ means \"he manifested himself\" or \"he revealed himself,\" emphasizing the act of making something hidden or obscured apparent and clear. The root encompasses ideas of uncovering, shining forth, and clarifying, often involving the transition from obscurity or concealment to clarity and brilliance. The connection lies in the unveiling or removal of barriers to bring forth visibility and presence, highlighting profound moments where the unseen becomes evident, reflecting concepts of revelation and brilliance.",
  "896": "تَجُوعَ and related words stem from the root ج-و-ع, with the root verb جَاعَ meaning \"he became hungry.\" تَجُوعَ means \"you become hungry,\" describing a state of need or deprivation. The root conveys themes of insufficiency and reliance, emphasizing human vulnerability and dependence on external sustenance. The connection lies in hunger as a clear reflection of need, tying back to the root’s broader themes of seeking fulfillment and the relief found in provision.",
  "897": "تَحَاضُّونَ and related words stem from the root ح-ض-ض, with the root verb حَضَّ meaning \"he urged,\" \"he incited,\" or \"he encouraged.\" تَحَاضُّونَ means \"you (all) mutually urge\" or \"you (all) collectively encourage,\" emphasizing the reciprocal nature of urging one another toward a shared goal. The root conveys themes of active motivation and driving others to action, which can be tied to either fostering positive outcomes, such as generosity, or addressing neglect and inciting harmful behaviors, depending on the context. This term highlights the significant influence of mutual encouragement and the responsibility to guide it toward constructive purposes.",
  "898": "تَحَرَّىٰ and related words stem from the root ح-ر-ي, with the root verb حَرِىَ meaning \"he was suited for\" or \"he was worthy of something.\" تَحَرَّىٰ means \"he sought earnestly\" or \"he aimed at, pursued, or endeavored to attain.\" The connection lies in intentional striving toward what is most fitting or appropriate. Just as the root conveys worthiness and suitability, this word reflects deliberate effort to reach what is proper, correct, or deserving. It implies careful pursuit, ensuring that one directs their actions toward the best or most rightful outcome.",
  "899": "تَحَسَّسُوا and related words stem from the root ح-س-س, with the root verb حَسَّ meaning \"he was tender or compassionate,\" and أَحَسَّ meaning \"he perceived\" or \"he sensed,\" indicating a deliberate or heightened act of awareness. تَحَسَّسُوا translates as \"seek out\" or \"investigate,\" emphasizing an active effort to perceive or discover. The connection lies in the deliberate pursuit of awareness or understanding, building upon the root's themes of tenderness, sensitivity, and perception. This term reflects a purposeful search for knowledge or information.",
  "900": "تَحَصُّنٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ص-ن, with the root verb حَصُنَ meaning \"it was fortified,\" and حَصَّنَ meaning \"he fortified,\" \"he protected,\" or \"he made inaccessible.\" تَحَصَّنَ means \"he fortified himself\" or \"he sought protection.\" تَحَصُّنٌ means \"fortification,\" \"seeking protection,\" or \"self-defense,\" emphasizing the act of actively securing oneself against threats. This directly connects to the root's essence of building defenses and ensuring safety. The term highlights vigilance and preparedness in safeguarding oneself, whether physically, emotionally, or morally, reflecting the proactive nature of seeking protection.",
  "901": "تَحُسُّونَ and related words stem from the root ح-س-س, with the root verb حَسَّ meaning \"he was tender or compassionate,\" and أَحَسَّ meaning \"he perceived\" or \"he sensed,\" emphasizing deliberate or heightened awareness. تَحُسُّونَ translates as \"you decisively affect\" or \"you destroy,\" often involving direct physical or tangible actions. The connection lies in the transition from sensory awareness to impactful action, reflecting the root’s themes of tenderness, perception, and intensity. This term highlights how heightened awareness or interaction with what is perceived can lead to decisive and significant outcomes, capturing the dynamic link between sensing and taking transformative measures.",
  "902": "تَحِلَّةٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ل-ل, with the root verb حَلَّ meaning \"he untied\" or \"he loosened.\" From this comes أَحَلَّ, meaning \"he made lawful,\" and تَحَلَّلَ, meaning \"he became free from restriction.\" تَحِلَّةٌ means \"an atonement\" or \"expiation,\" particularly in the context of breaking an oath. The connection lies in the act of releasing oneself from the binding force of a vow through proper atonement, akin to untying a knot. This reflects the spiritual practice of seeking forgiveness and restoring balance, emphasizing the merciful provisions within Islamic law for human shortcomings.",
  "903": "تَحِيدُ and related words stem from the root ح-ي-د, with the root verb حَادَ meaning \"he turned aside,\" \"he deviated,\" or \"he avoided.\" تَحِيدُ means \"you turn away\" or \"you deviate.\" The root conveys themes of movement, avoidance, or deliberate deviation, emphasizing the act of turning away or swerving from a path to avoid something. The connection lies in the physical or metaphorical act of shifting direction, often reflecting hesitation, rejection, or a desire to escape.",
  "904": "تَحِيَّةٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ي-ي, with the root verb حَيِيَ meaning \"he was shy\" or \"he felt modesty,\" reflecting restraint and humility. حَيَّا means \"he greeted,\" \"he honored or showed regard,\" or \"he acted with consideration.\" تَحِيَّةٌ translates as \"greeting\" or \"salutation,\" referring to the act of invoking well-being and peace upon others. The connection lies in the essence of honoring and acknowledging others with respect and sincerity. Just as modesty reflects self-restraint and awareness of others, a greeting embodies consideration and goodwill, reinforcing the themes of honor, humility, and refined interaction.",
  "905": "The noun تَحْتَ means \"below,\" \"under,\" or \"beneath.\" This term is used to describe physical locations, metaphorical positions, or relational dynamics, emphasizing humility or foundational support. Rooted in the broader concept of positioning, تَحْتَ implies a relationship of dependency or underlying support, often indicating something that provides strength, shelter, or basis from beneath. This positioning can also convey submission, protection, or a hidden yet vital role, particularly in contexts of humility or foundational support in relationships and structures.",
  "906": "تَحْرُثُ and related words stem from the root ح-ر-ث, with the root verb حَرَثَ meaning \"he plowed,\" \"he tilled the soil,\" or \"he sought to gain sustenance.\" تَحْرُثُ means \"you plow\" or \"you cultivate.\" The connection lies in the act of working the land to prepare it for sowing, reflecting effort and preparation for growth. Just as cultivation requires labor to yield crops, seeking sustenance demands effort and diligence. This word emphasizes the active role in nurturing potential, whether in agriculture or in striving for livelihood.",
  "907": "تَحْرِيرٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ر-ر, with the root verb حَرَّ meaning \"it became hot\" or \"he was free.\" حَرَّرَ means \"he freed or liberated,\" and تَحْرِيرٌ means \"emancipation\" or \"liberation.\" The connection lies in the idea of release and transformation—just as heat changes the state of a substance, freedom marks a transition from restriction to autonomy. The root conveys intensity and refinement, as freeing someone removes constraints, allowing them to exist independently. Similarly, تَحْرِيرٌ implies deliberate effort, emphasizing the process of granting or attaining freedom through decisive action.",
  "908": "تَحْلِقُوا and related words stem from the root ح-ل-ق, with the root verb حَلَقَ meaning \"he shaved\" and حَلَّقَ meaning \"he or it encircled.\" تَحْلِقُوا means \"you all shave.\" The root conveys meanings of circularity, enclosing, and cutting. In its Qur'anic usage, the act of shaving during pilgrimage reflects the root’s emphasis on removal (as in shaving) and circular motion (as in encircling the Kaaba). This term highlights themes of purification and renewal through shaving while also symbolizing unity and devotion through the broader concept of encircling in pilgrimage.",
  "909": "تَحْنَثْ and related words stem from the root ح-ن-ث, with the root verb حَنِثَ meaning \"he broke an oath\" or \"he committed a sin.\" تَحْنَثْ means \"you break an oath\" or, in command form, \"do not break your oath.\" The root reflects themes of deviation from truth or moral obligation, encompassing both the physical act of breaking an oath and the broader concept of sinfulness. This term highlights the gravity of violating a solemn promise, which disrupts trust and integrity, carrying both moral and spiritual consequences.",
  "910": "تَحْوِيلٌ and related words stem from the root ح-و-ل, with the root verb حَالَ meaning \"he or it changed or transformed,\" \"he or it moved or shifted,\" or \"he or it intervened or came between.\" حَوَلَ means \"he changed or altered something,\" or \"he turned or diverted something.\" تَحْوِيلٌ means \"change,\" \"transformation,\" or \"alteration.\" The root revolves around movement and transition, emphasizing a shift from one state to another. This term reflects both physical and abstract changes, whether altering direction, modifying circumstances, or intervening in a situation, capturing the essence of continuous transformation.",
  "911": "تَخاصُمٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ص-م, with the root verb خَصَمَ meaning \"he disputed in a valid or sound manner.\" تَخَاصَمَ means \"they disputed with one another,\" and تَخاصُمٌ means \"mutual disputation\" or \"argumentation.\" The root conveys contention, opposition, and legal disputation, often involving sharpness in argument. The connection emphasizes the reciprocal nature of disputes, where each party contends against the other. It reflects the complexities of human interactions, the persistence of conflict, and the challenges of resolving disagreements when both sides assert their claims.",
  "912": "تَخَلَّتْ and related words stem from the root خ-ل-و, with the root verb خَلا meaning \"he was alone\" or \"it became empty.\" The root conveys emptiness, solitude, separation, absence, relief, and the passage of time. خَلَّى means \"he released (something) from burden or obligation\" or \"he withdrew from or made (something) empty or vacant,\" while تَخَلَّى means \"he made himself empty or void (of something).\" تَخَلَّتْ means \"it made itself empty\" or \"it became free or relieved (of something),\" emphasizing a state of release or removal. This highlights the process of letting go, becoming unburdened, or transitioning into a state of emptiness or freedom.",
  "913": "تَخَوُّفٌ and related words stem from the root خ-و-ف, with the root verb خَافَ meaning \"he feared.\" خَوَّفَ means \"he instilled fear,\" while تَخَوَّفَ means \"he feared\" with added apprehension and prolonged anxiety, or \"he removed or diminished something gradually.\" تَخَوُّفٌ means \"gradual diminishment\" or \"apprehension,\" referring to the slow loss or reduction of something alongside lingering fear. The root revolves around fear, apprehension, and caution, encompassing both internal anxiety and external cautious action in response to danger. This highlights the dual nature of تَخَوُّفٌ, where fear is both an emotional state and a reaction to gradual loss or uncertainty.",
  "914": "تَخُطُّ and related words stem from the root خ-ط-ط, with the root verb خَطَّ meaning \"he drew a line,\" \"he made a mark,\" or \"he wrote.\" تَخُطُّ means \"you write\" or \"you draw.\" The root conveys concepts of marking, writing, and formulating plans, encompassing actions of drawing lines, inscribing text, and mapping out ideas. The connection lies in the physical act of making marks, emphasizing writing as a deliberate and structured process. In the Qur'an, it highlights that the Prophet Muhammad (ﷺ) was unlettered and did not write, affirming the divine origin of the revelation.",
  "915": "تَخْسِيرٌ and related words stem from the root خ-س-ر, with the root verb خَسِرَ meaning \"he lost.\" تَخْسِيرٌ means \"causing loss\" or \"inducing failure.\" The root conveys themes of loss, ruin, and error, encompassing deprivation, deception, and misguidance. This word emphasizes the act of leading others to loss, whether by deception, negligence, or harm. It reflects the ethical weight of causing disadvantage, highlighting the responsibility and consequences of actions that result in deprivation or failure.",
  "916": "تَخْضَعْنَ and related words stem from the root خ-ض-ع, with the root verb خَضَعَ meaning \"he was submissive,\" \"he lowered his head or neck in humility or submission,\" or \"he bent himself.\" تَخْضَعْنَ means \"you (women) submit\" or \"you (women) speak humbly,\" referring to a state of humility, particularly in tone or speech. The root conveys humility, submissiveness, and yielding, describing both physical lowering and metaphorical obedience. In the Qur'anic context, it highlights the need for balance in speech, cautioning against overly soft tones that could lead to misinterpretation or exploitation. This reflects the root's emphasis on humility while maintaining integrity and caution.",
  "917": "تَخْفِيفٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ف-ف, with the root verb خَفَّ meaning \"he or it was light,\" referring to weight, movement, or manner. خَفَّفَ means \"he lightened\" or \"he alleviated.\" تَخْفِيفٌ means \"lightening,\" \"alleviation,\" or \"easing.\" The root conveys concepts of lightness and reduction in weight or intensity. The connection lies in making something less heavy or burdensome, whether physically or figuratively. This reflects the idea of removing hardship, bringing ease, and extending mercy by reducing difficulty.",
  "918": "تَخْوِيفٌ and related words stem from the root خ-و-ف, with the root verb خَافَ meaning \"he feared.\" تَخْوِيفٌ means \"intimidation\" or \"causing fear,\" referring to the act of instilling fear in others. The root revolves around fear, apprehension, and caution, encompassing both internal anxiety and external reactions to perceived danger. تَخْوِيفٌ highlights the deliberate creation of fear, whether as a warning or as a means of control, reinforcing the connection between fear and its influence on thought and action.",
  "919": "تَدَايَنْتُمْ and related words stem from the root د-ي-ن, with the root verb دَانَ meaning \"he obeyed\" or \"he borrowed.\" دَايَنَ means \"he lent on credit,\" and تَدَايَنَ means \"they lent and borrowed from each other.\" تَدَايَنْتُمْ means \"you engage in mutual debt\" or \"you lend one another.\" The root revolves around obedience, judgment, and indebtedness, encompassing faith, legal rulings, and financial obligations. Debt creates a binding relationship, just as obedience implies duty, reflecting how financial, moral, and religious responsibilities structure accountability and obligation.",
  "920": "تَدَلَّى and related words stem from the root د-ل-و, with the root verb دَلَا meaning \"he lowered, let down, or extended\" or \"he drew out, pulled up, or retrieved.\" تَدَلَّى means \"he lowered himself\" or \"he descended,\" emphasizing a gradual and controlled descent. The root revolves around lowering, extending, drawing up, and leading, conveying a deliberate movement from above to below. Just as something lowered moves downward with precision and intent, this word reflects a purposeful and measured descent, highlighting an action carried out with care and control.",
  "921": "تَدُورُ and related words stem from the root د-و-ر, with the root verb دَارَ meaning \"he or it turned, revolved, or rotated.\" تَدُورُ means \"it revolves\" or \"it turns,\" emphasizing continuous or cyclic motion. The root highlights themes of movement, repetition, and circular progression. Just as turning follows a repeated pattern, this word reflects ongoing motion, whether in physical rotation or the recurrence of events.",
  "922": "تَدَّخِرُونَ and related words stem from the root ذ-خ-ر, with the root verb ذَخَرَ meaning \"he stored up\" or \"he saved.\" تَدَّخِرُونَ means \"you store up,\" reflecting the action of saving, preserving, or hoarding resources for future use. The root conveys themes of accumulation, preparation, and anticipation.",
  "923": "تَدْرِي and related words stem from the root د-ر-ي, with the root verb دَرَىٰ meaning \"he knew or was aware\" or \"he perceived or understood.\" تَدْرِي means \"you know\" or \"you are aware,\" emphasizing personal understanding or insight. The root highlights the importance of direct awareness and recognition, linking knowledge to an individual’s ability to comprehend and engage with the world.",
  "924": "تَدْمِيرٌ and related words stem from the root د-م-ر, with the root verb دَمَرَ meaning \"it perished\" or \"he intruded without permission.\" تَدْمِيرٌ means \"destruction,\" reflecting the deliberate act of causing ruin. The root verb’s sense of perishing connects to the inevitable loss caused by destruction, while the idea of intrusion emphasizes how this ruin comes uninvited and unstoppable. Broader themes of erasure and obliteration highlight the totality of loss, serving as a reminder of the consequences of corruption and the accountability for straying from Allah’s (ﷻ) guidance.",
  "925": "تَذَكَّرَ and related words stem from the root ذ-ك-ر, with the root verb ذَكَرَ meaning \"he remembered\" or \"he mentioned.\" تَذَكَّرَ means \"he remembered\" or \"he reflected,\" or \"to be reminded,\" indicating an internal process of recalling or pondering. The connection lies in deep contemplation and reflection, reflecting the root's emphasis on memory and mention. It encourages thoughtful consideration of life's signs and lessons, leading to greater understanding and spiritual growth.",
  "926": "تَذُودَ and related words stem from the root ذ-و-د, with the root verb ذَادَ meaning \"he repelled,\" \"he defended,\" or \"he drove away.\" تَذُودَ means \"she repels,\" \"she defends,\" or \"she drives away.\" The connection lies in the act of warding off or protecting against something, reflecting the root's emphasis on defense and safeguarding. This term underscores the proactive effort to protect oneself or others, highlighting the importance of vigilance and courage in the face of challenges.",
  "927": "تَذْرُو and related words stem from the root ذ-ر-و, with the root verb ذَرَا meaning \"he scattered\" or \"he winnowed.\" تَذْرُو means \"it scatters\" or \"it blows away,\" often referring to the wind dispersing dust or chaff. The connection emphasizes the act of dispersal by natural forces, reflecting the root's focus on scattering and separation. It serves as a metaphor for the transient nature of worldly things, which can be scattered and lost by forces beyond human control.",
  "928": "تَذْكِرَةٌ and related words stem from the root ذ-ك-ر, with the root verb ذَكَرَ meaning \"he remembered\" or \"he mentioned.\" تَذْكِرَةٌ means \"reminder\" or \"admonition,\" serving as a means to prompt recollection or awareness. The connection emphasizes the role of reminders in maintaining mindfulness and adherence to guidance, reflecting the root's focus on memory and mention. It highlights the importance of reminders in spiritual practice to keep one's heart and mind aligned with what pleases Allah (ﷻ).",
  "929": "تَذْكِيرٌ and related words stem from the root ذ-ك-ر, with the root verb ذَكَرَ meaning \"he remembered\" or \"he mentioned.\" تَذْكِيرٌ means \"reminding\" or \"admonition,\" referring to the act of prompting someone to remember or reflect. The connection lies in actively bringing something to someone's attention, reflecting the root's emphasis on memory and mention. It highlights the role of reminders in teaching and guiding others towards truth and righteousness.",
  "930": "تَذْلِيلٌ and related words stem from the root ذ-ل-ل, with the root verb ذَلَّ meaning \"he was lowly, humbled, or became submissive.\" تَذْلِيلٌ means \"subjugation,\" \"humiliation,\" or \"making easy.\" The connection lies in the act of bringing something into a state of ease or submission, reflecting the root's emphasis on humility and tractability.",
  "931": "تَذْهَلُ and related words stem from the root ذ-ه-ل, with the root verb ذَهِلَ meaning \"he was heedless,\" \"he forgot,\" or \"he was distracted.\" تَذْهَلُ means \"she becomes heedless,\" \"she forgets,\" or \"she is distracted.\" The connection lies in the state of being overwhelmed or inattentive, reflecting the root's emphasis on forgetfulness or distraction. This term highlights moments when intense situations cause one to lose focus or awareness, serving as a caution against negligence and the importance of mindfulness.",
  "932": "تَراءَتِ and related words stem from the root ر-أ-ي, with the root verb رَأَىٰ meaning \"he saw\" or \"he perceived.\" تَراءَتِ means \"they appeared to each other\" or \"they confronted each other,\" describing mutual visibility, recognition, or encounter. The root extends to themes of sight, perception, and reflection, encompassing both physical seeing and the unveiling of hidden realities. This term emphasizes situations of confrontation, recognition, or revelation, where opposing parties come face to face, highlighting themes of clarity, mutual awareness, and the uncovering of truths or realities through direct perception.",
  "933": "تَرَائِبُ and related words stem from the root ت-ر-ب, with the root verb تَرِبَ meaning \"he became dusty,\" symbolizing human origin, mortality, and vulnerability. تَرَائِبُ (plural of تَرِيبَةٌ) refers to the ribs and upper chest area, located between the backbone and the front of the body. The root’s connection to dust emphasizes the fragile nature of human life, while تَرَائِبُ highlights the chest as a protective enclosure for vital organs. Remarkably, reproductive organs develop in the fetal stage between the backbone and ribs, within this protected area, with their blood supply originating there. This reflects human origin, fragility, protection, and Allah's miraculous design.",
  "934": "تَرَاضٍ and related words stem from the root ر-ض-و, with the root verb رَضِيَ meaning \"he was pleased\" or \"he was content.\" تَرَاضٍ means \"mutual consent\" or \"mutual satisfaction.\" The connection lies in the reciprocal nature of contentment between parties, embodying the root's emphasis on pleasure and acceptance. This term highlights the importance of mutual agreement and shared satisfaction in interactions, reflecting harmonious relationships based on consent and contentment.",
  "935": "تَرَاضَوْا and related words stem from the root ر-ض-و, with the root verb رَضِيَ meaning \"he was pleased\" or \"he was content.\" تَرَاضَوْا means \"they mutually agreed\" or \"they came to a mutual understanding.\" The connection lies in the action of reaching an agreement that satisfies all parties involved, embodying the root's emphasis on contentment and pleasure. This term reflects the process of negotiation leading to a harmonious conclusion where all are pleased.",
  "936": "تَرَاقِي and related words stem from the root ت-ر-ق, with the root verb تَرَقَّى meaning \"he ascended\" or \"he progressed.\" تَرَاقِي (plural of تَرْقُوَةٌ) means \"collarbones\" or \"upper chest.\" This term is used in the Qur'an in the context of the soul ascending and reaching the collarbones at the moment of death, highlighting the soul's journey upward as life leaves the body. The connection between the root meaning of ascension and the word تَرَاقِي illustrates the soul’s final ascent in this life as it reaches the collarbones during the departure from the physical body.",
  "937": "تَرَبَّصْ and related words stem from the root ر-ب-ص, with the root verb رَبَصَ meaning \"to lie in wait\" or \"to watch.\" تَرَبَّصْ means \"wait\" or \"be on the lookout.\" The connection lies in the act of anticipating or being vigilant, reflecting the root's emphasis on waiting. This term can carry both positive and negative connotations, either as patience and readiness or as lurking with ill intent, highlighting the importance of intention in one's actions.",
  "938": "تَرَبُّصٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ب-ص, with the root verb رَبَصَ meaning \"to lie in wait\" or \"to watch.\" تَرَبُّصٌ means \"waiting,\" \"expectation,\" or \"ambush.\" The term encapsulates the concept of anticipation or watchfulness, directly reflecting the root's emphasis on waiting. It can signify a period of patience or a strategic pause, emphasizing the importance of timing and preparation in achieving objectives.",
  "939": "تَرْدَى and related words stem from the root ر-د-ي, with the root verb رَدِيَ meaning \"he perished\" or \"he fell into ruin.\" تَرْدَى means \"he perishes\" or \"he falls into ruin.\" The connection highlights the act of falling or perishing, embodying the root's essence of decline. It underscores the vulnerability of humans to downfall and the need for guidance to avoid ruin.",
  "940": "تَرَكَ and related words stem from the root ت-ر-ك, and as the root verb, it means \"he left\" or \"he abandoned.\" تَرَكَ signifies the act of leaving behind or forsaking something. This act of leaving implies a deliberate choice, often involving detachment or disassociation from something once held. The root reflects a transition where separation is intentional, suggesting either a purposeful departure from distractions or a neglect of responsibilities.",
  "941": "تَرْتِيلٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ت-ل, with the root verb رَتَلَ meaning \"he arranged\" or \"he recited distinctly.\" تَرْتِيلٌ means \"measured recitation,\" particularly of the Qur'an. The connection lies in the careful arrangement and clear articulation of words, reflecting the root's emphasis on order and precision. This term underscores the importance of thoughtful and deliberate expression to enhance understanding and contemplation of the divine message.",
  "942": "تَرْجُفُ and related words stem from the root ر-ج-ف, with the root verb رَجَفَ meaning \"it shook\" or \"it trembled.\" تَرْجُفُ means \"it trembles\" or \"it quakes.\" The connection lies in the action of shaking, directly reflecting the root's emphasis on movement and instability. This term often describes natural phenomena like earthquakes or metaphorical states of fear, highlighting the power of such forces to impact the physical and emotional realms.",
  "943": "تَرْدَى and related words stem from the root ر-د-ي, with the root verb رَدِيَ meaning \"he perished\" or \"he fell into ruin.\" تَرْدَى means \"he perishes\" or \"he falls into ruin.\" The connection highlights the act of falling or perishing, embodying the root's essence of decline. It underscores the vulnerability of humans to downfall and the need for guidance to avoid ruin.",
  "944": "تَرْقَىٰ and related words stem from the root ر-ق-ي, with the root verb رَقِيَ meaning \"he ascended\" or \"he climbed.\" تَرْقَىٰ means \"you ascend\" or \"you rise,\" addressing someone directly. The connection lies in the action of moving upward or progressing, directly relating to the root's meaning. This ascent can be physical or metaphorical, symbolizing spiritual elevation or advancement toward higher understanding.",
  "945": "تَرْكَنُ and related words stem from the root ر-ك-ن, with the root verb رَكَنَ meaning \"he inclined\" or \"he leaned.\" تَرْكَنُ means \"you incline\" or \"you lean,\" addressing someone directly. The connection lies in the act of leaning toward something, whether physically or metaphorically, directly relating to the root's meaning. In the Qur'an, it warns against inclining toward wrongdoers, emphasizing the importance of steadfastness.",
  "946": "تَزَاوَرُ and related words stem from the root ز-و-ر, with the root verb زَارَ meaning \"he deviated,\" \"he inclined,\" or \"he turned aside.\" تَزَاوَرُ means \"it inclines away\" or \"it turns aside.\" The connection lies in the sun's movement as it subtly shifts its position, embodying the root's concept of deviation and inclination. In the Qur'anic narrative of the sleepers in the cave, this term illustrates how the sun inclines away from them, protecting them from its rays. This showcases Allah’s (ﷻ) meticulous care in orchestrating natural phenomena for the benefit of His servants.",
  "947": "تَزَكَّى and related words stem from the root ز-ك-و, with the root verb زَكَا meaning \"he was pure\" or \"he grew.\" تَزَكَّى means \"he purified himself\" or \"he sought to become pure.\" The root encompasses ideas of improvement, cleansing, and achieving a higher state of goodness. The connection lies in the deliberate effort to cleanse oneself morally or spiritually, embodying the root's concepts of purity and growth. It emphasizes self-improvement and the pursuit of righteousness through conscious and intentional endeavor.",
  "948": "تَزَوَّدُوا and related words stem from the root ز-و-د, with the root verb زَادَ meaning \"he increased\" or \"he provided.\" تَزَوَّدُوا means \"they took provisions\" or \"they prepared supplies.\" The connection lies in equipping oneself with necessary supplies for a journey, reflecting the root's emphasis on provision and increase. It symbolizes preparing for future needs, including spiritual preparedness for the Hereafter.",
  "949": "تَزَيَّلُوا and related words stem from the root ز-ي-ل, with the root verb زَالَ meaning \"he separated\" or \"he parted.\" تَزَيَّلُوا means \"they separated themselves\" or \"they distinguished themselves.\" The connection lies in the act of differentiating or setting apart, embodying the root's concept of separation. تَزَيَّلُوا highlights the importance of distinguishing between truth and falsehood, and between the righteous and the wrongdoers.",
  "950": "تَزْدَرِي and related words stem from the root ز-ر-ي, with the root verb زَرَى meaning \"he blamed\" or \"he censured.\" تَزْدَرِي means \"you despise\" or \"she scorns.\" The connection lies in the act of looking down upon or belittling someone or something, reflecting the root's emphasis on censure and expressing contempt. It highlights a disdainful attitude that can lead to injustice or disregard for others.",
  "951": "تَزْرَعُ and related words stem from the root ز-ر-ع, with the root verb زَرَعَ meaning \"he sowed\" or \"he planted.\" تَزْرَعُ means \"you sow\" or \"you plant,\" directly addressing an individual. The connection lies in the act of planting seeds to cultivate growth, embodying the root's fundamental concept of agriculture and nurturing life. It highlights human effort in initiating growth while acknowledging that fruition ultimately comes from divine will.",
  "952": "تَسَوَّرُوا and related words stem from the root س-و-ر, with the root verb سَوَّرَ meaning \"he built a wall\" or \"he enclosed.\" تَسَوَّرُوا means \"they scaled a wall\" or \"they climbed over a barrier,\" emphasizing the act of surmounting enclosures. The connection lies in the root's focus on walls or enclosures—while the root involves constructing boundaries, this form reflects overcoming them. This term highlights determination, ingenuity, and the act of penetrating barriers, illustrating themes of persistence in surmounting obstacles.",
  "953": "تَسُرُّ and related words stem from the root س-ر-ر, with the root verb سَرَّ meaning \"he rejoiced,\" \"he was happy,\" or \"he delighted.\" تَسُرُّ means \"it pleases,\" \"it delights,\" or \"it brings joy.\" The connection lies in the act of causing happiness or joy, reflecting the root's emphasis on delight and pleasure. It conveys the idea of something that brings satisfaction and gladness to the heart.",
  "954": "تَسْبِيحٌ and related words stem from the root س-ب-ح, with the root verb سَبَّحَ meaning \"he glorified\" or \"he praised.\" تَسْبِيحٌ means \"glorification\" or \"praise.\" The connection lies in the act of exalting or honoring, embodying the root's concept of moving swiftly or swimming, symbolizing continuous and effortless praise. تَسْبِيحٌ reflects the practice of constantly remembering and glorifying Allah (ﷻ).",
  "955": "تَسْتَأْنِسُوا and related words stem from the root أ-ن-س, with the root verb أَنَسَ meaning \"he was sociable,\" \"he found comfort,\" or \"he became familiar.\" تَسْتَأْنِسُوا translates to \"you all seek familiarity,\" \"you all perceive,\" or \"you all find comfort.\" The connection lies in seeking familiarity and comfort, reflecting the root’s focus on companionship and perception. In the Qur'an, it refers to making oneself known before entering someone else's space. Even in close companionship, this term emphasizes that familiarity should coexist with courtesy and respect for personal boundaries.",
  "956": "تَسْتَبِينَ and related words stem from the root ب-ي-ن, with the root verb بَانَ meaning \"it became separated, severed, disunited, or cut off,\" or \"it became apparent, manifest, evident, or clear\" or \"it became distinct,\" implying separation from others. تَسْتَبِينَ means \"it becomes clear,\" emphasizing the ongoing process of pursuing or achieving clarity. The root conveys the idea of distinguishing or separating truth from obscurity, reflecting an active search for understanding where clarity is gradually revealed.",
  "957": "تَسْتَتِرُونَ and related words stem from the root س-ت-ر, with the root verb سَتَرَ meaning \"he concealed,\" \"he covered,\" or \"he veiled.\" The concept revolves around the act of covering, shielding, or hiding something from view. تَسْتَتِرُونَ specifically translates to \"you conceal yourselves\" or \"you hide yourselves,\" emphasizing an active and reflexive effort to seek concealment.",
  "958": "تَسْتَرْضِعُ and related words stem from the root ر-ض-ع, with the root verb رَضَعَ meaning \"he suckled\" or \"he nursed.\" تَسْتَرْضِعُ means \"she seeks to have someone breastfeed (her child)\" or \"she seeks a wet nurse.\" The connection lies in the act of seeking nourishment for a child through another, embodying the root's emphasis on nursing and sustenance. This term reflects the concern for a child's well-being, extending the root's concept of nurturing to include the procurement of a caregiver who provides essential nourishment."
};
